<DOCNO> AP890811-0002 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2329EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthKorea     08-11 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Korea,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Claims Opposition Leader Received $10,000 from Communist Spy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Saturday that
opposition leader Kim Dae-jung received $10,000 from a lawmaker
accused of being a spy for communist North Korea.
   They made the announcement at the formal indictment of Rep. Suh
Kyung-won, 52, and his aide, Bang Yang-kyun, 34. If convicted of
spying, Suh and Bang could be sentenced to life in prison.
   The prosecution claims that Suh, a member of Kim Dae-jung's
Party for Peace and Democracy, secretly visited North Korea in
August 1988 and received $50,000 from communist leaders.
   There was no immediate comment from Kim Dae-jung. Kim Won-kee, a
senior member of the opposition party, called the allegations
``complete fabrications.''
   The prosecution's claim that Kim Dae-Jung received money from
Suh followed allegations linking the leader of the largest
opposition party to the spy case. Kim Dae-jung has denied the
allegations.
   An earlier prosecution statement said that Suh was recruited by
North Korean agents operating in West Germany in 1985 and they gave
him $70,000 over a three-year period. It said Suh informed North
Korea about the political situation and dissident movements in
South Korea.
   The prosecution said Suh has confessed. It said Suh claimed Kim
Dae-jung gave him $1,000 a few days before he made the trip to
North Korea and when Suh returned he gave Kim Dae-jung $10,000.
   Prosecution officials said they would subphoena Kim Dae-jung to
determine if he had received $10,000 and knew it was from the North
Koreans.
   The prosecution claims that both Kim Dae-jung and Kim Won-kee
knew in April 1988 about Suh's planned trip to North Korea.
   Under South Korea's security laws, it is a crime not to inform
authorities about planned contacts with North Korea.
   Kim Dae-jung, who ran for president in 1971 and 1987, was
questioned by government intelligence officials last week about
possible involvement in the spy case.
   After the interrogation, Kim Dae-jung said he had been cleared
of all allegations but the Agency for National Security Planning
(NSP) said the investigation would continue. Officials said the NSP
was trying to determine if Kim Dae-jung had sent a message to North
Korean leaders through Suh.
   Six people have been indicted in the spy case but they have not
been arrested. They were charged with failing to report Suh's
activities to authorities.
</TEXT>
