<FIRST>u i AM-Guatemala 1stLd-writethru a0746 08-11 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala, 1st Ld-writethru, a0746,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenade Attack in Guatemala Kills One, Wounds Eight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs, 300 teachers cross into Mexico and ask for asylum.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorists hurled grenades in three
separate attacks around Guatemala City, killing one bus passenger
and injuring eight, authorities reported.
   Police said they had not determined who carried out the attacks
and no individual or group claimed responsibility.
   They said a grenade was thrown at a bus in the suburb of El
Limon and a woman was killed. Rescue workers said eight other
passengers were taken to a hospital.
   The other grenade explosions caused damages but no casualties.
One grenade was thrown at a church where a Roman Catholic priest
was saying Mass and another exploded at at the building housing the
Guatemala office of the Organization of American States.
   There has been a surge of violence in Guatemala during the
10-week-old strike by about 35,000 of the nation's 40,000 teachers,
who are demanding more pay.
   President Vinicio Cerezo has said the government cannot afford
to meet the demands. The Education Ministry said if a settlement is
not reached by Monday it will fire the striking teachers.
   Among the victims of the violence was a prominent member of the
Christian Democrat Party and friend of the president, who was
assassinated.
   Some of the violence has been blamed on right-wing militants,
who claim Cerezo is too liberal.
   Cerezo's inauguration in 1986 ended more than three decades of
military rule, and he has survived two coup attempts.
   In recent weeks, teachers have taken over buildings in Guatemala
City and border crossing stations to protest the government's
firing of 527 teachers for participating in the strike.
   The strikers are seeking a monthly increase of $80. Their
salaries now range from $136 to $328 per month.
   About 300 teachers crossed into southern Mexico and applied for
political asylum, claiming they had been harasssed by the Cerezo
government, two regional strike leaders said Friday.
   Strike leaders Victor Sosa Lopez and Amilca Escobar said the
teachers crossed into Chiapas state.
   Striking teachers have been blocking the international bridge on
the Guatemalan side of the border with Mexico since Thursday
afternoon, causing a traffic snarl on both sides.
   Reporters in the Mexican border town of Ciudad Hidalgo said they
saw about 50 armed Guatemalan soldiers along with a number of
police deployed near the strikers but they took no action.
</TEXT>
