<SECOND>PM-BRF--Malaysia-Planes,0110</SECOND>
<HEAD>Malaysia Plans to Sell 48 Jet Fighters Stored in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Tengku Ahmad
Rithauddeen told reporters today that Malaysia plans to sell 48
Skyhawk jet fighters now in storage at an air base in Tucson, Ariz.
   Malaysia bought Skyhawks that had been mothballed by the U.S.
armed forces about 10 years ago, refurbished about 35 of them and
now is using them here.
   It stored 48 of them at the base for future use, but now has
decided to buy Tornado fighter planes from Britain.
   Among the countries now using Skyhawks are New Zealand,
Indonesia, Israel and Singapore.
