<FIRST>r a PM-CDCBriefs     08-11 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CDC Briefs,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Here are Briefs from Centers for Disease Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the patients in a recent hepatitis
outbreak in a rural Illinois county either admitted intravenous
drug use or are suspected of it, according to federal health
authorities.
   Seventeen cases of non-A, non-B hepatitis were reported between
Nov. 15 and June 30 in Wabash County, Ill., a rural area which had
reported only one other such case since 1982.
   The national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday that
interviews and medical records showed seven of the 17 patients
admitted abusing intravenous drugs, and five ``were suspected IV
drug users.''
   The outbreak apparently began with an IV-drug user who returned
to the area and began sharing drug needles with other users before
becoming ill, the CDC said.
   Non-A, non-B hepatitis, transmitted via injections such as drug
needles or transfusions, accounts for between 20 percent and 40
percent of the viral hepatitis in this country, the CDC said.
Studies have shown that as many as 42 percent of such cases are
associated with drug use, the Atlanta-based agency said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nations of Central and South America have
made significant progress in their polio-eradication efforts in
recent years, U.S. health officials said.
   In the Americas, a record low 335 confirmed polio cases were
reported last year, down 64 percent from 930 confirmed cases in
1986, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control said Thursday. The
progress follows a 1985 Pan American Health Organization initiative
to eradicate indigenous transmission of wild polio virus by the end
of 1990.
   With special efforts toward the remaining pockets of polio, the
1990 goal ``probably can be achieved,'' the CDC said. But at this
point, transmission may continue in several countries, including
Brazil, which reported 106 cases in 1988, and Peru, which reported
58, the CDC said.
   Polio, a paralyzing, viral disease, has been essentially
eliminated in the United States, although the CDC said reports of
some cases, related directly to polio vaccine, are pending. Canada
reported just one confirmed case in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
