<HEAD>Foreigner Sentenced to 15 Years for Holding Onto Dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court convicted a foreign
national of illegally possessing $3,200 and trying to bribe a
police officer, and sentenced him to 15 years in jail, news reports
said.
   Al-Guwat al-Musalaha, the armed forces daily, did not specify
the foreigner's name or nationality in the report Thursday. It also
did not say when the trial was held.
   Shortly after a June 31 military coup overthrew the government
of Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi, new junta leader Lt. Gen. Omar
el-Bashir said his priorities included reforming the economy and
fighting corruption.
   Among other tough measures, the junta ordered people to exchange
all foreign money by July 31 or face trial by a military court, and
threatened the death penalty for hard-currency dealers.
