<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Norway-Shock     08-11 0164</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Norway-Shock,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Survives 22,000-Volt Shock, Rescued for Second Time by Same Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy survived a 22,000-volt
electrical shock with help from the same man who saved him from
drowning eight years ago, according to news reports.
   Isak Turi climbed a 22-foot-high electricity pylon in the
northern village of Oteren Monday and touched the power line. The
shock jolted him to the ground with his hair and clothes on fire,
the Oslo newspaper Verdens Gang reported Thursday.
   Paul Bakke, a neighbor, ran to smother the flames, the newspaper
said.
   A spokesman for the regional power company was quoted as saying
it was amazing that Turi, the son of a reindeer herder, survived.
   Bakke told Verdens Gang that eight years ago he saved Turi when
the boy nearly drowned in a spring flood.
   ``Isak has always been a tough kid who will dare anything,''
Bakke said.
   Turi was in stable condition at a local hospital, the newspaper
said.
</TEXT>
