<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Nicaragua-Conservatives     08-11 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Conservatives,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Contra Demobilization Plan Leaves Right Crotchety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To most people, former President Reagan went a
bit far a few years ago when he called the Nicaraguan Contras the
``moral equivalent of the founding fathers.''
   If the Contras don't rank with the likes of Thomas Jefferson in
the eyes of the majority, they have been one of those causes that
has kept conservative brows in a fevered state for years.
   And when Central American presidents set a Dec. 5 deadline
Monday for the demobilization of the Contras, conservative wrath
was once again energized.
   On no issue since the Vietnam war have conservatives and
liberals squared off as they have over the Contras. Democrats saw
Reagan as contributing to massive death and destruction in a
country that could never pose a security threat to the United
States.
   Conservatives saw Democratic resistance to the Contras as
guaranteeing the survival of a Marxist-Leninist regime intent on
spreading the gospel according to Fidel Castro right up to the Rio
Grande.
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., long a stalwart Contra backer, called
the proposed dismantling of the Contras a ``disaster.'' He said
that outcome might have been averted if Congress had shown more
willingness to stand by the Contras rather than strip them of
military aid, as it did last year.
   Hyde and like-minded conservatives, such as former Assistant
Secretary of State Elliot Abrams, could never understand the
congressional hostility toward the Contras.
   Hyde said Congress has a penchant for funding rebel groups in
such remote countries as Afghanistan, Cambodia and Angola but an
inexplicable aversion to helping out an insurgency in nearby
Nicaragua.
   If Nicaragua were 12 time zones away, Hyde said, the Contras
would be riding around in ``Rolls Royce jeeps, shooting silver
bullets and sipping Coors beer between battles,'' all compliments
of the U.S. Congress.
   Abrams spent four years as the executor of Reagan's Central
America policy, a role he carried out with a devotion that was so
uncompromising that, among Democrats, he was quite possibly the
most disliked official in the administration.
   Now in private business, Abrams was in a grim mood after the
Central America summit. He suggested that if the Democrats work
their will, U.S. aid will be manipulated by Congress in such a way
that the Contras will face the choice of starving in Honduran
border camps or risking their lives or imprisonment by returning to
Sandinista-led Nicaragua.
   Abrams said Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani entered the
summit hoping to win approval of a resolution putting the Contras
on an equal footing with the leftist guerrilla movement in his
country.
   But Cristiani backed away and acquiesced in the consensus
resolution to demobilize the Contras but not the FMLN in El
Salvador.
   As Abrams saw it, Cristiani felt that congressional Democrats
would punish him by cutting off aid to El Salvador if he were
responsible for a stalemated summit.
   That, in turn, would leave El Salvador vulnerable to a takeover
by the leftist guerrillas, a price that Cristiani was unwilling to
pay, Abrams said.
   Much of the debate in the coming months is expected to focus on
where the Contras will settle. To many outsiders, a process of
national reconciliation in Nicaragua is under way and the Contras
will be able to return safely to their homeland without fear of
reprisal.
   Hyde disagreed and said the administration should do what it can
to help the Contras resettle in the United States. Initially, he
said, he favored their relocation in Fort Worth, Texas _ home of
former Rep. Jim Wright, who fought Contra funding tooth and nail as
House speaker.
   But with Wright's resignation this past spring, the Fort Worth
option has lost its appeal. Hyde's alternate suggestion, delivered
in jest, is that Connecticut, home of anti-Contra warrior Sen.
Chris Dodd would make a fine home for the Contras as well.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
