<FIRST>r w PM-HelmsleyLawyer     08-11 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Lawyer,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsley Lawyer Expected to Join Justice Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer defending hotel ``queen'' Leona
Helmsley on charges of tax evasion is expected to be named head of
criminal tax prosecutions for the Justice Department, sources say.
   James A. Bruton III, part of the four-member defense team at
Mrs. Helmsley's federal trial in New York City, would be a deputy
assistant attorney general in the tax division, department sources
said Thursday.
   The appointment is not expected to be made until after the
Helmsley trial concludes. The department's tax division oversees
all federal tax fraud cases.
   Bruton, 39, is the choice of Assistant Attorney General Shirley
Peterson, head of the tax division, to oversee the unit's criminal
tax section, said the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``I can't comment,'' Bruton said Thursday when asked during a
break in the trial about the possible appointment. He had been
cross-examining an Internal Revenue Service agent.
   A partner in the Washington firm of Williams and Connolly,
Bruton was a trial lawyer in the Justice Department's tax division
and had worked for the IRS general counsel.
   Mrs. Helmsley, who appears in national ads as ``the queen of the
Helmsley Hotels,'' is accused of evading $1 million in federal
income taxes by writing off $4 million worth of personal purchases
as business expenses.
   A former housekeeper testified that Mrs. Helmsley once told her:
``We don't pay taxes. Only the little people pay taxes.''
   Mrs. Helmsley and her husband, Harry, run a $5 billion real
estate and hotel empire. Helmsley, 80, was charged but isn't
standing trial because he was declared mentally incompetent.
   The Helmsley case is one of the most highly publicized criminal
tax cases brought by the Justice Department in recent years.
   Prosecutors say the Helmsleys wrote off as business expenses
such renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., estate as the
installation of a marble dance floor and a sound system that pipes
music to a barbecue pit.
   The defense team is led by Gerald A. Feffer, who was deputy
assistant attorney general in the tax division during the Carter
administration.
   The prosecution is expected to rest its case early next week.
   Also on trial in U.S. District Court in Manhattan are former
Helmsley hotel executive Frank Turco and Joseph Licari, once a top
Helmsley aide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
