<DOCNO> AP890811-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-OffshoreOil     08-11 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Offshore Oil,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Task Force Recommends Environmental Safeguards in Oil Drilling</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 5 a.m. EDT; time set by source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Improved environmental safeguards are needed
before any oil exploration can occur in three disputed sites off
the California and Florida coasts, a task force said today.
   The task force, charged with recommending to President Bush
whether to open the three sites for oil exploration, made clear in
a progress report that it has made no decision on whether drilling
should be allowed.
   But it said that before a decision is made, additional
restrictions are needed to ``reduce the environmental impact'' of
such drilling. It outlined a long list of options aimed at
improving environmental safeguards, but said no decision has been
made on which ones to recommend to the president.
   In February, Bush directed the task force to examine the
environmental concerns surrounding the proposed oil drilling on the
two California sites, which together cover nearly 8 million acres
off the state's northern and southern coasts.
   He also asked for a review of plans to sell leases for oil
development in a third site, covering 14 million acres in the Gulf
of Mexico near the Florida Everglades.
   There has been strong opposition to opening the three areas to
the oil companies because of fear that drilling would endanger
nearby environmentally sensitive areas. The concern intensified
after the massive oil spill from the Exxon Valdez tanker last March
in Alaska.
   The task force, headed by Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan, has
conducted nine hearings so far and a recommendation is to be made
at the end of the year.
   The report said that during the hearings, most of more than 650
witnesses and some 11,000 written comments have expressed intense
concern about the potential environmental harm that could be caused
by oil exploration at the three sites.
   ``Many people expressed the view that while they would suffer
the losses from any environmental effects of oil and gas
development, they stand to gain few, if any, of the potential
benefits,'' said the task force. At the same time, the group noted,
oil and gas industry spokesmen disputed the environmental concerns
and suggested the risks are minimal.
   The task force said various ``restrictions designed to reduce
the environmental impacts of oil and gas development'' should be
considered before deciding whether to allow drilling.
   Options cited by the task force include the widespread use of
buffer zones between drilling sites and environmentally sensitive
areas, and an array of proposals to protect against oil spills or
control damage if a spill should occur.
   Other options include requiring oil from the three areas to be
transported to shore by pipeline and not tanker; that oil companies
hold a special bond to assure adequate compensation for spill
damage; that permanent emergency response teams be established with
adequate equipment, manpower and training, and that tankers, if
allowed, be limited in size and have double bottoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
