<DOCNO> AP890811-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Economy     08-11 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Economy,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation, Labor Unrest Provide Unsettling Scenario</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising prices are placing new strains
on ordinary Filipinos and threaten social and political unrest as
President Corazon Aquino seeks to restructure the nation's economy.
   According to official figures, consumer prices increased last
month by 10.3 percent _ their highest level since Mrs. Aquino took
power in the 1986 uprising that toppled President Ferdinand Marcos.
   Prices jumped nearly 12 percent in the central Visayas islands
and Mindanao. In a country where $300 a month is considered a
middle-class salary, any substantial price increase means hardship
for the public and political risks for the government.
   ``This will hit the citizenry like a cannonball in the eyes,''
wrote Mrs. Aquino's former spokesman, Teodoro Benigno. ``The
gauntlet comes alive when the public reacts to price increases.''
   Public school teachers and other government employees have
already been agitating for salary increases, which Mrs. Aquino says
the nation cannot afford.
   ``There's no money,'' wrote columnist Conrado de Quiros in the
Philippine Daily Globe. ``Why doesn't the government tell it to
foreign banks? Why should it tell that to its teachers and
workers?''
   Teachers demanded a minimum monthly salary of $215; they now
earn $95, which is below the poverty line. The government has
agreed to $148 a month for teachers.
   ``Even now, there is a growing recognition in government that
the moderately high growth rates of the last three years are
plainly unsustainable,'' wrote the independent daily Malaya.
``Unless bold measures are undertaken, we might as well kiss
recovery goodbye.''
   Many economists believe the outlook is not altogether gloomy.
The economy grew by more than 5 percent in 1988 and is expected to
increase this year by 6 percent.
   Agriculture, the livelihood of more than 60 percent of the 58
million Filipinos, grew by more than 10 percent. Investment jumped
more than 106 percent in the first four months of the year,
according to the Philippine Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Despite the impressive statistics, the Aquino administration has
been unsuccessful in spreading the effects of growth to the
majority of the population.
   The government acknowledges that the poorest third of society
controls only 9 percent of the national income, virtually unchanged
from the final years of the Marcos administration.
   In parts of Manila, elegant department stores rivaling those of
New York and London stand within a few miles of wretched squatter
camps, where tens of thousands live in clapboard shanties.
   Industrial nations have pledged $3.5 billion in 1990 to help the
Philippine economy. But the government acknowledges that the
effects of the aid may not been seen by ordinary Filipinos for
years.
   Under a controversial policy memorandum to the International
Monetary Fund, the government agreed to a number of measures,
including gradually eliminating subsidies on rice, energy, water
and other essentials.
   That will reduce the budget deficit but is expected to increase
consumer prices. The government also is studying an increase in
fuel prices, which may be increased by the end of the year
depending on the world petroleum market.
   During a recent walkout by government workers, employees of the
Central Bank carried banners denouncing the IMF and calling for
reductions in service payments on the nearly $30 billion foreign
debt. Domestic and foreign debt service accounts for 40 percent of
the national budget.
   Economic Planning Secretary Solita Monsod, a respected economics
professor, resigned last June after warning that government
economic policies threatened social unrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
