<FIRST>r w PM-DrugParaphernalia     08-11 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Paraphernalia,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tobacco Industry Wants Answers to `What is Drug Paraphernalia?'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There appears to be no easy answer to the
question of what is drug paraphernalia, and businesses complain
that they are losing thousands of dollars in merchandise that is
being seized in government raids.
   ``Are all glass pipes illegal?,'' businessman Richard K. Rowland
asked the U.S. International Trade Commission at a hearing Thursday.
   ``Are all wood pipes illegal? Are all stone pipes illegal or is
there one type that is legal? All I'm saying is give me the rules
and let me steer clear of this legal mine field called the Mail
Order Drug Paraphernalia Control Act.''
   Rowland, whose Contempo Tobacco Products warehouse in Nashville,
Tenn., was raided in March, said the tobacco industry needs ``some
very specific guidelines as to what is and what is not drug
paraphernalia and why.''
   John Esau, director of the Customs Service's commercial fraud
and enforcement center, said about $14 million worth of items had
been confiscated under the 1986 act but that tighter definitions
are needed.
   ``This particular law makes it extraordinarily difficult to
define what is drug paraphernalia,'' Esau said. ``We are going to
rely on the courts to help us define it.''
   The commission, an independent and bipartisan agency established
by Congress to investigate trade matters, is reviewing the imports
at the request of the Senate Finance Committee.
   Among the factors the law says can be used to determine whether
an item is drug paraphernalia are instructions about its use,
advertising, how it is displayed for sale and the existence and
extent of its legitimate uses.
   The act calls for penalties of up to 3 years in prison and
$100,000 in fines for each violation.
   But Rowland and other pipe-business representatives said
manufacturers and retailers can't read consumers' minds and can't
be held responsible for illegal use of legitimate items.
   ``I agree it's tragic there's a drug problem in this country,
but a lack of imagination is the only limit to turning anything
into drug paraphernalia,'' Rowland said.
   After Rowland's warehouse was raided, then-Customs Commissioner
William von Raab announced that the 306,000 items seized _ filling
eight 48-foot containers _ represented the largest such seizure in
U.S. history, worth about $10 million.
   But Rowland said the items confiscated ``are similar or the same
as items or materials that have been in the tobacco industry for
hundreds of years.''
   ITC Chairwoman Anne E. Brunsdale asked witnesses to suggest
guidelines to help define drug paraphernalia, such as a minimum
size of a pipe bowl.
   The only one who offered any ideas was Lorraine Shapiro of The
Mill in Corning, N.Y.
   She suggested a minimum pipe-bowl diameter of three-eights of an
inch and a minimum stem length of 2 inches. Her pipe company, which
uses imported woods, lost about $45,000 worth of inventory through
a Customs-led raid in January, she said.
   Esau also said the Customs Service wants to change required
manifests to help pinpoint questionable items.
   For example, he said, all imported plastic bags are listed as
plastic bags and don't differentiate between garbage bags and 1
{-inch square containers used by jewelers, makers of precision ball
bearings _ and drug dealers.
   The primary exporters of the paraphernalia are Pacific Basin
countries and ``areas of the Middle East,'' Esau testified.
   In an interview, he said Hong Kong, Taiwan and Japan were
exporters, adding that the People's Republic of China and Korea may
also export such items.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
