<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-11 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a thundering oink, Speedy Pigalis II
brought home the bacon when she won the Ohio State Fair annual
Buckeye Pig Race, beating Pigit and I'm A Bore by a snout.
   At first, Speedy trailed by 60 feet, but wedged between Pigit
and I'm A Bore down the stretch of the 80-foot course to secure her
victory oats after Thursday's race.
   But the champion wasn't about to ham it up after the big pig
win. The swine shunned well-wishers and turned her attention
instead to munch on her spoils.
   Trainer Amy Herbkersman, 15, of Collins, won the first-place
purse of $180 while notching her second consecutive title and fifth
overall. Miss Herbkersman won the race last year with champion
Turbo Pig.
   She also was the trainer of second-place I'm A Bore, and her
father, Doug Herbkersman, trained Pigit, the third-place finisher.
   The Herbkersmans put the pigs through a strict regimen at their
Pork Chop Downs facility.
   ``We train hard for about one month up to the race to build
stamina,'' said Judy Herbkersman, Amy's mother. ``They think the
food's down there at the finish line, so they go fast to get down
there.''
   Several pigs, including Chow Sow, Pigit and Pig O' War, shot out
of the gate backward, turning their snouts toward the finish line
and scampering around the competition.
   Other swine entries included Road Hog, Blazing Bacon and Lickity
Chop, but each bowed out in its first race.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clinton has a
suggestion for parents who are angry that their kids can't have
beepers at school to help them protect their expensive automobiles
_ drive crummy cars.
   Clinton said Thursday his office has received several irate
telephone calls from parents about the state law prohibiting the
electronic beepers.
   The problem, the parents said, was that the security systems for
their cars were activated by the beepers, ``and how dare me to
interfere with that,'' the governor told a meeting of juvenile
judges.
   The law was designed to prevent beepers from being used to set
up drug deals in school, Clinton said.
   ``I said, `Listen, I drove a car to school that I couldn't pay
anybody to steal,''' Clinton said. ```And this is more important
than that, and you need to get your kid a worse car.'''
