<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Pierce     08-11 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Pierce,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pierce Firm, Aide Got Special Treatment from HUD: Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government records indicate that the
Department of Housing and Urban Development gave special treatment
to deals involving Secretary Samuel Pierce's former law partners
and his one-time top aide.
   The Manhattan law firm of Battle, Fowler, Jaffin and Kheel and
former aide Lance Wilson kept in touch with Pierce during his
eight-year tenure as head of HUD in the Reagan administration,
according to files Pierce left at the agency.
   There have been a number of allegations of favoritism at HUD
during Pierce's leadership. Separate investigations of agency
programs during that period are being conducted by Congress, the
Justice Department and HUD itself.
   The latest records indicate that HUD waived regulations in one
case that allowed developers represented by Pierce's former law
firm to keep lucrative HUD subsidies. In another case, Paine Webber
Inc., where Wilson worked after leaving government service, won a
contract to serve as HUD's financial adviser.
   Both deals had been opposed by HUD staff members, but the
objections were overridden. While the two instances weren't
related, the law firm was involved in both.
   Wilson was first vice president at Paine Webber when it received
a $1.3 million bond contract, despite the fact that a HUD panel had
recommended another company. Battle, Fowler served as bond counsel
to Paine Webber, according to HUD documents and officials.
   Paine Webber told The New York Times it was conducting an
internal investigation.
   ``It's Paine Webber's policy to conduct our business in
accordance with applicable laws and regulations,'' said spokeswoman
Eileen Ruvane, saying the company wouldn't comment until the
internal investigation was complete.
   ``On the basis of the knowledge to date, we have no evidence of
wrongdoing,'' she told the newspaper. ``To imply otherwise, in our
opinion, would be inappropriate and inaccurate.''
   She wouldn't say when the investigation began or which employees
were under scrutiny.
   The developers who retained Battle, Fowler owned an Amherst,
N.Y., project that won an unusual waiver from HUD in 1988 allowing
the project to keep HUD subsidies.
   The developers of Allenhurst Apartments included Manhattan real
estate executive Stephen Ross, who last year contributed $100,000
to the GOP, and Dennis Penman, chairman of the 1984 Reagan-Bush
campaign committee in Erie County, N.Y.
   A HUD inspector general's report questioned whether Penman had
access to internal HUD information that allowed him to win backing
for the project, awarded nearly $27 million in subsidies over 15
years.
   The subsidies were awarded through a discretionary fund
controlled by Pierce, and its availability was supposed to be
advertised by the local housing agency. But HUD's inspector general
found that the agency never advertised the availability of the
money, instead awarding it directly to Allenhurst.
   Because of that, HUD staffers suggested the funding be canceled,
according a HUD official who spoke Thursday on the condition of
anonymity.
   The official was asked about the project after The Wall Street
Journal reported on the Allenhurst deal.
   R. Hunter Cushing, a former ranking department official, backed
a retroactive waiver for the ad requirement, arguing that if the
subsidies were halted the project likely would default and HUD
might have to pay more than $8 million because it had insured the
project's mortgage.
   Battle, Fowler, according to documents obtained by The
Associated Press from the files of Pierce and a former aide,
Deborah Gore Dean, frequently lobbied HUD on behalf of clients.
   In the bond deals, first reported in Thursday's New York Times,
Battle, Fowler served as bond counsel to Paine Webber and Salomon
Brothers, which managed sales of some of the bonds.
   Pierce's files contain a memo from an assistant telling him of
the involvement of Battle, Fowler and Wilson in the bond offerings.
Also, Wilson's name and telephone number are scribbled on a July
1988 a memo to Pierce from James Schoenberger, then HUD's general
deputy assistant secretary for housing, discussing Paine Webber's
involvement in the bond sales.
   HUD officials said the selection of Paine Webber over the
recommendation of a selection committee was made by
then-Undersecretary Carl Covitz. Covitz told the Times he generally
informed Pierce of his activities but didn't recall any
intervention by Pierce on behalf of Paine Webber or Battle, Fowler.
   Pierce kept in close touch with Wilson, his top aide from
1981-84 and whom he once described as his ``right hand.''
   Among the correspondence in the files was a letter from Pierce
to Wilson thanking him for helping arrange a dinner in Pierce's
honor. Wilson also sent his former boss books about wine and New
York city restaurants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890811-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0129EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Crops     08-11 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Crops,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Offers Soviet Farmers Foreign Currency for Surplus Grain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will pay farmers in foreign
currency for surplus crops to reduce the country's dependency on
imported grain.
   Under the decree announced Thursday, the government could save
money in the long run since foreign grain is more expensive than
that grown domestically.
   Foreign money can be used to buy hard-to-get imported goods,
providing incentive for farmers.
   Under the new policy, growers on state farms can sell part of
their high-quality wheat, peas, lupine and oil-bearing seeds to the
Soviet government for convertible currency, the official news
agency Tass said. The ruble is not officially convertible, but
foreign money is.
   The government believes that the chance to earn convertible, or
hard, currency will stimulate so much extra production that the
state will end up paying its own farmers less than it would have
paid for imports to make up chronic shortages, Tass said.
   The news agency said the system will be introduced as an
experiment with this year's harvest and run through 1990. The
government also will consider allowing individual farmers with
private plots and those who lease their land to sell for hard
currency as well, Tass said.
   The news agency's report said the policy is in accordance with a
decision of the Congress of People's Deputies.
   During the Congress' session in June, radical economist Nikolai
Shemelev suggested the Soviet Union adopt such a system.
   He said the government should tell collective farm leaders that
``if they sell grain and meat to the state above a certain level
they will be paid in hard currency with the right of spending it
wherever they want.''
   He was interrupted by applause from the 2,250-member parliament,
and then said: ``Our people are modest. I'm sure there's no need to
pay them $200 a ton of grain; they will be satisfied with $75.''
   In a deal announced in late June, the U.S. Agriculture
Department said the Soviets bought 400,000 metric tons of wheat at
about $140 a ton, bringing the 1988-89 total to 4.2 million tons.
   The department on Thursday said it estimated Soviet grain
production this year at 200 million metric tons, 10 million below
earlier forecasts, and said there would be a resulting rise in
imports.
   Tass said the state would pay farmers $96 in hard currency per
ton of strong and durum wheat; $64 per ton of other high-quality
wheat; $128 per ton of pea and lupine, and $144 per ton of
sunflower, soy, rape, flax and mustard seed.
   ``The farms will be free in spending the currency,'' it said.
   Soviet citizens' access to foreign currency is normally very
restricted. Soviets going abroad are allowed to exchange only a
small sum of rubles for hard currency, and ordinary citizens who
have not worked abroad are not allowed to hold foreign currency at
all.
   The restrictions have begun to loosen slightly, however, as more
and more Soviet firms are allowed access to foreign markets under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   The ability to buy foreign goods takes on added significance in
the face of the worsening shortages of such basic Soviet goods as
soap, detergent and medicine under the economic dislocation the
reforms have brought.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
