<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-LoanDefaults     08-11 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loan Defaults,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Loan Default Rate Down From Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The overall rate of student loan defaults this
year is below last year's average, the Education Department says.
   The agency issued a new school-by-school list of student loan
default rates Thursday, and said the overall rate of 17 percent was
4 percentage points below last year's average.
   ``There's a lot of work left to be done, but if the figures
suggest a trend, it's clearly in the right direction,'' Education
Secretary Lauro Cavazos said.
   The 17 percent rate is the percentage of borrowers required to
start repaying their loans in fiscal 1987 but defaulted in 1987 or
1988. Figures released earlier this year showed a 21 percent
default rate for those required to start repayments in 1986.
   Nearly 2 percent, or 101, of the schools, which include
colleges, universities and proprietary schools, had default rates
above 60 percent. Two-thirds, or 3,570 schools, had rates below 20
percent.
   Defaults are expected to cost the nation $1.9 billion this
fiscal year. Much of the problem involves proprietary, or
profit-making, trade schools.
   Although the default rate for such schools fell from 40 percent
to 33 percent in the latest list, the rate remains nearly twice as
high as the national average and the rate for two-year colleges. It
is nearly five times as high as the rate for four-year
institutions, the department said.
   The department attributed the decline in the overall default
rate to several factors, including improvements in data quality,
definition changes in calculating default rates, a probable
increase in loan payment deferments and public attention leading to
a reduction in defaulters.
   Schools with default rates above 60 percent, and those above 40
percent that fail to reduce their rates by 5 points a year, will be
subject to penalties and termination starting in January 1991.
   Only schools with at least 30 people due to start repaying loans
in 1987 were included on the department's list.
   Here is a list of the 10 schools with the highest default rates.
The figure in parentheses represents the number of students
entering repayment status. All of the schools are proprietary
except Carlinshar Institute, which is a two-year private
institution.
   Debbie's School of Beauty Culture, Chicago, 90.2 percent (51).
   Sierra College of Business, Los Angeles, 88.3 percent (1,456).
   Louisiana School of Professions, Shreveport, 87.2 percent (234).
   Stevenson's Academy of Hair Design, New Orleans, 86.8 percent
(53).
   Cambridge Technical Institute, Dayton, Ohio, 85 percent (1,947).
   Carlinshar Institute, Chicago, 84.4 percent (160).
   Alma's Beauty College, Detroit, 83.7 percent (49).
   Debbie's School of Beauty Culture, Harvey, Ill., 83.5 percent
(85).
   Baton Rouge Beauty College, Baton Rouge, La., 81.8 percent (132).
   Mane St. International School of Hair Design, Johnston City,
Tenn., 81.1 percent (90).
</TEXT>
