<DOCNO> AP890811-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-AIDSEnzyme     08-11 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Enzyme,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Targets For Drugs To Control AIDS, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study that describes the precise shape
of a key enzyme of the AIDS virus may help scientists develop drugs
to disable the deadly virus, researchers say.
   Stephen B.H. Kent of the California Institute of Technology in
Pasadena said Thursday that the discovery was the first accurate
description of protease, an enzyme essential in the reproduction
cycle of the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, which causes
AIDS.
   Pharmaceutical company representatives said drugs that block the
action of protease already are being tested, but that the new study
should contribute to a more detailed understanding of how the virus
works.
   Kent said the description will enable pharmaceutical companies
to develop compounds that will ``fit like a hand in a glove over
the active sites of the enzyme'' and prevent it from producing
reverse transcriptase, the next step in the life cycle of the AIDS
virus.
   AZT, or zidovudine, the only anti-viral drug approved for
treatment of AIDS, works by blocking the action of reverse
transcriptase. Protease, Kent said, is farther ``upstream'' in the
cascade of molecular events that leads to replication of the virus.
   ``If you turn off this protease enzyme, then you stop the
production of reverse transcriptase,'' he said, adding that it
would keep an AIDS virus from making copies of itself and thus
prevent the virus from infecting other cells in the body.
   ``That is the same as killing it,'' he said.
   Mariusz Jaskolski, a member of the the National Cancer
Institute, which worked on the study, said while other researchers
have described the protease enzyme, the new study accurately
locates each atom of the complex molecule.
   Paul Oestreicher, a spokesman for Hoffmann-La Roche, a major
pharmaceutical company, said a number of drugs that inhibit
reproduction of the AIDS virus are being developed, most of which
work by blocking the action of reverse transcriptase.
   He said a drug that would block the action of the protease
enzyme could provide another weapon in the war on AIDS.
   Sharon Arnold of SmithKline Beckman Co. said scientists there
already are testing known protease blocking agents and that precise
description of the protease molecule would merely be a refinement
of what is already known.
   ``It would have been useful two or three years ago,'' she said.
``We've already been able to synthesize powerful protease
inhibitors.''
   The protease structure study was a cooperative effort by the
Frederick, Md., Center Research Facility of the National Cancer
Institute, led by Alexander Wlodawer, and by a California Institute
of Technology team led by Kent.
   A report on the study is published this week in Science, the
journal of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome disables the body's immune
system so it cannot resist infection. The HIV virus most often is
spread through close contact with blood, blood products or semen
from infected people.
   As of June 30, AIDS had been diagnosed in 99,936 Americans, of
whom 58,014 have died since June 1, 1981, according to the Centers
for Disease Control. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890811-0034 </DOCNO>
