<FIRST>r a PM-Bishops-Abortion     08-11 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bishops-Abortion,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Bishops Call For New Action Against Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Roman Catholic bishops said the
anti-abortion movement should seize the opportunity offered by a
recent U.S. Supreme Court decision to lobby state legislatures for
new limits on abortion.
   While charging that abortion rights advocates are apparently
trying to revive anti-Catholic sentiments, the Committee on
Pro-Life Activities of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops
said Thursday the court ruling ``marks the beginning of a new
debate, in which many voices must be raised in defense of life.''
   The 1,500-word statement, called ``An Opportunity to Defend
Life,'' suggests opponents of legalized abortion concentrate on
such short-term goals at the state level as limiting government
funding of abortion; requiring parental notification and consent on
abortion for minors; restricting late-term abortions; and
installing other safeguards to ``prevent hasty or uninformed
consent'' to abortions.
   The statement by the bishops' committee headed by Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin of Chicago was a planning analysis following the
high court's July 3 ruling upholding a Missouri law that banned
abortions in public hospitals and stopped public employees from
counseling women about abortions. The decision stopped short of
overturning the 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision under which women have
the right to seek abortions, but allowed states to impose new
restrictions.
   In their statement, the bishops made a special appeal for groups
opposing abortion to work together. The groups have been battling
over tactics such as whether to picket abortion clinics or to seek
a total or partial ban on abortion.
   ``The movement in support of abortion on demand is united in its
agenda; pro-life Americans must not give their adversaries an easy
victory by launching attacks on each other over questions of
political strategy,'' the bishops said.
   The committee said the new legislative situation also raises a
special problem involving hints of anti-Catholicism.
   Some ``accuse us of seeking indiscriminately to impose our moral
ideals on other Americans,'' the bishops said. That attitude
``would exclude us at the outset from this debate on the alleged
grounds that our opposition to abortion is motivated solely by
religious convictions.
   ``Anti-Catholic sentiment has never been entirely absent from
the pro-abortion campaign, but abortion-rights advocates apparently
seek to revivify it now that the efforts of Catholics and other
pro-life citizens have begun to bear fruit,'' the committee said.
   Nevertheless, the bishops said, ``we do not intend to be ruled
out of this or any social debate by spurious interpretations of the
First Amendment. We must continue to speak for those who cannot
speak for themselves, our unborn sisters and brothers.''
   Abortion Rights Mobilization, a coalition of groups favoring the
legal right to abortions, has sued the federal government to revoke
the church's tax exemption status because of its lobbying against
abortion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
