<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS in 3rd graf that Nikkei lost sted gained; pickup 4th
graf pvs, `Chemical bank...' ^Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the yen Friday, while
stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged down.
   The dollar closed at 140.10 yen, up 1.05 yen from Thursday's
finish. It opened at 140.10 yen and moved between 139.87 yen and
140.20 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 139.47-point
loser on Thursday, dropped 6.84 points, or 0.02 percent, to close
at 34,712.96.
   Chemical Bank trader Minori Takeuchi said the dollar's gains at
the start of Tokyo trading followed a similar upswing in the market
in Sydney, Australia, where Japanese investors bought the dollar
before Tokyo opened.
   ``They bought the currency mainly for position adjustments
because many investors have sold the U.S. unit starting this
week,'' she said.
   Currently, the dollar is moving very little at a rate slightly
higher than 140 yen, as the majority of market players stepped off
to the sidelines ahead of a release of the U.S. producer price
index for July later Friday.
   ``Although the dollar has slowly climbed over the 140-yen mark,
demand for the currency is not strong enough to push it up
higher,'' Ms. Takeuchi said.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues regained 110.73 points, or 0.32 percent, to rise back to
34,830.53 within the first 15 minutes of trading. It had shed
139.47 points the previous day.
   Dealers said the index's recovery followed gains in the Dow
Jone's industrial average of 30 major issues in New York overnight,
where the index gained 26.55 points to end at 2,712.63, surpassing
the 2,700 level for the first time since August 1987.
