<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st item to FIX name to Newton, sted Hayes-Newton</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor John Newton, who portrayed
television's Superboy but had real-life problems with traffic cops,
is hanging up his cape.
   The Superboy syndicated television series begins its second year
of production Monday with a new actor who will replace Newton,
officials said.
   Newton played a college student who becomes the boy of steel to
assist the downtrodden, like his father, Superman. Executive
Producer Ilya Salkind on Thursday introduced Gerard Christopher as
the new Superboy.
   Newton had contractual and professional differences with Salkind
and Viacom Enterprises, the distributors of the TV series,
officials said.
   Newton was not entirely truthful with the sheriff and a judge in
Orlando when he convinced them to tear up a traffic ticket earlier
this year. He told them he had no other traffic violations and that
his Superboy image would be hurt if a careless-driving citation was
allowed to stand.
   Later, it turned out that Newton had at least four other traffic
tickets and his driver's license had been suspended twice since
1982.
