<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Edges Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar firmed against the Japanese yen today,
while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged down.
   The dollar closed at 140.10 yen, up 1.05 yen from Thursday's
finish. It opened at 140.10 yen and ranged between 139.87 yen and
140.20 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 139.47-point
loser Thursday, again shed 6.84 points, or 0.02 percent, closing at
34,712.96.
   The stock exchange's main barometer regained more than 100
points in slow, early morning trading, but softened afterward.
   Satoru Nagayoshi, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said
the downturn began as market players started selling for
profit-taking after the early gains that followed an overnight jump
in New York.
   ``Initiated by high-tech issues, prices were falling constantly
shortly after the early rise,'' he said.
   The market was quiet throughout the day because many investors
were taking summer vacations. Nomura Securities estimated the day's
volume at 500 million shares, or about half the daily average of 1
billion.
   The dollar firmed, hovering near 140.00 yen in relatively quiet
dealings.
   Chemical Bank trader Minori Takeuchi said the dollar's gain
followed a similar upswing in Sydney, where Japanese investors
bought the dollar before the Tokyo Foreign Exchange market opened.
   Another trader at a commercial bank in Tokyo said Japanese
investors were buying the dollar out of the expectation that an
increase in the U.S. producer price index for July would be larger.
