<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Kaifu     08-11 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Kaifu,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Prime Minister Denies Having Illegitimate Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu, chosen to restore
credibility to his scandal-plagued governing party, today said an
unsubstantiated report that he fathered an illegitimate child was
untrue.
   Kaifu told reporters he has asked the Nagoya Times to apologize
and publish a retraction.
   ``I was very surprised. It's groundless,'' the 58-year-old prime
minister said when asked about the report at a news conference.
   The report was published last week in the daily newspaper when
Kaifu emerged as the main candidate to replace Sousuke Uno, who was
accused of keeping mistresses.
   On Thursday, the day Kaifu's Cabinet was sworn in, a weekly
magazine published an article saying it had looked into the report
an illegitimate child and was unable to substantiate it.
   But the article in the Shukan Post magazine recounted the
allegation in detail, and the issue was advertised in major
newspapers.
   Neither the Nagoya Times nor the Shukan Post identified the
woman who purportedly had a child by Kaifu, who is married with two
grown children. The Shukan Post said it had found the woman and her
husband in Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost main island, and that
they had refuted the rumor.
   A Nagoya Times editorial staff member, Hideo Nagasaka, told The
Associated Press by phone that Kaifu's secretary had called this
morning to protest the story and ask for a retraction.
   But the newspaper was still looking into the allegation and
would not immediately comply with Kaifu's demand for a retraction,
Nagasaka said.
   The paper's story quoted unidentified political adversaries of
Kaifu as saying a woman in Hokkaido had a daughter by Kaifu about
20 years ago.
   As happened when allegations of sexual misconduct surfaced
against Uno, the story began to get wider attention in Japan after
some foreign media reported that Kaifu's morals were under attack
in the Japanese media.
   In Uno's case, the weekly Sunday Mainichi published a detailed
interview with an unidentified former geisha who said Uno had paid
her to be his mistress, then mistreated her. The allegation was not
reported in the major national newspapers or on television until it
had been published abroad several days later.
   An opposition lawmaker embarrassed Uno by asking him in
Parliament if he was suitable to represent Japan abroad when his
morality was under fire.
   The identity of the former geisha later was revealed when she
was interviewed on television and repeated her criticism of Uno's
character. The scandal contributed to his short-lived tenure as
prime minister.
   Kaifu has promised to carry out political reforms to help his
Liberal Democratic Party overcome the legacy of an influence-buying
scandal that forced Uno's predecessor, Noboru Takeshita, to leave
office June 2.
   Uno then took over as prime minister but announced he would
resign the day after the Liberal Democratics took a beating in the
July 23 election in the upper house of Parliament.
   That set off a search for a replacement, and Kaifu was chosen to
try to restore the Liberal Democrats' popularity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
