<DOCNO> AP890811-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strike     08-11 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strike,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walkout Continues in Estonia Despite Anti-Strike Decree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at about 24 Estonian factories and firms
defied a government decree today and stayed off the job to protest
a law they say discriminates against Russians and other migrants,
local journalists said.
   Sulev Hailik, a journalist with state-run Estonian radio, said
enterprises in the small Soviet republic on the Baltic Sea were hit
by walkouts for a third day, but that employees at some other
factories, including the Volta machine-building plant, had returned
to work.
   A representative for the strikers claimed the walkout had spread
to 42 enterprises and that the government measures taken to halt
the walkout had only strengthened workers' resolve.
   The Estonian Supreme Soviet Presidium, the government's top
executive body, issued a decree Thursday night ordering an
immediate end to the walkout and instructing the Council of
Ministers, or local government cabinet, to ensure the uninterrupted
functioning of the economy.
   That decree did not specify how workers who continued to strike
would be punished, mentioning only vague ``administrative and
criminal measures'' and the drafting of a tougher law on strikes.
   ``They want to threaten us but it won't work,'' a member of the
strike committee said in a telephone interview from Estonia's
capital Tallinn this morning. ``The strike will be continued.''
   The organizer, who refused to give his name, said strikers were
refusing to talk to Estonian officials, and would deal only with
Moscow. The committee on Wednesday sent four representatives to the
Soviet capital to seek a meeting with Vice President Anatoly I.
Lukyanov.
   The protest by non-Estonians was sparked by a new law passed by
the Estonian parliament Tuesday that tightens residency
requirements for voting and holding elected office.
   Non-Estonian residents of the republic, including leaders of the
Russian-dominated InterMovement group, complained the law is aimed
at them because many are new arrivals and launched a protest strike
the day following its passage.
   On Thursday the walkout spread and included as many as 20,000
workers, said Maarika Saarna, an editor at Estonian Radio.
   Hailik said it was not immediately known how many workers were
off the job today, and the strike committee representative said he
had no idea. ``We do not know how many people work at various
enterprises,'' he said.
   On Thursday, strike committee member Artur Kopykin claimed 37
enterprises were affected. On Wednesday, the strike's first day, 22
enterprises were reported on strike, including shipyards and a
motor works.
   Under the new election law, residents of Estonia must live in
the same district for at least two years, or have lived anywhere in
the republic for a total of five years, to be able to vote.
   Candidates for elective office must live in the same place for
five years, or in Estonia for 10 years.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population, and pushed for the law to protect themselves from an
influx of Russians and members of other Soviet ethnic groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
