<FIRST>r a PM-EggDonation     08-11 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egg Donation,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor Urging Couple Considering Divorce to Donate Frozen Egg</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Divorce-Embryo, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who wanted to have a test-tube baby
but now are considering a divorce may donate their frozen,
fertilized egg to another couple, their doctor says.
   ``It's a tough situation,'' said Dr. O'Dell Owens, head of an in
vitro fertilization clinic in Cincinnati. ``They're probably going
to donate the egg. That's what we've encouraged them to do.''
   The egg was frozen after the couple came to Owens for help in
conceiving a child more than a year ago, he said. Owens declined to
disclose their names.
   Terri Hornbach, a spokeswoman at the private Christ Hospital,
where the egg is in storage, also refused to identify the couple.
   Donation could prevent any possibility of the kind of battle
taking place in Maryville, Tenn. Junior Davis is suing his wife,
Mary Sue, for divorce and is asking the court to prevent her from
using any of their seven frozen embryos.
   As a result of the Tennessee case and his experience with the
Cincinnati-area couple, Owens said he plans to draft an agreement
that would give the clinic permission to anonymously donate a
couple's eggs in the event of divorce or death.
   Through the in vitro process, eggs are fertilized outside the
body in a laboratory dish and later implanted in the womb.
</TEXT>
