<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-US     08-11 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palace Announces Aquino To Visit Washington Nov. 9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino will visit
the United States in November for talks that are expected to
include debt relief and the future of American military bases here,
it was announced today.
   A statement from the presidential press office said Mrs. Aquino
will arrive in the United States Nov. 9, but gave no length for the
visit. Presidential spokeswoman Deedee Sytangco said Mrs. Aquino
would visit Canada before traveling to the United States but that
the schedule had not been completed.
   ``President Corazon Aquino has accepted the invitation of
President Bush to make a state visit,'' the statement said.
   Mrs. Aquino last visited the United States in September 1986,
seven months after she took power in the popular uprising that
toppled President Ferdinand Marcos.
   The November visit was announced following a meeting between
Mrs. Aquino and a three-member delegation from the U.S. House of
Representatives.
   ``We discussed her coming to the United States,'' said the
delegation's leader, Rep. Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo. ``We're very
excited that she's coming, and we want to make her visit very
successful. She's very nice to us.''
   Major issues facing the two countries include the Philippines'
nearly $30 billion foreign debt and the future of the six U.S.
military bases, whose lease expires in 1991.
   U.S. officials have said the Philippines probably would become
the second country after Mexico to benefit from American strategy
for reducing the debt burden of developing nations.
   But some Filipino officials believe the country should forego
debt reduction in favor of increased borrowing because of the
country's economic growth potential.
   The United States and the Philippines are expected to begin
talks later this year on whether to extend U.S. military base
operations beyond 1991. Any agreement would require two-thirds
approval of the 23-member Philippine Senate, where anti-base
sentiment is strong.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to say whether she supports keeping the
bases. She said this week that she may wait until September of next
year before informing Washington of her decision.
</TEXT>
