<FIRST>r w PM-BlochInterview     08-11 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch Interview,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bloch Tells Austrian Television He Was In Paris On May 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Felix Bloch, the U.S. diplomat suspected of
spying for the Soviet Union, admits being in Paris the day he
reportedly met a Soviet agent in a restaurant and left a briefcase
for him under the table.
   In an on-camera interview with the Washington correspondent of
Austrian Television, Bloch declined to say whether he dined in
Paris with the suspected Soviet agent or whether he left a
briefcase for him, according to the journalist who conducted the
interview.
   The interview, which was videotaped Thursday for broadcast today
in Vienna, was the first time Bloch has answered questions on the
allegations against him. But he maintained the pattern of his
contacts with reporters over the past two weeks _ offering
tantalizing glimpses but failing to shed much light on the
much-publicized case.
   The Austrian-born Bloch, 54, was suspended from his State
Department job June 22 but no charges have been brought against
him. He has been under close FBI surveillance as the investigation
against him continues, and in recent days has been leading a convoy
of reporters and photographers on jaunts through Washington and its
suburbs.
   Bloch first accepted an invitation to visit the offices of
state-run Austrian TV 10 days ago, but at the time he only chatted
with the correspondent but refused to be interviewed.
   On Thursday, he agreed to visit again and sat for a 15-minute
interview, said correspondent Robert Wiesner.
   ``We started off talking about Vienna, the cemeteries there, and
tombstones,'' said Wiesner, describing Bloch as relaxed.
   Bloch was posted at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna from 1980 to
1987, and for four of those years served as the deputy chief of
mission.
   Then, Wiesner said, he asked Bloch whether he had been in Paris
on May 14. ``Bloch thought for a long time, then said, `yes,'''
Wiesner said, translating the interview which was conducted in
German.
   Sources here have said suspicions about the U.S. diplomat arose
when the United States intercepted a telephone call on May 14 to
Bloch in Washington from a man under surveillance in Paris who
called himself Pierre. The two men set up a meeting in Paris, and
the United States asked French intelligence to monitor it, the
sources said.
   But ABC News reported last week that May 14 was the day Bloch
arrived in Paris from New York and met his contact for dinner,
leaving his briefcase under the table to be picked up by the
suspected Soviet agent.
   Austrian police authorities said they were told by the United
States that the suspected Soviet contact posed as a Finnish
computer salesman. ABC said he traveled with a Finnish passport in
the name of Reino Gikman.
   According to U.S. sources, Bloch has said he only knew the man
as a stamp collector.
   ``Did you meet a gentleman by the name of Reino Gikman?''
Wiesner said he asked Bloch.
   ``I can't answer that question,'' Bloch responded.
   ``Did you go to a restaurant and meet a gentleman and leave a
briefcase?'' Wiesner asked.
   ``I was in a restaurant and I enjoyed the food very much and
there were a lot of people there,'' Bloch reportedly responded.
   ABC identified the restaurant as being in the plush Meurice
Hotel.
   ``Are you missing a briefcase?'' Wiesner said he asked. He said
Bloch paused for a long time and then answered, ``No.''
   Asked whether the allegations that he spied for the Soviets were
true, Bloch declined to comment, Wiesner said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
