<FIRST>r a PM-StoreKillings     08-11 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Store Killings,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in Murder Spree Admits Killing Clerk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED MORENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RATON, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect in a four-state murder spree
confessed to killing a convenience store clerk, and said he had
been using cocaine heavily the month before the shooting.
   In an emotional confession, Gregg Francis Braun, 28, admitted
killing Geraldine Valdez on July 23 during a preliminary hearing
Thursday to determine if there was enough evidence to charge him in
state district court.
   Braun testified that he had been undergoing psychological
counseling in his home town of Garden City, Kan., since June for
recurring violent dreams, and that recent, heavy use of cocaine
worsened a lifelong violent tendency.
   He told the court he had been having more and more bad dreams,
``dreams of killing people.''
   A weapons expert testified that a .25-caliber handgun seized
from Braun, which he admitted using to kill Mrs. Valdez, is
apparently the same weapon used in the killings last month of two
people in Kansas and one in Texas.
   Braun also has been identified as a suspect in the shooting
death of flower shop clerk Gwen Miller and the wounding of two
other women in Ardmore, Okla., on July 21.
   All of the killings were similar: The victims were shop clerks
and were shot in the back of the head with a .25-caliber pistol.
   Braun, jailed here in lieu of $1 million bond, was held for
trial on charges of first-degree murder and second-degree armed
robbery. He will be arraigned before a district judge within 20
days, said Assistant District Attorney Leslie Skinner.
   Ms. Skinner said she would seek the death penalty.
   Assistant Public Defender Stephen Aarons said Braun has no
previous felony convictions, was impaired and unable to appreciate
the criminality of his action and was cooperative with authorities.
   Asked first by Aarons and later by Skinner whether he denied
killing Mrs. Valdez, Braun said, ``No, I don't deny it.''
   He also admitted stealing about $200 from J&amp;T Mini-Mart, a
combination store and gas station where Mrs. Valdez worked in
Springer, 100 miles northeast of Santa Fe.
   Larry Warehime, a firearms examiner for the state Department of
Public Safety, said tests showed the bullets taken from Mrs.
Valdez's body and other casings found in the store were fired from
Braun's gun.
   Warehime said similar tests indicated the gun was the same one
used in the Texas and Kansas shootings.
   Authorities in Kansas have charged Braun with the separate
murders of two Garden City convenience store clerks, Barbara
Kochendorfer and Mary Rains, on July 19. Prosecutors in Texas this
week charged Braun with the murder of photo shop owner Edley Perry
Spurrier in Pampa on July 20.
</TEXT>
