<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Gets Drenched, Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms brought more rain to already saturated ground in
the West today after downpours at Yellowstone National Park created
dangerous mudslides and flash flooding in California prompted
evacuations.
   Rain also fell on portions of the East Coast and widely
scattered thunderstorms developed over the Great Plains.
   Thunderstorms stirred Thursday afternoon along the Nevada and
California border, in areas that were experiencing runoff problems
from Wednesday's rain. In Mono County, Calif., most of the main
roads were either closed or cars had to be escorted.
   Persistent thunderstorms forced a debris-clogged stretch of the
Los Angeles Aqueduct to overflow, while flash flooding prompted
evacuations, stranded motorists and damaged homes, crop land and
highways across a wide swath of Southern California.
   The widely scattered downpours of Wednesday and Thursday deluged
cities throughout San Diego, Imperial, San Bernardino, Riverside,
Mono and Inyo counties, as well as Arizona's Yuma County and
Nevada's Clark County.
   At Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., three people trapped in a
camper were rescued seconds before their vehicle was pulled under a
mudslide Thursday evening, park officials said.
   ``It was a matter of seconds, virtually seconds, and that
vehicle would have gone under,'' said park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo
after talking to a park ranger who rescued the family visiting from
Mexico.
   Elsewhere, widely scattered thunderstorms rumbled across the
northern Rockies, the Dakotas, Wisconsin and parts of southern
Oklahoma and northern Texas today.
   Rain hit the middle and south Atlantic coastal states, and
thunderstorms were along the central Gulf Coast. A thunderstorm
produced wind gusts to 58 mph at Pensacola, Fla., Thursday night.
   Clear skies prevailed this morning over the Ohio Valley, much of
the Mississippi Valley, the Pacific Northwest, much of California
and parts of Texas.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over much of the East Coast, the Appalachians, the upper Ohio
Valley and portions of the Great Lakes; numerous showers and
thunderstorms from eastern New York across the middle and south
Atlantic coastal states to central Florida; scattered thunderstorms
over the Plateau region, much of the Rockies, and northern and
western portions of Texas; and numerous showers and thunderstorms
over much of Arizona and New Mexico.
   Temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s along much of the
East Coast; in the 60s and 70s along the Pacific Coast; into the
lower 90s across the Florida peninsula, and over much of the
northern Plains; above 90 degrees from southern Texas across much
of New Mexico and southern Arizona to the interior valleys of
California; from 100 to 105 degrees in the Desert Southwest; and in
the 80s throughout the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 50 degrees at Yellowstone
National Park, Wyo., and Quillayute, Wash., to 87 degrees at
Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 68 fair; Boston 66 cloudy; Buffalo 61 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 67 cloudy; Cincinnati 61 fair; Cleveland 64 partly
cloudy; Detroit 64 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 64 rain;
Philadelphia 65 rain; Pittsburgh 62 cloudy; Washington, D.C. 69
cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Des Moines 63 fair; Fort Worth 71
cloudy; Indianapolis 64 fair; Kansas City 63 fair; Nashville 65
fair; New Orleans 70 partly cloudy; Oklahoma City 63 partly cloudy;
St. Louis 70 fair; Minneapolis@St. Paul 65 fair; San Antonio 72
fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 fair; Anchorage 58 rain; Boise 74 fair;
Honolulu 78 partly cloudy; Las Vegas 80 partly cloudy; Los Angeles
64 foggy; Phoenix 86 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City 67 cloudy; San
Diego 70 cloudy; San Francisco 56 partly cloudy; Seattle 56 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 fair; Toronto 61 foggy.
