<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     08-11 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fierce Shelling Duels Overnight Kill 27, Injure 152</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dazed civilians stumbled out of basements
and bomb shelters today to inspect damage from an overnight duel
between Syrian and Christian gunners that police said killed 27
people and wounded 152.
   Police said the 15-hour battle involved howitzers and
multi-barrelled rocket launchers in Beirut, the surrounding
mountains and the eastern Bekaa valley.
   The casualties raised the toll from the five-month confrontation
between Gen. Michel Aoun's predominantly Christian troops and
Syrian forces to 576 killed and 1,474 wounded.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with police
rules, said about a dozen shells crashed into Baabda and the nearby
suburbs of Hazmiyeh and Hadath today but that no casualties from
that fighting were immediately reported.
   On Thursday, the shelling escalated sharply after Syrian gunners
started pounding the presidential palace with salvos from 240mm
mortars.
   Aoun moved into a bunker beneath the palace when the latest
round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war began March 8.
   In the overnight barrage, rockets gouged gaping holes in
residential apartments, shattering walls and windows and triggering
fires that blazed out of control and lighted up the night sky.
   ``Thank God we're alive,'' said Mrs. Khadija Alaya as she came
out of a shelter with her daughter, each carrying a mattress and a
pillow, to find smoke billowing from their sixth-floor apartment.
   Other residents of the Moslem Tarik Jedideh district, still in
pajamas and nightgowns, made their way through debris and glass
shards carpeting the street to inspect their homes for damage.
   The artillery battles have damaged thousands of buildings in
Beirut and sent all but 200,000 of the city's 1.5 million residents
fleeing to safer areas in southern Lebanon, the Bekaa valley and
northeastern mountains.
   ``My sister fled a month ago to the Bekaa, she rented a house
there. I wonder whether she's still alive after last night's
shelling,'' said Hoda Qannine, a housewife in Tarik Jedideh, a
low-income district that took the brunt of the shelling along with
the city's southern slums.
   The police spokesman said more than 10,000 shells and rockets
rained on Beirut, the southeastern mountains and the eastern Bekaa
valley in a barrage that peaked at 60 shells a minute.
   He said the battlefield was expanded as Aoun's gunners opened up
on Syrian army positions in the ancient town of Baalbek and other
areas of the valley 40 miles northeast of Beirut.
   Reliable sources in the Bekaa, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Aoun's gunners scored direct hits on at least six
Syrian army outposts and artillery emplacements. A Baalbek resident
who drove to Beirut early in the day said a dozen shells crashed
into the city and the surrounding villages overnight.
   She said Syrian army ambulances ``brought casualties all night
from different parts of the Bekaa'' to a hospital in Baalbek run by
the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   The Syrian command in Lebanon refuses comment on its losses.
   The current fighting began after Aoun blockaded ports run by
Syria's militia allies south of Beirut with the aim of salvaging
about $100 million annually in lost customs dues.
   The Syrians and allied militias retaliated by besieging and
shelling the Christian enclave northeast of the capital.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Catholic, escalated the confrontation by
declaring a ``war of liberation'' against the 40,000 Syrian troops
in Lebanon. He said they betrayed their 1976 peacekeeping mandate
from the Arab League by taking the Moslem side against the
Christians in the civil war.
</TEXT>
