<SECOND>PM-Fried Appliances,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility To Pay For Appliances Fried In Power Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   VCRs started smoking, light bulbs
exploded and ceiling fans raced as if they were going into orbit
when the power company mistakenly doubled the normal amount of
electricity in 30 homes.
   ``It's a $50,000 foul-up _ 30 houses suffered as much as $2,000
in damages,'' said Florida Power &amp; Light customer service manager
Vic Arena, who promised that the utility would pay to replace all
the burned-out appliances.
   Helen Johns was feeding her 6-year-old son and three infants
Tuesday when the power surge hit her house, snuffing out the air
conditioner, television, stereo, telephone answering machine, can
opener, clock-radio and every other appliance she had plugged in.
   ``My son started screaming, `Mom, the VCR's on fire!''' Mrs.
Johns said. ``I grabbed the three little ones and my son and threw
them outside.''
   The utility blamed a work crew for the mistake, saying crew
members missed a section of line when they were converting
transformers in the neighborhood to a new voltage.
