<FIRST>r a PM-JDLFeud     08-11 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-JDL Feud,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged with Attempted Murder in Jewish Militants' Feud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a Jewish militant group fired
shots at a longtime rival and injured a bystander, then holed up in
his heavily armed apartment for 2{ hours before surrendering,
authorities said.
   Mordechai Levy, 27, head of the Jewish Defense Organization, was
arrested Thursday afternoon at his home in Greenwich Village.
   Police said Levy took a Ruger Mini-14 rifle to the roof of his
townhouse after it was approached by Irv Rubin, head of the Jewish
Defense League. Levy led a JDL splinter group and had been feuding
for years with the Los Angeles-based Rubin.
   ``He was afraid that the people were coming to kill him,'' said
Chief Robert J. Johnston Jr.
   Levy expressed the fear in calls to the police Wednesday night
and again about noon Thursday, when two men started throwing rocks
at his window, Johnston said. The men were trying to serve Levy
with papers for a libel suit Rubin filed against Levy in Los
Angeles Superior Court on July 27, Johnston said.
   Levy was charged with attempted murder of Rubin and three other
men _ a private investigator, a process server and a 69-year-old
bystander who was shot in the knee, police said.
   The libel lawsuit says Levy, in an interview with a Los Angeles
talk radio station, accused Rubin of being a drug dealer and said
his wife, Shelly, had attempted suicide, according to Earl Krugel,
chairman of the JDL's Los Angeles chapter.
   Police kept Levy's building under siege until he surrendered
because he had permits for seven guns, said Inspector Richard
Mayronne. Levy's building lobby was rigged with remote-controlled
tear gas, police said.
   People who said they were linked with Levy's group have claimed
responsibility for bombing targets they accused of anti-Semitism,
but Levy has always denied his group was involved.
   The JDL was formed by Rabbi Meir Kahane to mount armed response
to anti-Semitic acts in New York. It dropped most of its activities
after Kahane moved to Israel and was elected to the parliament.
</TEXT>
