<FIRST>r i PM-France-Satellite     08-11 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Satellite,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Efforts to Boost European Satellite Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two efforts to boost the Hipparcos star-mapping
satellite into its final orbit have failed, the European Space
Agency said today.
   The agency said more attempts were planned Saturday and Sunday.
   The satellite was launched Tuesday night by an Ariane rocket. It
is in a safe orbit and all other systems are operating normally,
the agency said.
   But if not placed in a higher orbit soon, the satellite will be
pulled back to earth.
   The satellite, launched from the European Space Agency's center
in Kourou, French Guiana, is on a mission to plot with
unprecedented precision the position and motion of 120,000 stars.
   A secondary experiment is to provide less precise data
concerning 400,000 stars.
   A first effort to light the satellite's engine to boost it into
geostationary orbit failed for unknown reasons Thursday. The
agency's engineers in Darmstadt, West Germany, tried again this
morning, with no results.
</TEXT>
