<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0471 08-11 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Stage Warning Strike in Gdansk</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Solidarity-called one-hour strike.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buses stopped running and plants halted production
today in Gdansk as Solidarity staged a one-hour strike demanding
compensation for recent price increases and an end to political
favoritism in factories.
   The general strike in the Baltic port city, which union
spokesmen said affected hundreds of workplaces, was the first
provincewide action taken by Solidarity since it was legalized in
April after a seven-year ban.
   In Italy, meanwhile, two key Solidarity political leaders
reiterated the labor movement's demand to head the government but
raised the possibility of including reform-minded communists in a
governing coalition.
   In an editorial today, the Polish government newspaper
Rzeczpospolita renewed its call for a ``grand coalition''
government that would include Solidarity and the communists.
   But the opposition paper Gazeta Wyborcza stressed that only a
Solidarity-led government would ``bring about the social
reawakening necessary for reconstruction after the catastrophe.''
   The protest action today from noon to 1 p.m. was joined by the
communist-linked trade union federation OPZZ in the province, which
said it approved of Solidarity's economic demands.
   ``I can see through the window that city transport has
stopped,'' said a spokesman at Solidarity's Gdansk Information
Agency, speaking by telephone shortly after noon. ``Trams and buses
have stopped ... I see people waiting at bus stops.''
   Krzysztof Dowgiallo of the Solidarity regional council in Gdansk
estimated that 500 enterprises planned to strike, and it appeared
the action was successful. He said the city had become quiet, and
banners were hanging from many factories proclaiming the strike.
   The protest was aimed at achieving six economic and political
demands:
   _Increasing planned pay compensation for recent food price
increases of up to 300 percent.
   _Ending monopolies in the purchase and distribution of
agricultural products.
   _Stopping the financing of political or union organizations by
enterprises (such as factory-level communist groups.)
   _Liquidating the ``nomenklatura'' _ the system by which
promotions to management are nearly always given to party loyalists.
   _Creation of union rights for employees whose plants are
subordinated to the defense and police ministries.
   _Speeding up the holding of local council elections to be held
for the first time on a totally democratic basis.
   Solidarity chapters in the northwestern port of Szczecin and the
southern city of Katowice said they would stage similar one-hour
protests Wednesday.
   Today's strike came a day after Solidarity began talks with two
minor parties who hold the balance of power in parliament about
forming a Solidarity government, as urged this week by the
movement's leader Lech Walesa.
   Bronislaw Geremek and Adam Michnik, who were received by
Polish-born Pope John Paul II at the pope's Castel Gandolfo summer
palace, stressed in interviews Thursday with Italian television
that the key was for Solidarity to head the next government but
that it could include communists.
   ``That which was offered to us, participation in a government
headed by communists, means the perpetuation of the regime,'' said
Geremek, the No. 2 Solidarity political leader after Walesa.
   ``The only government that can appear credible in the eyes of
the Polish people is an executive headed by Solidarity in coalition
with all the reformist forces in the country,'' including communist
reformers, said Michnik, one of Walesa's closest strategists.
   Geremek explained in the interview that Solidarity feels forced
by the economic crisis _ especially the sharp increase in food
prices Aug. 1 _ to accelerate its long-range timetable for taking
power.
   ``We asked ourselves, do we have time to wait? The answer we
gave ourselves is no. There is no more time,'' Geremek said.
   As Solidarity works to form a government, newly elected
communist Prime Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak is pressing on with his
search for a Cabinet to present to the Sejm, or parliament. Walesa
has said he will urge Solidarity lawmakers to reject any government
led by Kiszczak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
