<FIRST>r i PM-NewZealand     08-11 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Zealand,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palmer Forms Cabinet, Names Lange As Attorney-General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Geoffrey Palmer
formed his Cabinet today and appointed his predecessor, David
Lange, to the post of attorney general.
   Palmer took over as prime minister after Lange resigned Monday
for what he described as health reasons. Lange quit after five
years following a year-long internal party wrangle over economic
policy. Palmer was elected leader of the governing Labor Party the
following day.
   Lange, 47, also was named minister of state and put in charge of
the Serious Fraud Office. The positions, including that of attorney
general, fall outside Cabinet.
   Lange said he was pleased with his new jobs, which he will
assume officially on Monday.
   Palmer made no major changes to financial or economic
portfolios. David Caygill remains finance minister and minister of
revenue, with Peter Neilson staying as associate minister of
finance outside of Cabinet.
   Roger Douglas, who was returned to the Cabinet last week after
being dismissed by Lange last year as finance minister, was
appointed minister of police and minister of immigration, as well
as having responsibilities for the Audit Department and for Special
Projects, such as planning election strategy.
   The Labor government must go the polls by October 1990.
   Palmer has cut his workload to enable him to concentrate on the
job of prime minister, but he remains minister for the environment.
He was formerly attorney general and justice minister. Palmer also
remains minister in charge of the New Zealand Security Intelligence
Service.
   Helen Clark, deputy prime minister, remains minister of health
and becomes minister of labor.
   Mike Moore stays on as minister of external relations and trade,
and minister of overseas trade and marketing.
</TEXT>
