<FIRST>u w PM-RetailSales 2ndLd-Writethru a0523 08-11 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0523,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Rebound in July</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new to CORRECT that declines not back to back after
official revision; picks up at pvs 3rd graf, Retail sales</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   .
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales, paced by renewed spending on
automobiles, rebounded 0.9 percent in July after falling the
previous month, the government reported today.
   The Commerce Department said sales increased to a seasonally
adjusted $143.7 billion last month following a 0.1 percent decline
in June. The June sales had been revised to $142.4 billion from the
$140.8 billion originally reported last month.
   The department also revised the May retail sales sharply to an
0.8 percent increase, rather than the 0.1 percent decrease
previously reported. It said the revision was due to responses from
additional retailers.
   Retail sales are viewed as a measure of economic health since
they account for about one-third of the nation's economic activity.
   The economy has slowed over the past year as the Federal Reserve
drove interest rates higher to head off inflation. Spending on
durable goods _ big-ticket items such as cars expected to last more
than three years _ has been particularly affected by the Fed's
credit-tightening measures.
   The Fed switched course in June, however, and since then has
nudged interest rates lower in an effort to keep the economy out of
a recession.
   The Commerce Department said auto sales, which fell 1 percent in
June, bounced back 2.7 percent last month, their best month since
rising 4.7 percent in October 1988. Auto sales posted a 0.7 percent
drop in May.
   Autos represent about 20 percent of total retail sales.
   July auto sales totaled $31.7 billion, the highest level since
$31.9 billion in sales in December 1988, the department said. The
sales record was $33.9 billion in September 1986.
   Durable goods sales as a whole rose 1.7 percent in July after
falling 0.9 percent in June and 0.5 percent in May.
   Furniture and other home furnishing sales were down 0.3 percent.
   Excluding the automotive category, overall retail sales rose 0.4
percent, following increases of 0.2 percent in June and 1.2 percent
in May.
   Sales of non-durable goods rose 0.4 percent last month after
climbing 0.4 percent in June and 0.2 percent in May.
   Department store and other general merchandise spending was up
0.5 percent.
   Also showing increased sales in the non-durable category were
grocery stores, up 0.6 percent; restaurants, up 1.2 percent, and
drug stores, up l0.1 percent.
   The only non-durable category posting a decline was clothing
stores, down 1.5 percent. Service station sales remained level.
   For the three months from May through July, overall retail sales
were 6 percent higher than the same period in 1988.
   The retail sales declines in May and June represented the first
consecutive monthly drops since 1987, when sales fell 0.8 percent
in September and 0.9 percent in October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
