<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0937EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Anti-AbortionArrests     08-11 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anti-Abortion Arrests,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suit Seeks Order Against LAPD Over Use of `Pain Compliance' Arrests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Should stand for PMs; hearing set for 4:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservative Christian group asked a
federal judge to prohibit police from using painful arrest methods
against anti-abortion protesters.
   The request for a temporary restraining order was filed Thursday
by the Rutherford Institute of California on behalf of Operation
Rescue supporters, who have attempted to block abortion clinics and
slow down police efforts to arrest them by such tactics as going
limp and even smearing their arms with petroleum jelly.
   A hearing on the request was scheduled this afternoon before
U.S. District Judge A. Wallace Tashima.
   ``Our case is really not, if you will, an abortion rights
case,'' said Samuel B. Casey of the Rutherford Institute. He
described the complaint as a civil rights case that arises under
the Fourth Amendment to the Constitution, which protects citizens
from unreasonable seizure.
   ``The rights that we seek to vindicate are equally valuable to
any kind of peaceful, non-violent demonstrator,'' Casey said.
   The suit was filed, Casey said, because he believes police are
using pain compliance techniques, such as bending a wrist or arm
backward against the joint, in escalating fashion against
anti-abortion demonstrators. The group is trying to block the use
of such tactics at a deminstration planned for Saturday.
   Police will argue against any attempt to prohibit officers from
using the force necessary to make arrests, said Cmdr. William
Booth, a police spokesman.
   ``A police department can hardly function and society can hardly
have effective order if those who are to be arrested dictate the
terms of their arrest,'' Booth said.
   ``The law provides for us to use the amount of force necessary
to make an arrest, and the courts have interpreted that to mean the
amount of force needed to overcome the arrestee's resistance to
arrest.''
   However, Booth said police will protect the rights of
demonstrators who exercise their rights to free speech and
assembly, providing the protest is lawful.
   Police in Los Angeles are using painful arrest techniques to
counter Operation Rescue's strategy of illegally blocking the
entrances to abortion clinics and delaying arrests to keep them
closed as long as possible. To accomplish this, Operation Rescue
protesters are taught to resist passively, by going limp like a rag
doll or flexing their muscles rigidly.
   Others smear petroleum jelly on their arms and legs to make it
more difficult for officers to carry them to paddy wagons.
   Police made arrests during Operation Rescue protests in Los
Angeles on June 10 and March 25 because the demonstrators were
blocking abortion clinics in defiance of a federal court order.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
