<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Zambia 1stLd-Writethru a0509 08-11 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Zambia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rift Between Botha, de Klerk, Widens Over Zambian Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 6th, `The independent...,' to UPDATE with
media reaction, Botha's whereabouts. Pickup 7th, `Foreign Ministry...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing President P.W. Botha
said today he was not consulted about a diplomatic mission to
Zambia his heir apparent plans to make, indicating a deepening rift
between the two.
   F.W. de Klerk, expected to succeed Botha in September, responded
to Botha's complaint by calling an urgent meeting of his fellow
Cabinet ministers. He said he had not been able to arrange an
appointment with Botha to discuss the ``possible misunderstanding.''
   Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda announced Thursday that he
would meet Aug. 28 with de Klerk, leader of the governing National
Party.
   The planned meeting in Livingstone, Zambia, was confirmed by
South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha, who said he also would
attend. The foreign minister said the meeting was arranged after
consultations with President Botha.
   However, the president issued a terse statement contradicting
the foreign minister.
   ``I am not aware, in terms of the rules governing overeas
journeys by (Cabinet) ministers, of the discussions to be held ...
as announced by Dr. Kaunda,'' President Botha's statement said.
   The independent South African Press Association said the
president's ``bombshell statement'' had plunged the National Party
into a ``pre-election crisis.'' Andries Treurnicht, leader of the
far-right Conservative Party, said the administration was in
``total chaos.''
   The president's spokesman, Jack Viviers, told the agency that
Botha was at his office in Cape Town. Asked why Cabinet ministers
were unable to meet him, Viviers replied: ``I don't know. Ask
them.''
   Foreign Ministry officials said they were trying to reach Pik
Botha for an explanation. The two Bothas are not related.
   ``Attempts by ministers to arrange an urgent appointment with
the state president in order to attempt to clear up the matter have
so far been unsuccessful,'' de Klerk said in a statement. ``In the
light of these facts, I am in the process of calling an urgent
meeting of all available National Party ministers for the earliest
opportunity.''
   Botha technically is in charge of the Cabinet, but de Klerk also
has some authority over the ministers because all of them are
National Party members.
   Relations between President Botha and de Klerk have been uneasy
since February, when Botha resigned as National Party leader after
suffering a stroke. Party leaders subsequently threw their support
behind de Klerk.
   Botha last year launched an unprecedented diplomatic initiative
into black Africa, holding summit meetings with the presidents of
Mozambique, Zaire and the Ivory Coast.
   De Klerk, expected to succeed Botha after parliamentary
elections Sept. 6, has continued the initiative, meeting recently
with Mozambique's President Joaquim Chissano.
   His planned meeting with Kaunda is seen as particularly
significant, since the Zambian is chairman of the Frontline States,
a six-nation group established for the purpose of confronting South
Africa's white rulers.
   Kaunda has led calls for isolation of South Africa until its
policy of apartheid, which bars the black majority from having a
voice in national affairs, is abolished.
   Kuanda's country also is headquarters for the African National
Congress, the main guerrilla group fighting to overthrow the South
African government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
