<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1048EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Namibia-UN     08-11 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-UN,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Official Refutes SWAPO Election Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Nations official today
dismissed claims by the SWAPO movement that South Africa is
planning to rig Namibia's elections by bringing in 100,000 people
to vote.
   SWAPO, the South-West Africa People's Organization, fought a
23-year bush war against South African rule of Namibia and is
favored in November's pre-independence polls.
   But SWAPO's U.N. observer, Hinyangerwa Asheeke, said Thursday
that a ``loophole'' in Namibia's election law allows up to 100,000
South Africans with Namibia ties to vote, and that another 50,000
Angolans belonging to the UNITA rebel movement will be fraudulently
registered.
   South Africa supported UNITA, or the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola, in its battle against Angola's
Marxist government until a regional peace treaty was signed last
year.
   ``We have no evidence to support (SWAPO's) allegations,'' said
Hisham Omayad of Ghana, the United Nations electoral director in
Namibia.
   Omayad said only 1,560 South Africans have registered in Namibia
under a proposed election law that extends voting rights to anyone
who has lived in the territory for the past four years or longer,
regardless of nationality.
   People who were born in Namibia but now live elsewhere also
would be allowed to vote under the proposed law.
   U.N. officials have said previously there is no evidence of
Angolan citizens coming to Namibia to register.
   Voter registration began in early July and ends Sept. 15. More
than 500,000 of the 700,000 people expected to register have done
so, U.N. officials said.
   The election law remains open for public comment and still must
be approved by Martti Ahtisarri, who heads the U.N. operation in
Namibia.
   Omayad also said that people are required to show birth
certificates when they register and SWAPO could challenge in court
any voters they believe were registered fraudulently.
   Thousands of South Africans have served in Namibia over the
years as soldiers or civil servants. But most have left and only a
fraction of those remaining meet the four-year residency
requirement.
   Asheeke suggested SWAPO would not recognize the results of an
election that is not ``free and fair.''
   ``We are forewarning the international community to a very
dangerous situation,'' he said.
   ``Pretoria proceeded with enacting this election law, obviously
with the connivance of (Ahtisaari)'' said Asheeke, apparently
unaware that Ahtisaari has yet to rule on the proposed legislation.
   African nations called for the U.N. Security Council to meet
Monday to discuss ``the deteriorating situation in Namibia.''
Ghanaian Ambassador J.V. Gbeho made the request in a letter to the
council's president.
   November's election will choose a constituent assembly, which
will write a constitution and organize a government. If SWAPO can
win two-thirds of the vote, it can write the consititution by
itself.
</TEXT>
