<HEAD>Group Threatens to Kill Pope if He Visits Indonesia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 4th, `Whether it...' to ADD Vatican statement.
Pickup 5th pvs, `The letter...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clandestine Islamic fundamentalist
group has threatened to kill Pope John Paul II if he visits
Indonesia, Indonesian authorities and church sources said today.
   The Islamic movement, which calls itself Mujahiddin
Fisabillillah, sent letters to Indonesian authorities and the
apostolic nunciature of the Holy See in Jakarta saying ``there will
be a blood bath'' if the pope comes to Indonesia as planned in
October.
   ``Whether it is a prank or not, we must take all the necessary
precautions,'' said a Roman Catholic Church official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   At the Vatican, the Rev. Giovanni D'Ercole, a Vatican spokesman,
said he had not heard anything about the letter.
   The letter described the committee arranging the pope's visit as
``no more than colonialist dogs during the rule of the Dutch.''
   Indonesia, a former colony of the Netherlands, declared
independence from Dutch rule on Aug. 17, 1945.
   The Vatican ambassador, Francesco Canalini, refused to say
whether he had seen the letter. He said the main purpose of the
pope's visit will be to meet with the country's Catholic faithful.
   About 90 percent of Indonesia's 175 million people are Moslem.
   The pope will be in Indonesia from Oct. 9-14 and is scheduled to
visit Jakarta, Jogjakarta in central Java, Flores in the lesser
Sunda islands, Medan in north Sumatra and the former Portugese
colony of East Timor.
   It will be the first papal visit to the country since Pope Paul
VI visited in 1970.
</TEXT>
