<HEAD>Security Guard Killed In Attack On U.N. Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to ADD that suspect vehicle was stopped but
sped away. Pickup 6th graf pvs, `U.N. officials...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HEIDI VON EGIDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers armed with grenades and a
machine gun damaged two U.N. buildings and killed a black Namibian
security guard, police and U.N. officials said today.
   The Thursday night attacks occurred at U.N. posts in Outjo, a
town 210 miles north of Windhoek, police said.
   ``I expect all Namibians to unite in the condemnation of such
acts and to reaffirm their commitment to a peaceful transition to
independence,'' said Martti Ahtisaari, who heads the U.N.
monitoring team overseeing the territory's independence process.
   The attackers threw two grenades into an office, killing a
22-year-old Namibian working for a private security firm and
setting fire to the building, police said. U.N. spokesman Fred
Eckhard said it appeared a machine gun also was used.
   Two white men and one black man were suspected of carrying out
the attack, police said.
   The alleged getaway vehicle was stopped at a police roadblock,
and crudely painted U.N. initials were noticed on the sides, but
the vehicle sped away, said Gerhard Roux, a spokesman for the
territorial administrator, Louis Pienaar.
   U.N. officials reported a second attack at a nearby U.N.
military base where arms are stored. There was minimal damage to
the building, and no injuries, the officials said.
   South Africa, which has ruled Namibia for 74 years, agreed to
grant independence to Africa's last colony under a regional peace
accord signed in December. More than 6,000 U.N. military and
civilian personnel are monitoring the year-long process.
   Despite various problems, the plan is on schedule, according to
U.N. officials. Elections are set for November and independence is
expected early next year.
</TEXT>
