<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Narcotics 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Narcotics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0549,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israelis Nab Suspected Lebanese Drug Runner Across Border</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs of background on Israeli drug problem.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special cross-border police unit nabbed a
Lebanese man accused of being a drug kingpin and whisked him to
Israel, officials said today.
   Thursday night's operation came exactly two weeks after Israeli
commandos abducted a Shiite Moslem clergyman in south Lebanon and
flew him to Israel.
   The capture of Mohammed Berro appeared unrelated to Obeid's
kidnapping, which was aimed at arranging a prisoner swap.
   Department Chief Rami Zutler of the Severe Crimes Division told
a Tel Aviv court today that Berro is ``one of the biggest'' drug
dealers in Lebanon, the national news agency Itim said.
   The court remanded Berro in custody for 15 days, it said.
   When asked by the judge how Berro, 46, had arrived in Israel
from Lebanon, Zutler replied that the police had ``transferred''
him.
   Zutler alleged that Berro was responsible for smuggling 46.2
pounds of heroin seized last week in Israel's biggest drug bust.
   Zutler also said Berro was wanted by Egypt for drug smuggling.
   Reports from Egypt said that in June, Berro was sentenced in
absentia to death for attempting to smuggle 4.1 tons of opium, 1.8
tons of hashish, and 635 pounds of heroin into Egypt.
   Security sources in Lebanon said Israeli civilian police have
been operating in Israel's self-declared security zone in southern
Lebanon for at least six months.
   Police spokeswoman Ruth Schlesinger said a joint police and
military unit is conducting anti-smuggling operations along
Israel's northern border and in the security zone.
   The zone was carved out by Israel in 1985, after it pulled the
majority of its troops out of Lebanon following the 1982 invasion.
The zone is patrolled by about 1,500 Israeli troops backed by
Israel's militia allies.
   There are approximately 5,000 drug addicts receiving treatment
in Israel, but there are no accurate figures on the numbers of drug
users in the country. The supply of drugs coming in from Lebanon
has risen sharply in recent years.
   Until 1978, drug usage in Israel was confined to hashish,
traditionally smuggled from Lebanon. But in 1982, Lebanese dealers
began to produce heroin and Israeli drug dealers began distributing
it.
   The contact was made easier after Israel's invasion of Lebanon.
</TEXT>
