<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Germany-Flights     08-11 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Germany-Flights,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Carrier Begins First Service to West Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUESSELDORF, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East German Interflug jet
arrived Friday in this West German business center, completing the
first exchange of commerical flights in the 40 years since the
nation was divided.
   Heinz Ruhnau, head of West Germany's Lufthansa airline that
inaugurated a Frankfurt-to-Leipzig service Thursday, deemed the new
routes ``a step toward normality.''
   But despite the new services aimed at shuttling passengers from
both sides among the major business cities, a remnant of the Cold
War continues to encumber both national carriers: Neither Lufthansa
nor Interflug is allowed to fly over the border between the
countries, so they must detour to the south and fly through
Czechoslovak airspace.
   Under a post-World War II agreement among the Western allies,
only France, Britain and the United States are allowed to provide
air service between West Germany and West Berlin, and they must
travel along three closely prescribed routes.
</TEXT>
