<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--PotatoProtest     08-11 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Potato Protest,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activists Uproot Government Potato Field</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAGENINGEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group calling itself ``The
Seething Spuds'' Friday claimed responsibility for destroying 400
genetically altered potato plants that are part of a research
project, police said.
   The protest caused a delay of at least one year in research at
the Agriculture Ministry's ITAL institute, which planted the
potatoes in June, said institute spokesman Willem Stiekema.
   The potato plants were ripped out of the ground tossed on a heap
early Thursday, according to police spokesman H. Martin. No arrests
were made.
   In a letter to the Dutch national news agency, the group said
the protest was aimed at using genetic manipulation to make
potatoes more resistant to herbicides.
   Stiekema confirmed that one group of potatoes was involved in
such an experiment, adding that another batch had been genetically
manipulated to resist a common potato virus.
   ``In a third type, we implanted two (manipulated) gens that we
reseachers can play around with a little,'' Stiekma said.
   ITAL is one of several biotechnological research institutes in
this central Dutch city.
</TEXT>
