<FIRST>u w PM-CentralNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru a0441 08-11 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chain Affiliated With Quayle Family Goes Public</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Neither the, to delete incorrect reference to
Quayle's membership on board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central Newspapers Inc., the newspaper chain
owned by Vice President Dan Quayle's family, is going public with
an initial offering of more than 3.5 million shares of common stock.
   The Indianapolis-based company, founded by Quayle's grandfather,
publishes papers in Arizona and Indiana, according to Thursday's
filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Neither the vice president nor his wife, Marilyn, was listed in
the SEC filing as a selling shareholder.
   Existing shareholders who are selling some of their stock
include Quayle's mother, Corinne Pulliam Quayle, and Huntington
Newspapers Inc., which puts out the Huntington Herald-Press, a
northern Indiana daily published by the vice president's father,
James C. Quayle.
   The company won't receive any of the proceeds from the stock
offering.
   Phoenix Newspapers Inc., a wholly owned subsidiary, publishes
The Arizona Republic and The Phoenix Gazette. A 70 percent-owned
subsidiary, Indianapolis Newspapers Inc., publishes The
Indianapolis Star and The Indianapolis News.
   Central Newspapers also publishes three smaller papers in
Muncie, Ind., and Vincennes, Ind., and a business weekly in Arizona.
   The stock offering consists of 3 million shares of Class A
common stock to be sold in the United States and 592,800 shares of
Class A to be offered outside the country.
   After the stock sale, Central Newspapers outstanding stock will
consist of 23.16 million shares of Class A common stock and 33.27
million shares of Class B common stock.
   Each Class A common stock share has 10 times the dividend and
liquidation rights of Class B common shares. However, Class B
shares have 10 times the voting power of Class A.
   All the Class B shares will be retained by current shareholders,
including the Eugene C. Pulliam Trust, which holds 68.85 percent of
the stock. The trust is named for Quayle's grandfather, who died in
1975.
   Holders of Class A shares were reducing their holdings by only a
fraction.
   DePauw University, Quayle's alma mater, will sell only 181,818
of its 300,000 shares. Quayle's mother will sell just 36,363 of her
659,600 shares, according to documents filed with the SEC.
   The offering was approved late last month by shareholders as
part of a recapitalization plan. The Eugene C. Pulliam Trust, which
has had voting control since 1965, permitted the plan as long as it
retains at least 53.77 percent voting power.
   Pulliam, the vice president's grandfather, was publisher of the
two Indianapolis papers. His son, Eugene S. Pulliam, Quayle's
uncle, is the current publisher.
   Central Newspapers reported net income of about $29 million last
year on revenues of nearly $418 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
