<FIRST>u a PM-FloodsRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 08-11 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Floods Rdp, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Storms Cause Aqueduct To Overflow, Force Evacuations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with details of Yellowstone slides,
forecast for more possible today, Yuma damage. Picks up 9th graf, `Damage
also...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE M. PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms crossing from California into Nevada today left
homes flooded, mudslides imperiled Yellowstone visitors and
Arizona's governor toured areas of Yuma where ``there were lakes
where cars had been.''
   Widely scattered downpours Wednesday and Thursday deluged areas
from San Diego to Las Vegas. The aqueduct supplying most of Los
Angeles' water overflowed. Some roads and highways in the eastern
Sierra Nevada range, where deputies rescued several motorists from
high water, remained closed today.
   Heavy rain and hail at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., caused
three major mudslides and 12 smaller ones that mired 30 vehicles in
waist-deep mud and swept one family inside of a camper into a
raging river Thursday evening.
   ``It was a matter of seconds, virtually seconds, and that
vehicle would have gone under,'' said park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo
after talking to a park ranger who rescued the family visiting from
Mexico.
   No one was injured, but Paul Lauze, a meteorologist for the
National Weather Service in Cheyenne, cautioned that there could be
more slides today. ``Everybody watch out. It's going to be the same
thing,'' he said.
   ``The problem is aggravated in Yellowstone National Park because
of the exposed terrain as the result of the forest fires last
year,'' he said.
   Arizona Gov. Rose Mofford declared Yuma County a disaster area
Thursday after touring areas where homes were flooded by up to 4
feet of water from a storm Wednesday night. The desert town got
more rain in an evening _ about 3{ inches _ than it normally gets
in a year.
   ``There were lakes where cars had been, and you could tell that
businesses were wiped out,'' Mrs. Mofford said.
   Police threatened to ticket sightseers who drove through
floodwaters, creating waves that washed into homes and businesses.
   Police spokesman Jan Schmidt estimated 1,000 homes were damaged,
but said there were no estimates of monetary losses this morning.
   ``People are still digging out to figure out what got ruined,''
he said. ``We have homes that had four feet of water in them. I
know one man who had a swimming pool seven feet deep that was
covered with sand. He was standing on top of it; it was filled in.''
   He said the National Weather Service reading of 3.5 inches of
rain on a mesa overlooking the city was conservative.
   ``Down in the valley, they had about 5.6 inches in 2{ hours,''
Schmidt said.
   ``On the south side of town, they lost just about all the water
pressure because the water eroded away the areas, and what was left
fell down and crushed the pipes,'' Schmidt said.
   Damage also was reported at the Yuma Marine Corps Air Station,
in the desert just southeast of California, where 2,000 gallons of
firefighting foam leaked during the storm. ``It was like a washing
machine gone wild,'' Gunnery Sgt. Hal Wheeler said.
   In Mono County, Calif., between Yosemite National Park and the
Nevada line, about 150 residents were evacuated Thursday, and at
least 28 homes suffered moderate to severe water damage, Sheriff
Marty Strelneck said.
   A one-mile section of the Los Angeles Aqueduct that had been
closed because of previous flooding filled with rain again and
overflowed, forcing a cleanup crew of 30 to evacuate, officials
said.
   The section runs near the towns of Olancha and Cartago, 180
miles north of Los Angeles.
   The aqueduct supplies 75 percent of Los Angeles' water, but
reservoirs in the area have enough water to prevent a shortage in
Los Angeles, said Dorothy Jensen, spokeswoman for the Los Angeles
city water department.
</TEXT>
