<FIRST>r i AM-ShipSurvivors     08-11 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ship Survivors,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Fishermen Survive 24-Day Ordeal Afloat on High Seas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten Chinese fishermen survived a 24-day ordeal
aboard tiny, typhoon-tossed sampans by eating cardboard and
drinking rainwater, but 14 others perished, a report appearing
Friday said.
   On Wednesday, the survivors sailed into the southern Chinese
port of Zhuhai adjacent to the Portuguese enclave of Macao about 40
miles southwest of this British colony, the official China News
Service reported.
   According to the news service, the ordeal began July 17 when the
Maowan No. 1, a fishing vessel from Taishan in southern China,
caught fire in the vicinity of the Paracel islands, also known as
the Xisha islands, about 450 miles south of Hong Kong.
   The 24 crewmen had to abandon ship and board two small sampans.
They had no food but ate cardboard television packing cartons that
were in the vessels. They drank sea water and rainwater.
   A surviving fishermen said he ate a small piece of packing
carton and three mouthfuls of rainwater, the news agency said in
its report from Zhuhai.
   Fourteen men died of hunger, exposure and heat as the sampans
were buffeted by four typhoons in the South China Sea, the report
said. The last casualty was the captain, who died on the 18th day.
   One survivor said that on the 22nd day, the fishermen arrived at
the Pratas islands, also known as the Dongsha islands, about 170
miles west of Hong Kong. Taiwan soldiers occupying the island gave
the Chinese candy and canned food.
   The survivors are undergoing treatment at Zhuhai City People's
Hospital for exhaustion but are out of danger, the report said.
</TEXT>
