<SECOND>AM-BRF--France-Trains,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm Knocks Out Power To Trains, Stranding 12,000 Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOULON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm knocked out power to the rail line
along France's Mediterranean coast, stranding about 12,000
passengers overnight, railroad officials said Friday.
   Trains began running again about 9 a.m. Friday, more than 12
hours after the storm interrupted service.
   The national railroad apologized for the problem and invited
inconvenienced customers to apply for refunds or replacement
tickets.
   Transport Minister Michel Delebarre said he would ask the
railroad to explain what went wrong and to propose ways that
travelers could be better informed in such cases.
   Passengers complained on French radio that they were were told
the trains could start again at any minute, but ended up waiting
all night. Some eventually took buses, called taxis or walked to
nearby highways to hitch rides.
