<FIRST>u w PM-LelandVigil     08-11 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland Vigil,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman's Spokeswoman Rap Rescue Effort</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Ethiopia-Leland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A frustrated spokeswoman for Rep. Mickey
Leland said today she wasn't satisfied with the ``sense of
urgency'' involved in the search for her boss and others missing
since Monday in Ethiopia.
   President Bush and the State Department said they understood the
worried mood of the Texas congressman's staff and defended the
rescue effort.
   Leland's press secretary, Alma Newsom, said that with all of
sophisticated equipment dispatched to Ethiopia to search for the
congressman's missing plane and his traveling party, ``we could
have and should have located them by now.''
   ``I certainly had a great deal more confidence in our
capability,'' she said. Leland's plane, which also carried several
congressional staff members and State Department employees,
vanished Monday after taking off from Addis Ababa for a refugee
camp 480 miles away.
   Leland, D-Texas, chairs the House Select Committee on Hunger and
has been a leader in congressional efforts to aid people displaced
by war and famine in Africa.
   Ms. Newsom said she was appealing to Bush to get involved, ``and
to issue a strong statement to all of his people, that this is a
priority, they've got to work together and they have got to get
their act together and find Congressman Leland and his party.''
   The president, asked about the subject at a photo session in the
Oval Office said:
   ``I can understand the anxiety of all this and I can understand
the concern that people that love Mickey Leland feel and that I
feel. But there's a lot going on, so let's just hope and pray he's
OK.''
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said ``I
know the president and the secretary of state deeply and sincerely
empathize with the frustration, with the tension, with the
situation (Ms. Newsom is) having to deal with ....''
   Ms. Newsom said, ``I think there has been a problem of
communication. I think there has been a problem of somehow, the
sense of urgency from the top has not filtered considerably as it
went down.''
   ``There's an obvious leadership or organizational vacuum here,
... there's a missing link,'' she said.
   Ms. Tutwiler also denied there had been any breakdown in the
search effort.
   Rep. Alan Wheat, D-Mo., one of two congressmen sent to Ethiopia
by House Speaker Thomas Foley, was briefed on the situation
Thursday, and Ms. Newsom said there was a ``general acknowledgment
that more facilities were needed, that more aircraft were needed,
that more helicopters were needed. That particularly more personnel
were needed. That there were fliers needed, pilots needed to spell
the ones that are there.''
   Ms. Newsom said she and others in Leland's office had spent the
night calling on other congressmen to urge the Pentagon to move
more quickly on the rescue effort, saying time was of the essence
and that there had been ``a lot of missteps'' and misstatements.
</TEXT>
