<FIRST>r a PM-HighwayShooting     08-11 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Highway Shooting,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen Injured in Shooting Was to Be Witness in Drug Case; Boy's Mother
Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OPAL, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was killed with gunfire from a passing
vehicle as she took her 17-year-old son to testify at a
drug-related court hearing, police said.
   The prosecutor said he had hoped the teen-ager, who was wounded
in the attack, would testify in juvenile court against two
Washington, D.C., men charged with contributing to the delinquency
of a minor by encouraging cocaine distrubution. The youth is also
charged in the case.
   Anne Louise Gordon, 32, of Washington, D.C., died at the scene
from a single gunshot wound to the head after Thursday morning's
shooting, police said.
   Her 17-year-old son was shot in the neck and was reported in
fair condition at Fauquier Hospital in Warrenton. A second
passenger in the car, a 13-year-old boy, was not hurt.
   The shooting occurred on U.S. 29 about one-half mile south of
here, said state police spokewoman Lucy Caldwell.
   Ms. Caldwell said Ms. Gordon, en route to Charlottesville, was
driving south when a car passed her and one or more shots were
fired from a handgun.
   The injured teen and a second youth faced charges, along with
the two men, Gary Hinkle and Wilson Emory Smith, both 29, stemming
from an incident in which Albermarle police stopped the four May 3
and confiscated small amounts of cocaine and more than $4,300 cash.
   Ford Childress, assistant Albermarle commonwealth's attorney,
said Thursday that he believed that when the group was stopped,
``they'd sold their drugs and were on their way out of town. All
they had left was cash.''
   Childress said he thought the juveniles' statements to police
were enough to convict the two adults and he planned to call the
youths as key witnesses against them on the delinquency charges.
Childress said because of the age of the two juveniles, he could
not reveal what charges they themselves face.
   After the shooting, Hinkle and Smith were questioned Thursday by
state police and released.
   Smith's attorney, Francis Lawrence, said his client voluntarily
underwent a test to determine whether he had recently fired a
firearm and Smith allowed police to search his car.
