<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru   08-11 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0571,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede PANAMA CITY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panama Asks U.N. For Military Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with demand for U.N. military observers.
No pickup. ^By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's foreign minister today asked the
Security Council to send military observers to his country to
prevent the U.S. Army from instigating confrontations as a pretext
for armed intervention.
   Jorge Ritter said U.S. forces have been leaving their bases for
months to harass Panamanian citizens and ``the Republic of Panama
became, de facto, an invasion site in which only the order to fire
is lacking.''
   ``What the situation in Panama calls for is the presence of
military observers, which we hope would be able to go as early as
next Monday.
   ``The testimony of observers, to be designated, will insure that
the reality of the situation cannot be hidden and it will be
recorded in the annals of history as a crime,'' said Ritter.
   The United States, as a permanent member of the Security
Council, would be able to veto any council resolution to send
military observers to Pamama.
   Panama did not have any nation on the council introduce a
resolution, which would be required to send observers.
   In Panama, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on Thursday said his
regime will not yield to U.S. pressure that he quit as Panama's
Defense Forces chief.
   ``Panama will not bow to the law of force that those barbarians
from the North, their lackeys and tame politicians are trying to
impose on it,'' he said Thursday night, referring to his Panamanian
opponents.
   The comments were Noriega's first reaction to a week of
confrontations between his forces and U.S. Southern Command troops
that included arrests on both sides and the blocking of nearby Fort
Amador by American soldiers.
   U.S. troops have been conducting exercises to defend the Panama
Canal under the 1977 treaties, and Noriega's troops in some cases
have been shadowing them.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today
that the recent exercises were routine manuvers, but he
acknowledged they were to some degree a show of force.
   ``We have always said that we would feel free to carry out
exercises in support of our rights under the Panama Canal treaty
... from time to time we do conduct those kind of exercises,'' he
said. ``They're all designed to ensure our rights and acess to
protect the canal.''
   Addressing a group of 20 retired military officers, Noriega
reiterated earlier accusations the United States wants to replace
him with a ``docile'' government to elude treaty obligations to
turn the Panama Canal over to Panama.
   ``You,'' Noriega said pointing at the retired officers, ``are
front-row witnesses of the aggressive and arrogant policies of the
United States towards Panama.'' But he said Panama ``will not bow,
will not humiliate itself, will not give up its project of
liberating itself (of American soldiers) in the face of injustice
or arrogance.''
   The group of officers, believed to have been founded recently by
Noriega, calls itself the executive committee of the Organization
of Military Men for Democracy, Integration and the Liberation of
Latin American and the Caribbean.
   The Bush administration and opposition politicians have been
trying to force out Noriega since two federal grand juries in
Florida indicted him on drug trafficking and money laundering
charges last year.
   U.S efforts have included diplomatic pressure and trade and
economic sanctions against Panama. But the steps have yet to budge
Noriega, whose regime annulled May 7 presidential elections.
International observers said opposition candidate Guillermo Endara
won by a landslide.
</TEXT>
