<FIRST>r a AM-PostalDrugs     08-11 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Postal Drugs,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter Carrier Doubled As Drug Dealer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter carrier has pleaded guilty to drug
charges after admitting he took telephone orders at the post office
and delivered cocaine to some customers along his route.
   Isaiah Millings, 33, pleaded guilty Thursday to six drug-related
counts in exchange for a two-year prison sentence.
   Postal inspectors and police secretly filmed Millings as he sold
cocaine while delivering mail and as he transported the drug on
other occasions using his official Postal Service vehicle.
   Police and post inspectors also taped Millings taking cocaine
orders over the telephone at the post office.
   Millings' supplier, Antonio F. Brown, 49, also pleaded guilty
and was sentenced to 10 years in prison. Brown, a native of Panama
who entered the United States illegally, has a long criminal record
and was wanted by police in South Carolina for escape.
   Baltimore Circuit Court Judge Elsbeth Levy Bothe and Assistant
State's Attorney Jill Myers said Brown was eligible for a 25-year
sentence without the possibility of parole because of his criminal
history.
   ``As one of the taxpayers of the state of Maryland, I don't want
to support him for the next 25 years,'' Bothe said. ``It's the only
reason I'm willing to not impose the 25 years he so richly
deserves.''
   Myers said after Brown serves his prison time in this country,
he probably will be returned to Panama.
   Postal employees who have drug problems are encouraged to take
advantage of free programs offered by the Postal Service, postal
inspector Jeff L. Fry said.
</TEXT>
