<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Irish     08-11 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forces on Full Alert Before 20th Anniversary Marches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces went on full
alert throughout Northern Ireland on Friday before weekend marches
to mark the 20th anniversary of the deployment of British troops in
the province.
   The army and police said they feared the Irish Republican Army
would attempt a terror offensive to mark the occasion.
   Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad on Thursday urged the
public to be particularly vigilant on the British mainland.
   Belfast's mayor, Tony Carlin, said, ``I am sure I am speaking
for everyone in the city when I say that the main concern over the
weekend must be the preservation of peace and calm,'' Carlin said.
   At 5 p.m. on Aug. 14, 1969, 400 soldiers of the Prince of Wales
Own Regiment entered Londonderry, the first soldiers sent in to try
to control sectarian fighting between Protestant and Roman Catholic
extremists.
   The IRA has waged a bloody campaign, primarily in Northern
Ireland, to drive the British out of the predominantly Protestant
province and unite it with the mainly Catholic Irish Republic. So
far, 2,742 people have been killed in the conflict.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Brooke pledged to keep troops
in Ulster ``as long as they were needed.''
   In a radio interview, he said to the IRA: ``You cannot win.''
   The government wanted to continue to work toward a devolution of
power to the province, he said.
   As many as 1,000 mourners, meanwhile, attended the funeral of
Seamus Duffy, a 15-year-old boy killed by a plastic bullet early
Wednesday as he walked home from watching bonfires marking the 18th
anniversary of the start of the British policy of interning
suspected terrorists without trial. The policy was modified in the
following years and the last detainees were released in 1975.
   More than 120 people were evacuated from their homes in the
County Antrim resort of Portrush on Friday after a suspected
booby-trap bomb was found under a policeman's car. An army bomb
disposal expert safely exploded the bomb.
   Police arrested an unspecified number of men in Catholic areas
of Londonderry overnight and took them to an interrogation center
in Belfast for questioning.
   Extra police and troops were being assigned to Londonderry for
Saturday's annual Protestant loyalist Apprentice Boys' parade
marking the 300th anniversary of the Siege of Derry. More than
15,000 Protestant marchers were expected to take part.
   Thirteen apprentice boys slammed the gates of Londonderry on the
army of King James II at the start of the siege in 1689.
   Extra security was planned Sunday when thousands of Catholics
were to take to the streets in Belfast's Falls Road to mark the
internment and troops anniversaries. That march was expected to be
one of the largest in the area in years.
   On Monday night, Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the IRA, is to lead 5,000 supporters through the
city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
