<FIRST>r a PM-FireDeaths 2ndLd-Writethru a0582 08-11 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fire Deaths, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0582,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Kills Parents, Three Children Despite Neighbors' Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT mother's name to Marylin sted Marilyn,
daughter to Lori sted Lauri.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY NACHTIGAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOTTS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire swept through a wood-frame house
early today, killing a family of five as neighbors frantically
pounded on doors and honked car horns to alert them, authorities
said.
   The victims were Bill Fullerton, 51; his wife, Marylin
Fullerton, 42; and their children, Lori, 14; Justin, 10, and
Curtis, 3, according to the Lawrence County Sheriff's Department.
   The fire broke out about 1:30 a.m. in the garage and spread
quickly, leaving the single-story home in ashes with only a
concrete kitchen wall standing.
   The cause was unknown, said Bill Farr, an investigator for the
state fire marshal's office.
   Residents who live near the house in Stotts City, a southwestern
Missouri community of some 200 residents, noticed the flames and
tried to alert the family by pounding on doors and blowing car
horns.
   Beatrice Weaver, a neighbor, said her husband noticed the house
was on fire and tried to rescue the family.
   ``He jumped into his clothes, grabbed a fire extinguisher and
ran across the street,'' she said. ``But before he got across the
street the whole inside of the house lit up. He pounded on the
house and hollered but he couldn't get inside.''
   The body of one of the children was found in a hallway and
another child was found lying on the floor next to a bed,
indicating they had tried to flee, Farr said.
   Authorities said four bodies were recovered after the fire was
extinguished. The fifth body was found in the rubble shortly after
dawn, according to the Lawrence County sheriff's office.
   Fullerton, a construction crane operator, was described as a
friendly man who enjoyed gardening.
   ``He was generous as could be,'' said a friend, Gene Smith. ``He
would give away vegetables from his garden to all of the
neighbors.''
</TEXT>
