<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-KillingFields     08-11 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Killing Fields,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodians Flock To `The Killing Fields'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Cambodians have thronged
to see ``The Killing Fields,'' the film that brought to Western
screens the horror of life under the Khmer Rouge, since it
premiered in Phnom Penh this month.
   Richard Walden, head of the U.S. relief agency Operation
California that arranged the screening, said Friday that a day
after the Aug. 4 premiere a crowd of up to 5,000 people jostled for
tickets at one of the capital's four movie theaters.
   ``There was literally a human sea trying to get tickets, there
was almost a riot to get in,'' Walden said in an interview in
Bangkok.
   Walden led a delegation including the film's British director
Roland Joffe and the principal character, U.S. journalist Sydney
Schanberg, to Phnom Penh for the screening. The delegation was
invited by Cambodian Premier Hun Sen.
   The film has been available in Cambodia for some time on
videotape, but only this month were audiences able to view it in
theaters.
   ``The Killing Fields'' tells the story of how Schanberg and his
Cambodian assistant, Dith Pran, were separated as the Khmer Rouge
entered Phnom Penh in 1975 to begin their murderous rule. The
radical Communist faction killed hundreds of thousands of
Cambodians between 1975 and 1978.
   Schanberg and Dith eventually were reunited, but only after Dith
made a hazardous trek to Thailand though rice fields filled with
the bones of the Khmer Rouge's victims.
   Walden said the Cambodian audience appeared thrilled to see
Cambodian actor Haing Ngor, who won an Academy Award for best
supporting actor for his portrayal of Dith, alongside Western stars.
   But many broke down in tears whan asked about their experiences
later, he said. The reaction of many in the audience was ```that is
all true, that is what it was like for my family,''' he said.
   Many said life under the Khmer Rouge was even worse than that
portrayed in the movie, Walden said.
   ``There was an incredible response especially in scenes which
showed the Khmer Rouge, which showed people marching out of Phnom
Penh or working in the rural areas,'' Walden said.
   He said the present government plans to continue showing the
film, hopefully outside the capital as well.
   On April 17, 1975 when the Khmer Rouge entered Phnom Penh, they
ordered the population of 2 million out of the city to work under
slavish conditions in the countryside.
   The capital was a ghost town for 3{ years while the Khmer Rouge
attempted to build a radical agrarian utopia.
   Although ousted by a Vietnamese invasion in 1978, the Khmer
Rouge still survives with its leadership structure intact. Backed
by China, it is currently the largest of three guerrilla groups
fighting the Cambodian government from bases on the Thai border.
   In recent peace talks Hun Sen's government has insisted that the
Khmer Rouge should not be allowed a role in the future of Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
