<DOCNO> AP890811-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1448EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Spies     08-11 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Spies,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Remorse, Not Trickery, Elicited Spying Confession</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Michigan man convicted of spying for the
CIA confessed to atone for harm he did Egypt, not because he was
tricked or frightened, the judge in the case said.
   The security court that convicted Samy Wassef ``found no
evidence of physical or moral factors as claimed'' involved with
the confession, Sayeed Mahmoud Sayed wrote in explaining his
court's July 20 decision. The document was released Thursday.
   Wassef, 26, has said interrogators used photographs purporting
to show torture scenes to persuade him to sign the confession. He
told his mother, who is pressing U.S. and Egyptian authorities for
her son's freedom, that he was told his bags were packed and an air
ticket home awaited him if he signed it.
   Because no witnesses were presented at the 90-minute trial,
Wassef's 253-page confession was the main evidence on which he, his
30-year-old brother, Samir, and another American, Nicholas Edward
Reynolds, were convicted.
   Both Wassef brothers, whose family lives in Detroit, were
sentenced to 10-year prison terms and fined the equivalent of
$3,850. Reynolds was sentenced to five years and a fine of about
$1,925.
   Only Samy Wassef is in prison. The other two had left the
country before he was arrested.
   Prosecutors claimed Reynolds was the Central Intelligence Agency
paymaster for the Wassefs. They said the brothers were trained in
spy techniques and sold Reynolds information he could not have
obtained from newspapers.
   ``The court is satisfied with the evidence of guilt and with the
accuracy of (the) confession,'' Judge Sayed wrote on behalf of his
three-man tribunal. ``The verdict was comfortable and convincing.''
   His document explaining the verdict said the court was convinced
Samy Wassef signed the confession solely ``because he wanted to
repent, wanted to atone, resented what he had committed in regard
to Egypt.''
   Mrs. Wassef's efforts got another setback after Sayed issued his
explanatory statement. She said her son's lawyer, Hassan Ibrashy,
whose name she obtained from a list of lawyers supplied by the U.S.
Embassy, withdrew from the case without explanation.
   Repeated telephone calls to Ibrashy's home were unanswered.
   Security agents arrested Wassef on Nov. 14, and he signed the
confession a few days before his first visit by a U.S. consular
officer Dec. 8. He was held eight months before charges were filed
in early July.
   The explanatory document Sayed released Thursday is the final
step before the case can be appealed to the Court of Cassations,
Egypt's highest tribunal. The only recourse from that court's
review is the president, Hosni Mubarak.
   Mrs. Wassef said she will would find a new lawyer and appeal
before the Aug. 29 deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
