<DOCNO> AP890811-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BiotechnologyLaw     08-11 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Biotechnology Law,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compromise Law Pleases Biotech Companies, Some Environmentalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new state law regulating the use of
genetically altered plants and animals strikes a balance between
protecting the public and letting companies test new technology,
some environmentalists say.
   At a news conference Thursday in Washington, a coalition of
biotechnology companies and environmentalists praised the law as a
national model, and said it will boost North Carolina's role in
biotechnology, the search for better, hardier plants and animals.
   ``Citizens can be informed participants in the
decision-making,'' said Rebecca Goldburg of the Environmental
Defense Fund.
   But Andrew Kimbrell, a lawyer for a group that opposes field
testing of genetically engineered organisms, denounced the law,
especially the provision that prevents local authorities from
banning experiments.
   ``They're playing ecological roulette with communities,'' he
said, because the full impact of new organisms is unknown.
   Kimbrell's group, the Foundation on Economic Trends, is headed
by Jeremy Rifkin, a prominent critic of biotechnology.
   The law was enacted by the Legislature on Wednesday as part of
budget legislation. It establishes a 10-member state board that
will review applications by companies to take genetically altered
plants and animals out of the laboratory and into the field.
   The board can require public hearings before granting such
permits and can decide what information is made public. That
provision is intended to make sure any potential adverse effects of
a test are not kept secret under the pretense of being confidential
business information, said Gerry Hancock, a Durham lawyer and
former chairman of the quasi-public N.C. Biotechnology Center.
</TEXT>
