<FIRST>r a AM-StolenHorse     08-11 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stolen Horse,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thieves Make Off With Statue of Tom Mix's Horse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLORENCE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Tom Mix were still here he'd know how
to handle the low-down varmints who stole his favorite horse.
   A statue of Tony the Wonder Horse, the late cowboy movie star's
favorite steed, has been stolen from his place of honor at the Tom
Mix memorial near here, Pinal County authorities said Thursday.
   Sheriff's Sgt. Melvin Moore said deputies know only that the
metal statue is gone. They don't know when it was stolen, who took
it, or why.
   ``The horse was on top of the Tom Mix monument out there, and it
seemed like someone just pushed it backwards and forwards until it
broke off,'' Moore said. ``It looks like they took it with them
because we couldn't find it out there.''
   The Mix memorial was built in 1947 at a site along the
Tucson-Florence highway where the silent-screen cowboy died at the
age of 60 in a 1940 traffic accident.
   The monument, which included a bronze plaque, was topped by an
iron statue of a horse with its head lowered and its saddle empty.
   That original statue, donated by the Florence Chamber of
Commerce, was stolen in the spring of 1980. It was never found.
   The county Historical Society replaced the statue five years ago
with help from inmates at the Arizona State Prison in Florence,
society spokeswoman Billy Earley said.
   ``And now the new statue has been the private research group, the Game
Conservancy.
   ``During the season, which lasts until December, people who
usually stage 10 days of shootings will probably hold two or
three,'' he said.
   ``A large amount of shooting is being canceled,'' agreed Charles
Orssich of Roxton Sporting Agency Ltd., which organizes shoots on
the grouse moors, most of which are privately owned.
   But he said demand was still high from ``English, American,
French, German, all sorts of people from all walks of life'' who
can afford the $1,100 to $1,600 a day it costs to shoot.
   Traditionally, the Glorious Twelfth was highlighted by a race to
whisk the first game from the moors and serve it piping hot on the
table.
   ``People would try to serve it for breakfast. They'd be out on
the moors in Formula One racing cars,'' said Pamela Crawford,
spokeswoman for the prestigious Gleneagles Hotel in eastern
Scotland, a former grouse-serving contender.
   But a combination of ecological awareness and hunt protesters
who make pre-dawn attacks to drive off the birds has toned down the
presentation.
   ``We used to celebrate the Glorious Twelfth, but for the fifth
year running, we're giving the money we normally spend on the race
to the Scottish Grouse Research Project Appeal,'' said Ms.
Crawford. ``The only guns at the hotel tomorrow will be fired at
clay pigeons.''
   Still, people will be able to eat a traditional Twelfth meal at
the 65-year-old hotel. ``I'm sure grouse will be on the menu,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
