<FIRST>r w AM-US-Syria     08-11 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Syria,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Condemns Syrian Role In Beirut Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday took the
unusual step of singling out Syria for its role in the latest
outburst of fighting in Beirut.
   The criticism came as U.S. officials continued to seek Syrian
help in obtaining the release of eight American hostages held by
pro-Iranian militants in Lebanon.
   ``The United States condemns the indiscriminate slaughter of
innocent people and the renewed use of heavy caliber weapons, such
as the 240-millimeter mortar, which are in the Syrian arsenal,''
said State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler.
   ``We again call upon Syria, an active participant in the
fighting, the Lebanese armed forces, as well as the various
Lebanese factions, for an immediate cease-fire, the lifting of all
blockades, and the initiation of a dialogue for the political
reconstruction of Lebanon,'' she added.
   The State Department has in the past generally refrained from
singling out the combatants by name, preferring to call for
restraint by all sides.
   The latest round of fighting in the five-month artillery war
over control of Beirut came on Friday, when Syrian and Christian
gunners dueled with howitzers and rocket launchers, killing six
people. The fighting followed 15 hours of fierce fighting Thursday
that escalated sharply when Syrian gunners targeted the
presidential palace with 240mm mortars.
   ``The escalation and the shellings and the dramatic increase in
casualties give urgent impetus to our call for the Arab League to
overcome the obstructions facing it and resume its efforts on
behalf of the people of Lebanon,'' Tutwiler said.
   Several weeks of mediation efforts by leaders of the 21-nation
Arab League have failed to bring about a lasting cease-fire.
   Tutwiler said the United States, through its embassy in
Damascus, approached the Syrian government about the hostages. The
approach came after a group of kidnappers claimed last week to have
hanged Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins and the State Department
sought to determine his fate.
   ``We have continued our contacts to try to assure that Syria
will do everything possible to assist in a successful resolution to
the hostage crisis,'' she said.
   U.S. policy toward Syria treads a delicate balance of criticism
of the Soviet-backed government for its support of Palestinian and
Shiite terrorism and seeking to enlist its support for the
Arab-Israeli peace process and other negotiations in the volatile
region.
</TEXT>
