<FIRST>r w AM-US-Panama     08-11 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush `Would Not Rule Out' Seizing Panama's Noriega</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush ``would not rule out'' seizing
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, Panama's de facto ruler, to face
charges in Miami in a federal drug trafficking case, White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday.
   The spokesman, however, did not say the president was
contemplating such a move, and said there was no correlation
between Bush's comments to that effect in an interview and the
recent military maneuvers by U.S. forces in Panama.
   The stepped up military maneuvers are intended to make an
impression in that volatile country and ensure that ``our degree of
interest and control there is recognized and protected,'' Fitzwater
told reporters.
   Reporters asked for clarification on the difference between
seizing Noriega, who is accused of drug trafficking by the United
States, and terrorists kidnapping Americans they believed guilty of
crimes.
   Elaborating on Bush's comments in an interview this week with
Hearst Newspapers Washington bureau, Fitzwater said:
   ``The president was pointing out ... the difference between
kidnapping and capturing someone who has been indicted, charged and
ordered to be extradited to the United States for legal violations.
And he said he would not rule out that option in the case of Mr.
Noriega.''
   Bush, asked how he viewed the Noriega situation in light of his
position that he would not abduct anyone to set up a hostage trade,
said in the interview that ``there's a differentiating precedent
between taking somebody hostage and apprehending somebody to bring
them to trial.''
   ``I took an oath to uphold the law. It doesn't include
necessarily telling me how I have to go about apprehending people,
but I wouldn't rule out an option or discuss what I might or might
not do in terms of Noriega.
   ``But I view that very differently than if you took somebody and
then wanted to trade him off,'' Bush said.
   The United States has tried unsuccessfully to pressure Noriega
from power, and currently supports the ongoing diplomatic efforts
of the Organization of American States to arrange a peaceful
transfer of power by Sept. 1.
   The OAS called for subsequent democratic elections to select a
new president, although the organization did not specifically call
for Noriega to step down, as the United States has urged.
   Bush beefed up U.S. trooppresence in Panama as part of a show of
opposition to the Noriega regime after the strongman refused to
acknowledge results of the May election that was widely said by
observers to have been won by the opposition forces.
   A weeklong series of confrontations between Noriega's Defense
Forces and U.S. Southern Command troops included arrests on both
sides and the blocking of nearby Fort Amador by American soldiers.
   U.S. troops have been conducting exercises to defend the Panama
Canal under the 1977 treaties, and Panamanian troops in some
instances have been shadowing them.
   Noriega on Thursday said he will not yield to demands that he
quit as chief of the Defense Forces from what he called ``those
barbarians from the North, their lackeys and tame politicians.''
   Fitzwater said the U.S. exercises would continue.
   ``We have always said that we would feel free to carry out
exercises in support of our rights under the Panama Canal Treaty
... And in the current situation there, frankly, the purpose of
that is just to make sure that we do have that access, to make sure
our degree of interest and control there is recognized and
protected.''
</TEXT>
