<FIRST>r i AM-Auschwitz     08-11 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Cardinal Says Accord on Auschwitz Should Be Respected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Albert Decourtray, Roman Catholic
archbishop of Lyon, said Friday the agreement with Jewish groups
calling for moving a Carmelite convent away from the site of the
Auschwitz death camp should be respected.
   ``An accord binds those who signed it,'' said Decourtray, who
was involved in negotiating the agreement between Jewish and
Catholic leaders signed in Geneva in February 1987.
   Jews have argued it is offensive to locate the convent and erect
religious symbols at the Auschwitz-Birkenau complex. An estimated
2.5 million Jews were murdered at the camp in Nazi-held Poland.
   The archbishop of Krakow, Cardinal Franciszek Macharski, said
Thursday the agreement with Jewish leaders had been suspended and
blamed recent protests by Jewish groups at the convent for creating
an ``atmosphere of aggressive demands.''
   Decourtray said in his statement Friday that ``demonstrations
and regrettable reactions cannot be taken into account against the
cause which the accord of Feb. 22, 1987, was intended to defend.''
   He said the French Roman Catholic bishops would ``do everything
we can so that the dialogue inaugurated under the sign of the
Geneva accord can continue. We need mutual respect so as not to
damage the memory of Auscwhitz.''
   A statement in Paris by members of the Jewish delegation to the
Geneva talks noted ``with satisfaction and respect the terms of the
declaration Cardinal Decourtray has just issued.''
   It said the delegation ``fully associates itself with Cardinal
Decourtray's appeal for mutual respect in the memory of Auschwitz
and of all Jewish and non-Jewish victims of Auschwitz.''
</TEXT>
