<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Strikes     08-11 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Strikes,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Volkswagen, Samcor Strikes Ended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wildcat strikes at Volkswagen
and South African Motor Corp. ended Friday with 8,500 workers
promising to go back to work Monday if the companies returned to
the bargaining table.
   Toyota South Africa Ltd., with 3,600 employees on strike, was
the only major auto manufacturer remaining shut down. Toyota has
balked at demands by the black National Union of Metalworkers of
South Africa that it join industrywide wage negotiations and has
fired the striking workers.
   Volkswagen and South African Motor Corp. (Samcor), which
manufactures Fords and Mazdas, had been participating in the talks
but closed their plants when they were hit by wildcat strikes in
the midst of negotiations. Volkswagen dropped out of the talks
Wednesday and threatened to fire its 5,500 employees at the plant
in Uitenhage in eastern Cape province if they didn't agree by
Friday to return to work.
   Union organizer Gavin Hartford said the workers decided Friday
to return to their jobs Monday and that Volkswagen said it would
rejoin the national negotiations, which are to resume Wednesday.
   Les Kettledas, the union's collective bargaining co-ordinator in
Port Elizabeth, said the 3,000 workers on strike at the Pretoria
and Port Elizabeth plants of Samcor had agreed to return to work
Monday and the company had dropped other preconditions. Samcor had
never dropped out of the wage talks.
</TEXT>
