<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1656EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Cornycopia     08-11 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cornycopia,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cornfield Becomes Artists' Canvas: Art With Good Taste</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sculptor and a poet who spent their
boyhoods working the family farm have planted a field of corn in
the middle of the city and scattered furniture within the rows _
all in the name of art.
   In two weeks, they'll have a poetry reading, a harvest and then
roast an ear of art.
   Now that's art with good taste, or at least art that tastes good.
   Sculptor Caleb Brennan and part-time poet Dale Hasenick hope to
raise _ along with an edible crop _ awareness about the importance
of corn in American life.
   ``I'm hoping that people might have an awareness of how corn is
in our lives all over _ everything from corn oil to plastics,''
said Hasenick, whose poetry inspired Brennan's sculpture in the
front yard of the Urban Institute for Contemporary Arts.
   Inside the 30-by-30-foot patch of maize are a stove, kitchen
table, stuffed chair and toilet, all culled from the Salvation Army
and a dump. An old-fashioned bedstead surrounds a coverlet of
marble chips, upon which sleeps a little white pine tree. Elf-size
chairs and a sewing machine were added by an artist in residence at
the institute.
   The pair reason that if corn starch compounds can be used to
make such items as biodegradable garbage bags and disposable
diapers, surely its stalks can be used for art.
   Some neighbors aren't pleased with the urban field of dreams and
question how anyone could consider it artwork.
   But Mary Barwacz, who grows corn in her garden down the block
from the institute, gets a kick out of the piece.
   ``It's comical,'' see said with a chuckle. ``Darn nice corn,
too.''
   Brennan and Hasenick both worked on family farms near Jackson in
their youth and met at Spring Arbor College.
   Brennan, who sets up exhibits at the Grand Rapids Art Museum,
got the idea for the ``Maize House'' when he read part of a poem in
progress by Hasenick in which a man makes himself a house amid a
cornfield.
   ``The character sets up his living space and a religious shrine
in the middle of a cornfield,'' said Hasenick, who works as a
magazine typesetter in Chicago.
   He sees three levels of interpretation of the exhibit: corn as a
commercial product, corn as an object of sustenance and spiritual
reverence for North and Latin American natives, and corn as a
cornerstone of Midwestern traditions and culture.
   But in the last analysis, Brennan and Hasenick hope the public
will appreciate the sculpture at face value. People are invited to
walk through the stalks.
   ``I think it should be enjoyed as kind of a fun idea,'' Brennan
said. ``Just come at it with what you know about corn and houses.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
