<FIRST>u i AM-Peru     08-11 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankers Strike; Miners and Construction Workers Threaten Walkouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of Peru's 30,000 bank employees walked
off the job Friday to demand higher wages, and miners and
construction workers threatened strikes to demand pay increases to
help them survive the nation's worst economic crisis.
   Inflation in the last 12 months has topped 5,000 percent, and
the economy shrank last year by nearly 9 percent. Hundreds of
thousands of people are out of work.
   The bank strike forced the nation's stock market to close
Friday. Police escorted customers through picket lines, and
mid-level managers handled some transactions.
   Radio reports said police used tear gas to break up a
demonstration outside the Banco Internacional in downtown Lima.
There were no reports of injuries.
   The Communist-led Federation of Bank Employees, whose members
make from $250 to $310 a month, are asking for increases of about
$400 a month. The banks have offered $90.
   The country's minimum wage is $45 a month.
   The National Mine Workers Federation has called a general strike
Monday to demand salary increases and joint negotiations with mine
owners. Miners struck for three months last year over the same
issue, resulting in $400 million in lost export earnings for the
country.
   The country's 80,000 miners make from $2 to $12 a day, depending
on the company. They are seeking at least $500 a month.
   The Civil Construction Workers Union said it would strike Aug.
16 to protest the ``grave crisis of hunger and misery experienced
by the workers and the public,'' according to the secretary general
of the union, Pedro Huilca.
   Friday also marked the 73rd day of a wage strike by public
doctors, which has left government hospitals and emergency clinics
unattended. The 8,000 doctors average about $100 a month and are
seeking to be paid about $290 a month. The government has offered
$250.
   All the strikes have been declared illegal by the government.
   Peru is suffering its most serious economic crisis in its
168-year history as an independent nation.
   Many accuse President Alan Garcia of bankrupting the country and
sparking hyperinflation with his free-spending, populist economic
policies.
   The government blames much of the crisis on the battle with two
rebel groups, the Mao-inspired Shining Path, which took up arms in
1980, and the pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, which
has been fighting since 1984.
   The groups have attacked power lines across the country.
Electric power has been rationed in Lima and other cities as a
result of the attacks, which the government says has caused more
than $10 billion in damage.
   The government declared the mining province of Huarochiri, 30
miles east of Lima, under emergency restrictions Thursday. The move
gave the military control of the important Central Highway, which
connects most of the country's highland mining centers with the
capital.
   Jorge Quesada, general secretary of the miners union, said the
move would not affect plans for the strike Monday.
   Mining exports brought in more than $1.2 billion in 1988,
representing more than half the foreign exchange earnings of this
debtor nation.
</TEXT>
