<FIRST>u i AM-BoatPeople     08-11 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Battle at Detention Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnamese refugees at a detention center
fought a battle Friday with homemade weapons and 17 people,
including two guards, were injured, police reported.
   They said they had not determined the cause of the fighting but
it involved about 150 people from the Haiphong and Quang Ning areas
of northern Vietnam.
   Police said the rival groups fought for more than an hour with
iron bars and stones before police restored order at the refugee
camp that houses about 9,000 Vietnamese boat people.
   They said five of the injured people were hospitalized.
   A similar brawl occurred 10 days ago at the Shamshuipo detention
center when about 200 Vietnamese hurled stones at each other and
eight people were injured. The Shamshuipo center holds more than
4,000 Vietnamese.
   More than 50,000 Vitenamese boat people are languishing in Hong
Kong camps and most will have to prove they fled political
persecution to qualify for resettlement in this British colony.
   The government, struggling with the mounting problem, has
declared it will send back to Vietnam boat people who do not
qualify as political refugees.
