<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     08-11 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>23 Killed; Official Says Sinhalese Plan Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 23 people were reported
killed on this ethnically divided island Friday, and the foreign
minister said Sinhalese extremists were plotting to overthrow the
government.
   Ranjan Wijeratne, the foreign minister, said the radicals had
sent death threats to many lawmakers.
   ``It is very clear there is a well-conceived plot to destroy
those who are committed to the democratic form of government,'' he
said in parliamentary debate. ``Today, the people hesitate to talk
about this situation because of fear. They have been terrorized.''
   Military officials said at least 23 people were killed in the
previous 24 hours. The officials, who cannot be named under
standing regulations, said 71 Sinhalese were arrested during the
period.
   Among the dead were 16 civilians, two policemen, three Sinhalese
radicals and two members of the Tamil ethnic minority. The
officials said the Tamils were killed by Sinhalese, the predominant
ethnic group in Sri Lanka, but that details of the other killings
were not available.
   Wijeratne said 972 government officials and supporters of the
governing United National Party had been killed in the two years of
an anti-government campaign by the People's Liberation Front, a
radical Sinhalese group.
   He also accused the extremists of killing 184 opposition
politicians and 354 soldiers and policemen.
   ``All of you are aware that ruling party members of Parliament
have received death warrants from unseen hands,'' Wijeratne said.
``You are aware that some of our parliamentary colleagues have
already been disposed of.''
   Police say many lawmakers and senior government officials have
received death threats.
   About 2,500 other people, including members and suspected
members of the Sinhalese front and police informers, have been
killed in the confrontation between the extremists and the
Sinhalese-dominated government.
   Sinhalese radicals began their campaign in July 1987, claiming
the government made too many concessions in a peace accord aimed at
ending a seccesionist Tamil war in which at least 11,000 people
have died since 1983.
   Tamils make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
claim discrimination by the Sinhalese.
</TEXT>
