<FIRST>r a AM-Drownings     08-11 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drownings,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Confesses to Premeditation in Drownings, Police Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead planned after arraignment; timing uncertain. Kadie is cq
in 10th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect confessed to premeditation in
the drownings of four children killed when their family's car
crashed through a barrier and into the Detroit River, police said
Friday.
   Police said they had sought a murde warrant against the suspect,
whose name they refused to release pending arraignment later in the
day.
   Relatives said Lawrence DeLisle, the father of the children, was
taken into custody Thursday after he and his wife submitted to
polygraph tests.
   ``The premeditation goes back some time, and the opportunity
presented itself,'' Police Chief Edward Rothermal said at a news
conference Friday.
   Though they would not identify the suspect, police did say they
were not seeking charges against DeLisle's wife, Suzanne, who also
survived the Lincoln Park family's crash Aug 3.
   ``The facts of the investigation reveal she had nothing to do
with this,'' Rothermal said.
   He said the suspect disclosed a motive during questioning
Thursday. But the police chief declined to elaborate, or say
whether Mrs. DeLisle was an intended victim or whether the accident
was a suicide attempt.
   ``Yesterday afternoon, things started working out for us,''
Rothermal said. ``The investigating officer received a statement
indicating the involvement (of a suspect) and what actually
happened at the river.''
   DeLisle, 28, was driving when his car ran into the river in this
Detroit suburb. He and Mrs. DeLisle, 32, escaped when boaters
passed life preservers to them, but their children, Brian, 8;
Melissa, 4; Kadie, 2; and Emily, 8 months, were killed.
   DeLisle said a leg cramp caused him to floor the accelerator.
   William DeLisle, Lawrence DeLisle's uncle, said Mrs. DeLisle
called him Thursday night to say her husband was in jail.
   ``She didn't say why,'' William DeLisle said. ``This is worse
than what happened five days ago. I don't know what it is. I'm
going to find out as quick as I can.''
   Asked if DeLisle's detention made him doubt his nephew's story,
William DeLisle said: ``Certainly I have doubts. The boy's in
jail.''
   Mrs. DeLisle, who also took a lie detector test, said she tried
to stop the car by turning off the ignition and shifting gears
before the car struck the barrier.
   Rick Stoneburner, a witness to the accident who threw life
preservers to the couple from a boat, said the father appeared
exhausted and Mrs. DeLisle was hysterical, crying, ``I am not
leaving without my children! Save my children! They are under
water!''
</TEXT>
