<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Cleveland     08-11 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Cleveland,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>No. 2 HUD Official To Decide Fate of Long-Troubled Housing Agency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 2 official at the Deparment of Housing
and Urban Development said Friday he will ask Cleveland-area
officials to shake up the management of their housing authority but
opposes a federal takeover of the long-troubled agency sought by
the mayor of the city.
   ``The problem is basically a management problem and I think
clearly the management in place is not up to the challenge at
hand,'' HUD Undersecretary Al Dellibovi said of the Cuyahoga
Metropolitan Housing Authority. ``The solution to this kind of
local problem is not a federal takeover.''
   Dellibovi is traveling to Cleveland on Monday to meet with Mayor
George Voinovich, the mayor of neighboring East Cleveland and
members of the Cleveland City Council, all of whom share
appointment power to the authority board. Voinovich repeatedly has
asked the federal agency to take over the housing authority.
   Delibovi, who requested the meeting, said he wanted to reserve
judgment on the performance of the five-man board that oversees the
authority but said ``clearly the major problem is the day-to-day
management.''
   ``We are not really equipped to operate that kind of agency and
deliver public housing services but we can take supervisory action
to bring the services to to level that tenants deserve.''
   He declined to discuss steps HUD was contemplating if it did not
receive a satisfactory response from local officials.
   HUD pays more than half of the agency's operating budget. In
September 1985 HUD labeled the Cleveland authority ``operationaly
troubled'' because of its high vacancy rates and poor condition of
its units, which house more than 19,000 people on 38 sites.
   A 1987 audit found the authority on occassion paid maintenance
workers double or triple their salaries in overtime without
required proof that the work was performed. In both 1982 and 1986
HUD's inspector general issued audits critical of the authority's
maintenance program.
   An earlier internal HUD review determined that errors by the
housing agency's staff resulted in inflated rent subsidies to
developers participating in an housing rehabilitation program.
   George M. James, the authority's executive director, did not
immediately return telephone calls seeking comment.
</TEXT>
