<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2028EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ExportSanctions     08-11 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Export Sanctions,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Department Penalizes Exporters Over Mustard Gas Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German companies have been denied
U.S. export privileges for nine years because of their relationship
to a West German convicted of re-exporting a mustard gas ingredient
to Iran, the Commerce Department reported Friday.
   The companies, Chemco and Colimex of Cologne, were added to a
previous order denying similar privileges to West German
businessman Peter Walascheck of Colgne because of their
``affiliation, ownership, control or portion of responsibility'' to
Walascheck, the department said.
   Walascheck pleaded guilty Aug. 26, 1988, in U.S. District Court
in Baltimore to illegally re-exporting thiodiglycol from Singapore
to Iran, the department said. Thiodiglycol is an ingredient of
mustard gas used in chemical warfare.
   In addition to barring exports by the West Germans, the order
prohibits other firms from dealing with them in any export
transaction involving U.S.-origin goods without prior Commerce
Department authorization.
   The department said the order was the first authorized by the
1988 trade act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
