<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-11 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appearance on NBC's ``Tonight Show''
notwithstanding, Homer Williams says he's ``cotton-pickin' tired''
of reliving his resurrection from the dead.
   ``It's been fun, exhausting fun,'' said the 63-year-old
Evansville man, who gained celebrity status by being mistakenly
declared dead, and then ``legally alive'' by a Vanderburgh Superior
Court judge. ``It's fun, but I don't want to have to die to do it
again.''
   Williams' attorneys probated his will after another man sharing
his name died in a nursing home. The retired road surveyor was
fishing with his grandson in Alabama at the time. Vanderburgh
Superior Court Judge Robert Lensing straightened out the mess in
May.
   Williams said from his Los Angeles hotel Wednesday night that
his reluctant days in the spotlight have been exhausting as well as
exciting.
   After agreeing to do the ``Tonight Show'' with host Johnny
Carson last month, Williams said he has been treated like a king.
   He was flown to Los Angeles first class, where a stretch
limousine was waiting at the airport to whisk him to one of the
city's most expensive hotels.
   ``This ain't Evansville, buddy, this is hussel-bussel-go and
expensive city,'' Williams said.
   Williams said before the show that he was afraid Carson might
ask embarrassing questions and that he would clam up.
   ``But he was wonderful, he was really just super,'' he said. The
show's host also signed a copy of Williams' death certificate
during a commercial break.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WYOMING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-year-old Alexandria Crooks is having
a street named in her honor. In fact, an entire subdivision is
being named after her.
   That's what happens when your mom is the developer.
   Mary Helen Crooks, a former mortgage broker, and two of her
eight sisters are launching a subdivision development business in
this Grand Rapids suburb.
   While many housing development companies are family affairs,
they usually are of the father-and-son or brother-and-brother
variety.
   Alexandria Estates, which also will include streets named for
Crooks' young nieces, Amanda and Michela, received final approval
by city officials last week for 50 single-family homes.
   ``I was raised to believe that you can do anything that you set
your mind to, regardless of whether you are male or female,'' said
Crooks, 31.
</TEXT>
