<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NervousWitnesses     08-11 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nervous Witnesses,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Study Says Fidgety Defendants Shouldn't Testify if Prosecution
Weak</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hand-wringing, tie-fiddling, nervously sweating
criminal defendant actually appears more deceitful to jurors when
the evidence against him is weak than when it is somewhat stronger,
a psychological study indicates.
   Researchers who performed the study, published in Saturday's
Journal of Applied Psychology, say it supports what every country
lawyer knows: If the evidence indicates innocence to a jury, don't
let a fidgety defendant have a chance to put a noose around his own
neck.
   ``When the evidence is strong, they (jurors) could decide it
more on the evidence,'' said David R. Shaffer, a University of
Georgia psychology professor who led the study. ``The same is true
if the case is close.''
   But, Shaffer said, anxious-looking defendants appear more
deceptive to jurors if the evidence is weak.
   ``I think the jurors are saying, `The evidence isn't all that
strong, but this guy is nervous and he looks guilty.' They
reinterpret the evidence,'' Shaffer said.
   He said the study appears to contradict research indicating that
demeanor comes into play only when the evidence is ambiguous.
   Shaffer and two colleagues from Georgia College, Sarah H. Hendry
and Dina Peacock, used 120 undergraduate students as mock jurors to
hear a case of academic fraud on an exam. An actor from the
university's drama department played the defendant, whose pseudonym
was Cliff Roberts.
   Three trials were held before three juries. In the first, the
evidence was strong: Eyewitnesses saw Roberts using a cheat sheet
on the exam, his answers were identical to another student's and a
student testified Roberts had been caught cheating off her paper in
a previous class.
   The second case was weaker, with the eyewitness accounts more
ambiguous and the allegation of past cheating implied rather than
confirmed.
   In the third case, Roberts was portrayed as an excellent student
with no need to cheat. His professor testified that Roberts had
worked hard to perform well on the exam and there was no allegation
of past cheating.
   The jurors then watched a three-minute videotape, during which
Roberts made identical points about his innocence: He had no cheat
sheet or advance knowledge of the exam and had never been accused
of academic fraud previously.
   The only difference in the testimony was the actor's portrayal
of Roberts' demeanor. Half the jurors saw a calm, confident
witness, while the others saw one who stammered, fiddled with his
tie, hesitated and generally looked anxious.
   Jurors were then asked to vote for conviction or acquittal,
taking both the evidence and the defendant's demeanor into account.
   The study found demeanor had the most effect when the evidence
favored the accused, with 85 percent of those who considered the
weakest evidence and saw the nervous witness voting for conviction.
Only 15 percent indicated guilt when the defendant was calm and the
evidence was weak.
   In the strong-evidence case, 100 percent of jurors voted for
conviction when the witness was nervous and 90 percent when he was
calm; when the evidence was balanced, 70 percent favored conviction
when the defendant was nervous and 60 percent when he was
controlled.
   A nervous defendant, therefore, stood a better chance of
acquittal when the evidence against him was balanced than when it
was weak.
   ``We think that the hesitancy and uncertainty of the apparently
deceptive defendant must have appeared especially suspicious in the
face of objectively weak evidence against him ... ,'' Shaffer wrote.
   Richard Hendrix, an Atlanta criminal defense attorney who
represented former Rep. Pat Swindall in his recent perjury trial,
said the study bears out his experience in handling fidgety
defendants.
   ``If there is a strong case against the defendant, he might be
able to convince the jury to let him walk. If it's teetering either
way and you have a guy who's articulate and you think he might
carry the day, you might put him up,'' Hendrix said.
   ``It's best not to call a defendant when in doubt. He may come
off bad even if he's innocent,'' he said.
   Hendrix did not put Swindall on the stand, and the congressman
was convicted. Hendrix has not said why Swindall did not testify.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890811-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1704EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-BlochProbe     08-11 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bloch Probe,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Says Leak Compromised Bloch Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department on Friday said flatly
that public disclosure of its investigation of suspected Soviet spy
Felix S. Bloch has compromised the government's ability to obtain
evidence against him.
   ``There is no doubt that the premature disclosure of that case,
the premature disclosure that there was an ongoing investigation,
did compromise the investigation,'' David Runkel, chief department
spokesman, told reporters.
   Runkel refused to specify how the leak hampered investigators,
but his comments hardened the government's assessment of the damage
done.
   The case was publicly disclosed July 21. Runkel's statement
Friday contrasted with his more cautious July 31 assessment that
``premature disclosure may have had an adverse impact on the
development of new evidence.''
   On Friday, Runkel said ``the difference in the statements
reflects a different view, based on how people in the department
see the situation today.''
   No charges have been brought against Bloch, once the No. 2 U.S.
diplomat in Vienna, who is suspected of having spied for the Soviet
Union since 1974. He has been suspended with pay.
   Runkel acknowledged that the Justice Department opposed
confirmation by the State Department on July 21 of an ABC news
report that Bloch was under investigation.
   Since then, Bloch has been followed _ in what Runkel described
as ``the circus going on out there'' _ by a horde of reporters and
FBI agents who are conducting an open surveillance while
investigators try to gather evidence to bring charges.
   The chief obstacle, according to government sources, is that
investigators cannot identify a specific secret that Bloch may have
compromised. The sources say Bloch was videotaped giving a
briefcase to a Soviet agent in Paris on May 14, but investigators
don't know what was in it.
   On Thursday, Runkel acknowledged the department did not have a
case to bring against Bloch.
   ``The department does not bring charges unless it believes it
has sufficient evidence to convince a jury beyond a reasonable
doubt that a person is guilty of violating the law,'' Runkel said.
   He refused to comment when asked if the Justice Department was
negotiating a deal with Bloch under which the 54-year-old diplomat
would receive immunity from prosecution in return for detailing
information allegedly given to the Soviets.
   Runkel also has refused to discuss whether the department has
evidence of espionage that it is unwilling to use in court because
disclosure would impair counterintelligence operations.
   Bloch, meanwhile, continued on Friday to lead print and
television photographers on daily excursions from his apartment in
the capital's posh Kalorama neighborhood.
   In the afternoon, Bloch stuck his head out a window and
announced to photographers that he was about to leave.
   Two hours later, Bloch finally left in his light-blue
Mercedes-Benz, after inviting a TV crew to join him for a ride
while he did errands.
   Bloch, followed by a 20-car caravan of reporters, photographers
and FBI agents, drove to a supermarket in suburban Bethesda, Md.
Bloch also visited a nearby book store.
   In the supermarket, a TV cameraman knocked over an elderly woman
shopper while backpeddling to get a shot of Bloch.
   The woman cut her hand when she fell to the floor and TV crews
left the store after the manager asked them to leave.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
