<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Prater     08-11 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Prater,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Figure Tied to Yablonski Killings Dies in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former United Mine Workers official
convicted of helping raise money for the 1969 murders of union
dissident Joseph ``Jock'' Yablonski and his family has died of a
heart attack, authorities said Friday.
   William Prater, 70, was found dead early Friday morning in his
cell at the state prison, said prison spokesman Roy VanWhy. Prater
had been confined to a wheelchair since suffering a stroke in 1983,
he said.
   George Hudock, Luzerne County coronor, said death was caused by
a heart attack.
   Prater was convicted in 1972 of three state murder charges and
was serving three life sentences. In addition, he had pleaded
guilty to federal conspiracy charges in the case.
   Yablonski, 59; his wife, Margaret, 57; and their 25-year-old
daughter, Charlotte, were shot to death as they slept at their
Clarksville home on New Year's Eve 1969. The bodies were found six
days later.
   Weeks earlier, Yablonski, founder of a group called Miners for
Democracy, had lost a bitter electoral battle to unseat UMW
President W.A. ``Tony'' Boyle. Yablonski had described the election
results as fraudulent and said he would challenge them.
   Mindful of his union's violent history, Yablonski had predicted
his challenge could lead to his death.
   In all, eight people were convicted or pleaded guilty to a role
in the deaths.
   Boyle was convicted of ordering the assassination. He died in
1985 while serving life terms in prison. The three men identified
as the gunmen _ Paul Gilly, Claude Vealey and Aubran ``Buddy''
Martin _ also received life sentences.
   Prater, a union field representative from LaFollette, Tenn., was
accused of helping obtain $20,000 in union funds to hire the
killers.
   He served 16 years of a life sentence on a federal conspiracy
charge stemming from the murders. After he was paroled, he was
extradited to Pennsylvania and committed to the state prison at
Pittsburgh in September 1988 to serve life terms. He was moved to
the prison in Dallas, Pa., later that year.
   Prater had a petition pending before the state Board of Pardons
contending the state sentence was supposed to be concurrent with
his federal term and that he should therefore have been released in
1988.
   Pennsylvania corrections spokesman Ken Robinson said prison
records showed Prater had a wife, Maxine, in Tennessee and seven
children.
</TEXT>
