<HEAD>Rebels Kill Two Policemen in Highland Towns</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peru</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas of the Maoist Shining Path movement
killed two policemen and wounded a third in two attacks in the
Andes highlands, officials reported Friday.
   They said gunmen fired at two officers as they were dining
Thursday night in a restaurant in the town of Churcampa, 185 miles
east of Lima, killing one and wounding the other. The killers took
the slain policeman's revolver before fleeing, according to
authorities.
   They said a detective was beaten to death Thursday by a gang of
Shining Path guerrillas who stopped the truck carrying the police
officer and members of his family on the road between Pucara and
Huancayo, about 140 miles east of the capital.
   The Shining Path movement began its insurgency in 1980 and the
government says more than 15,000 people have been slain in violence
related to the revolt.
