<FIRST>r w AM-Judge-Robinson     08-11 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Judge-Robinson,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robinson Retires After Quarter-Century in Federal Judiciary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals Judge Spottswood
Robinson is retiring after serving 25 years in the federal
judiciary, court officials announced Friday.
   Robinson plans to retire Aug. 31, leaving another opening for
the Bush administration to fill on the appeals court in the
District of Columbia. Robinson has offered to serve as a senior
judge who continues to accept judicial assignments, according to a
statement.
   There are three vacancies on the 12-member appeals court. One
opening was created with the departure of Robert Bork, the Reagan
administration's unsuccessful nominee for the Supreme Court.
Clarence Thomas, formerly chairman of the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission, has been nominated to fill Bork's spot.
   The other vacancy is that of Kenneth W. Starr, who recently
became solicitor general.
   Robinson was nominated by President Kennedy and appointed in
1964 by President Johnson to U.S. District Court in Washington,
D.C. He then served nearly 23 years on the appeals court, including
five as chief judge.
   He was a noted civil rights attorney and participated in the
landmark Brown v. Board of Education case before the Supreme Court.
Robinson also has served as the dean of the Howard University Law
School and on the U.S. Civil Rights Commission.
</TEXT>
