<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Spending     08-11 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Spending,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Weapons Chief Sworn In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ford Motor Co. executive John Betti,
sworn in as the Pentagon's undersecretary of defense for
acquisition, promised ``a fundamental change'' Friday in the way
the Defense Department spends its money.
   Betti has been put in charge of streamlining the agency's $150
billion-a-year purchasing bureaucracy.
   ``The new undersecretary hopes to help restore public confidence
and credibility in defense acquisition,'' said a Pentagon statement.
   ``A fundamental change is required if we are to optimize the
overall aquisition process and provide the highest quality products
and services to the men and women in the field _ on time and on
cost,'' Betti was quoted as saying in the statement.
   Under a manangement review released last month by Defense
Secretary Dick Chency, Betti will serve on an executive panel that
will oversee weapons buying by the Pentagon.
   Betti will also serve on a new ethics panel called for under the
management plan.
   Since 1962, Betti had worked for Ford in a variety of positions,
most recently as executive vice president for Ford's diversified
products operation.
</TEXT>
