<FIRST>r w AM-Pentagon-Marsh     08-11 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-Marsh,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Secretary Steps Down to Become Defense Secretary's Adviser</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Army Secretary John O. Marsh Jr. bid farewell
_ sort of _ to his colleagues at the Pentagon on Friday after
serving the longest term of any such service secretary in the
nation's history.
   As of Friday, Marsh served 8 years, 6 months and 15 days in the
job.
   On Monday he will be succeeded by Michael Stone, the current
undersecretary of the Army.
   In a ceremony attended by Defense Secretary Dick Cheney and the
Pentagon's top brass, Marsh was awarded the Medal for Distinguished
Public Service, the agency's highest civilian award.
   But Marsh is not leaving the Pentagon, despite his length of
service.
   He returns Monday as an adviser to Cheney, helping him implement
his plan for streamlining the agency's management.
   In February, Marsh broke the record for longevity set by Thomas
Jefferson's secretary of war, Henry Dearborn, who served from 1801
to 1809, according to figures provided by the Army's office of
public affairs.
</TEXT>
