<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Crash     08-11 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Crash,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Train Crash Victims Buried; People Search For Family Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUASAVE, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Hector Armando Calderon said
Mass on Friday in front of blank, white wooden crosses marking 38
fresh graves _ blank because the bodies in the graves were not
identified.
   Eulogio Partida Gurrola went through photos taken of the
unidentified dead, looking for his brother.
   Rosario Castro walked onto the baseball field being used as a
helicopter pad, trying to hitch a ride to the site of the train
crash to search for her father and brother-in-law.
   While Father Calderon officiated at the burials, searchers flew
crisscross patterns, looking for more victims who might have been
swept downsteam when the train plunged into a raging river
Wednesday.
   The train, a crowded local of the national railroad, plunged 25
feet into the San Rafael River, 15 miles south of Gusave, when a
bridge it was crossing collapsed. The government news agency
reported 112 people killed.
   On Friday, the government said it would pay $3,200 to the
families of victims for each person killed.
   Only about 100 townspeople attended Friday's Roman Catholic
burial service. Relatives went from place to place seeking loved
ones.
   Partida, from Tecuala in Nayarit state, was looking for his
21-year-old brother, Jose Patricio.
   ``His aunt and her 6-year-old daughter had come to Tepic on
vacation and he was taking them home to Mexicali,'' he said.
   Ms. Castro, from Guadalajara, said she had gone to the hospital,
the makeshift morgue, the Red Cross. She said her family boarded
the train in Mazatlan for Mexicali, where they planned to cross the
border to visit a relative in the United States.
   Carlos Orozco Sosa, director of Mexican National Railways, said
600-700 passengers were on the Pacific Railways train for its
regular 700-mile run from the beach resort of Mazatlan to Mexicali,
about 100 miles east of San Diego.
   The second-class train is known as ``The Burro'' because it
stops at every station.
   A week of the heaviest rains in 50 years had flooded large areas
of southern Sinaloa state and caused a small dam three miles
upstream to burst a few hours before the train passed.
   Federal highway police said in a preliminary report the rain had
weakened the railbeds, causing the train to sway sharply, and the
narrow bridge caved in under the stress.
   Some victims were battered to death inside the cars by the fall.
Others drowned and some were swept away by rushing watern in what
normally is a dry bed.
   Carlos Guzman Leffer of the state attorney general's office said
bodies originally taken to Guamuchil were brought to Guasave for
burial.
   ``We have brought them so they can all be together,'' he said.
``They are looking for bodies. The rescue operation continues.''
   Guzman said a few people were found alive as far as 12 miles
downstream, ``holding onto the branches of trees with their train
tickets still in their shirt pockets.''
   Water still stood in some fields Friday. Others were muddy, but
drying quickly in the hot summer sun. On the riverbank, nine cars
lay beside the tracks.
   All but a few of the people with minor injures had left by
Friday. Identified bodies were being flown home by the government.
</TEXT>
