<FIRST>r a AM-Newspaper-Subpoena 1stLd-Writethru a0675chasedhim.HisdeathsparkedanoutcryfromPhiladelphia'sHispaniccommuCoppa'scase
08-11 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper-Subpoena, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0675,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Delays Deposition From Newspaper Publisher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with judge delaying deposition;
Picks up 5th graf, `The 1984 ...; SUBS penultimate graf to conform; CORRECTS
spelling of subpoena in slugline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday delayed an
attempt by United Press International to make the publisher of
Nashville's morning newspaper identify the source of disparaging
comments about a former UPI president.
   Publisher John L. Seigenthaler of The Tennessean was subpoened
to give a deposition Tuesday and had filed a motion to quash the
order. U.S. District Judge John T. Nixon ordered the deposition
delayed while he considers the request.
   The comments from the source were printed in a September 1984
story in The Tennessean about the firing of William J. Small as
head of the wire service.
   Small later sued UPI seeking $10 million and alleging breach of
contract. He also claimed UPI and several of its executives libeled
him in explaining the reasons for his departure.
   Seigenthaler said in court papers filed Thursday that
Tennessee's shield law allowed the newspaper to withhold the name
of the source.
   The 1984 story quoted the source as saying Small had failed ``to
perform in a manner expected of the chief operating officer. He did
not live up to expectations.''
   Small was hired as president of UPI in September 1982. His
contract ran until Dec. 31, 1989, according to court papers.
   Small claimed in his lawsuit that the defendants conspired to
force him to quit. He was fired Sept. 8 when he refused, he said.
   The subpoena ordered Seigenthaler to appear Tuesday with all
documents relating to statements attributed to the source. The
court papers filed Thursday seek to quash that subpoena.
   The state law cited by Seigenthaler says that reporters can not
be required by government bodies to disclose ``any information or
the source of any information procured for publication or
broadcast.''
</TEXT>
