<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bolivia-Art     08-11 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia-Art,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bolivia Claims Lufthansa Executive Smuggled Colonial Art</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government claims the former manager
of West Germany's Lufthansa Airlines office in La Paz shipped more
than 100 colonial paintings and works of art out of the country.
   It asked the West German government and the United Nations for
assistance in recovering the items.
   In a letter released Friday, Education and Culture Minister
Mariano Baptista said his ministry ``has sufficient information to
indicate that Mr. Hans J. Liedtke, former manager of Lufthansa in
Bolivia, took more than 100 paintings and works of art out of the
country, utilizing the advantages that the airline at his disposal
offered.''
   It claimed that Liedtke ``took out of the country the equivalent
number of pieces that would fill two museums of this type. He could
not ignore the clear laws on this matter, which prohibit the export
under any circumstances of Bolivia's historical past.''
   Baptista did not describe the artworks in further detail.
   Officials said Liedtke left Bolivia last year after serving in
La Paz for four years and now is manager of the Lufthansa office in
Venezuela. Calls went unanswered to the airline's office in Caracas
late Friday.
</TEXT>
