<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-Stock     08-11 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Stock,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Indicts 11 in Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has indicted
multimillionaire Naji Nahas and 10 other brokers in the scandal
that caused the one-day closing of Brazil's stock exchanges, the
Justice Ministry said Friday.
   Judge Augusto Guilherme Diefenthaeler of Rio's 13th Federal
Court, in his ruling Thursday, set a trial date of Sept. 13 for
Nahas and Elmo Camoes Filho, the son of former Central Bank
president Elmo Camoes, according to ministry spokesman Vinicio
Becquer.
   An arrest order was issued July 21 for Nahas and Camoes Filho on
charges of ``inadmissible manipulation'' of the Rio and Sao Paulo
stock exchanges but both men remain at large and are considered
fugitives.
   Nahas, a 42-year-old businessmen and the largest investor in
Brazil's $30 billion stock market, was the key figure in the
scandal that brought about the closing of six brokerage firms and
the resignation of Camoes as the head of the government bank.
Camoes' brokerage company was operated by his son.
   If convicted, Nahas and Camoes Filho could face up to 11 years
in prison, Becquer told The Associated Press.
   The nine others indicted in the case were not arrested or
jailed. Becquer said three trials have been set for them. The
trials begin Sept. 26.
   The others indicted include Eduardo da Rocha Azevedo, president
of the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, and former Rio Stock Exchange
president Sergio Barcellos, Becquer said.
   The stock crisis began June 9 when Nahas failed to cover checks
worth $31 million for highly speculative deals on the Rio exchange.
   On June 12, the government shut down all of Brazil's stock
exchanges to avoid panic selling and Nahas was prohibited from
leaving the country. The markets reopened the next day.
   Camoes resigned from the Central Bank several days later.
   On June 26, the federal police filed two charges against Nahas,
one accusing him of trying to illegally remit $20,000 to London in
1987 and of borrowing the equivalent of $12 million from a bank of
which he was a major shareholder in 1983.
</TEXT>
