<HEAD>Gunmen Attack Opposition Leader's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen fired 25 shots and exploded a
hand grenade Friday at the house of a leading opposition leader and
daughter of slain President Sheik Mujibur Rahman, police and
witnesses said. No one was hurt.
   ``Killers of my father are conspiring to kill me also,'' said
Sheik Hasina, the leader of an eight-party opposition alliance.
   Hasina, 42, was in the library on the first floor of her home
when the gunmen, riding motorcycles, pulled up outside, police
said. The assailants opened fire and threw two hand grenades. One
grenade exploded and the other failed to go off. The gunmen fled.
   The attack came four days before the anniversary of Rahman's
1975 assassination.
   Rahman's killing _ in the same house _ was blamed on two
Bangladesh military officers who led a coup. One of them, Col.
Farooq Rahman, now heads the opposition Freedom Party.
   Hasina's alliance is campaigning for the ouster of President
Hussain Mohammad Ershad.
