<SECOND>AM-Canada-Bravery,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Gives American Firefighter Award for Bravery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada announced Friday that an American
firefighter has been awarded the Star of Courage for saving three
people, including a 5-year-old child, from a burning car.
   Richard Shiah, of Niagara Falls, N.Y., was among 14 people
awarded bravery decorations Friday by Gov. Gen. Jeanne Sauve. The
other 13 were Canadians.
   In May 1988, Shiah saved three members of a family when their
truck and trailer carrying fuel crashed and burst into flames near
Fonthill, Ontario.
   Shiah, who suffered severe facial burns during the rescue, is
one of only 315 people to receive the Star of Courage.
   The governor general, Canada's ceremonial head of state, will
present the bravery awards at a ceremony later this year.
   Since 1972, the governor general has awarded 1,278 decorations
for bravery, including 15 Crosses of Valor, 315 Stars of Courage,
and 948 Medals of Bravery.
