<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Amnesty     08-11 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Amnesty,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amnesty Granted To 42 In Disappearance Of Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Friday upheld a
ruling granting amnesty to 38 members of the military and two
civilians who had been indicted in the disappearence of 10 members
of the outlawed Communist Party.
   The unanimous ruling cannot be appealed.
   The court ruled that the 40, who included a former air force
commander, were covered by an amnesty law issued by the military
government.
   The opposition, which is favored in polls to win the Dec. 14
presidential election, has promised to repeal the 1978 law.
   It says it will investigate the human rights violations occurred
since military president Augusto Pinochet seized power in a bloody
1973 coup, and bring those responsible for them to trial.
   Military leaders, however, have warned that repealing the law
would have ``unpredictable consequences.''
   The amnesty law covers crimes, including human rights abuses,
that occurred from Sept. 11, 1973, when elected President Salvador
Allende was overthrown, to March 11, 1978.
   Among the defendants were retired air force Gen. Gustavo Leigh,
a former member of the four-men military junta led by Pinochet that
took power after the coup. Leigh retired in 1978.
   Also covered by the amnesty were two other air force generals
and a national police general, all retired.
   After seizing power, the military jailed thousands of members
and supporters of the toppled leftist government. Some were
tortured and killed, and thousands were forced into exile.
   The Roman Catholic Church and human rights groups here and
abroad have documented the cases of more than 700 disidents who
disappeared after being arrested by security agents.
   The group granted definite amnesty today had been indicted by a
civilian judge, Carlos Cerda, in the cases of 10 members of the
Communist Party members who disappeared after being arrested in
1976.
   After Judge Cerda filed the charges, however, the Santiago
Appeals Court ordered him to stop the proceedings and apply the
amnesty law in the case.
   Cerda refused, but the Appeals Court suspended him from his job
for two months, applying the amnesty law. That suspension also was
upheld Friday by the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
