<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Anti-AbortionArrests     08-11 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Abortion Arrests,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Resquest for Restraining Order Against LAPD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday decided to allow
police to use ``pain compliance'' techniques against anti-abortion
protesters affiliated with Operation Rescue.
   Such techniques involve bending a wrist or arm backward against
its joint, and, increasingly, the use of a an oriential martial
arts weapon known as nunchakus.
   U.S. District Judge A. Wallace Tashima, in refusing to issue a
temporary restraining order, said lawyers failed to show that
abortion foes were likely to be injured.
   ``I think under the law of this state ... officers are entitled
to use such reasonable force as necessary to take the person into
custody,'' Tashima said.
   Tashima also said that the abortion foes' lawyers had failed to
show a protest was likely to occur Saturday.
   ``Essentially, the judge said there's no case in controversy
because we don't know there's going to be a demonstration
tomorrow,'' said Samuel B. Casey, a lawyer representing six
anti-abortion protesters.
   ``We will enforce the law as we have in the past,'' said
Commander William Booth, a police spokesman. ``And when we have to
make an arrest, if there are resistances, pain compliance will be
used.''
   The nunchakus used by police, which Booth described as a ``come
along device,'' consists of two foot-long pieces of plastic that
are attached by a cord and are used like walnut crackers on a
person's arm or leg.
   Tashima said the issues presented by the case were novel, but he
was not persuaded that anti-abortion protesters are entitled to
court protection, said Jack Brown, an assistant city attorney.
   ``He said there was a question as to whether the demonstrators
were resisting arrest,'' said Brown, who represented the Police
Department in the hearing.
   Instead of issuing the emergency restraining order sought by
Casey, Tashima set a hearing for Oct. 2 to consider further
evidence and arguments.
   Police in Los Angeles developed pain compliance to counter
Operation Rescue's strategy of illegally blocking entrances to a
women's health clinic and delaying arrests to keep the clinic
closed.
   Operation Rescue protesters are taught a variety of methods to
passively resist arrest. Some have smeared their arms and legs with
petroleum jelly to make it more difficult for arresting officers to
grip them.
   The request for a temporary restraining order was filed Thursday
by The Rutherford Institute of California, a conservative,
Christian-oriented, public interest group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
