<DOCNO> AP890811-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WoundedKnee 1stLd-Writethru a0727 08-11 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wounded Knee, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seminole Indian Remains Reburied at Historic Sioux Indian Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with ceremony held, quotes, other
details; picks up 5th graf: `Arrangements for ...; ADDS 2 grafs comment
from anthropologist Zimmerman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH KEENAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WOUNDED KNEE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A summer thundershower rolled across
the South Dakota prairie Friday as the remains of Seminole Indians
were reburied near the site where Sioux Indians were killed by
soldiers almost a century ago.
   About 1,200 pounds of prehistoric remains of members of the
Seminole Tribe were returned to the earth after being stored in
boxes at the University of South Dakota for the past three years.
   A traditional ceremony was held Friday evening less than a mile
from the cemetery where Sioux Indians were buried following the
slaying of more than 200 Sioux on Dec. 29, 1890, by soldiers of the
U.S. Army's 7th Cavalry.
   The 1890 assault _ known as the Wounded Knee massacre to Indians
and a battle to the U.S. Army _ was one of the last major conflicts
between Indians and soldiers. It occurred just 14 days after
Sitting Bull was killed on the Standing Rock Reservation.
   ``There's an awful lot of power here, this is a powerful
place,'' said Mike Haney, a representative of the Seminole Tribe of
Oklahoma who was asked by tribal leaders in Florida to attend the
ceremony.
   ``One of the reasons I'm here is because I'm from the Alligater
clan of the Seminole people,'' Haney said. ``Traditionally, we (the
clan) bury our people.''
   Indians and archaeologists took turns digging a 6-foot-deep
grave atop a hill surrounded by pine trees.
   ``We want them to dig, we want them to finish the job they
started,'' said Roger Byrd, a spiritual leader of the Oglala Sioux
who said prayers over the gravesite, which will become part of the
National Indian Cemetery.
   ``As Indians we are all the same and we return to the ground the
same,'' Byrd said.
   Arrangements for the reburial were made with the help of
American Indians Against Desecration, a group that has been
fighting for reburial rights for the past decade.
   ``We're making sure we bury these people in a place that will
never be touched by archaeologists,'' Jan Bear Shield, a founder of
AIAD, said. ``That is why we picked Wounded Knee. As long as there
is an Indian alive, they will never touch it.''
   It is not known how many skeletons were buried Friday because
the remains, which included earth and Seminole burial articles,
were not studied by archaeologists.
   Larry Zimmerman, a professor of anthropology at the University
of South Dakota, was asked by members of the Seminole Tribe to
catalog the contents of the boxes containing the remains. They
appeared to be prehistoric, he said.
   The remains were unearthed at a construction site near Tampa,
Fla.
   Zimmerman was part of a similar reburial in 1981 following the
discovery of 500 people, ancestors to the contemporary Arikaras, at
the Crow Creek archaeological site near Fort Thompson. The
skeletons found at that site in 1978 were all victims of a massacre
that scientists have said occurred before white men arrived in the
region.
   The ceremony at Wounded Knee, on the Pine Ridge Reservation,
followed a four-day World Archaelogical Congress symposium on the
reburial issue.
   At the Inter-congress, the executive committee introduced the
Vermillion Accord, which calls for increased cooperation between
indigenous people and the scientific community when deaing with
archaeological remains.
   About 200 people from 20 nations attended the conference, which
ended Thursday in Vermillion.
   Some of the archaeologists who were at the conference also were
at the reburial and took part in digging the grave.
   ``I feel satisfied, comfortable about it,'' Zimmerman said.
``Although these bones weren't dug up by archaeologists, I think it
is important to get them back.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
