<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 0005EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CentralAmerica     08-11 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Church Leaders Urge U.S. Not To Hamper Peace Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Church leaders on
Thursday urged the United States to help restore peace in Central
America by not hampering a recent accord to disband the Nicaraguan
rebels.
   ``The U.S. government must support the accord, since it is no
secret that it is financing the irregular forces camped in
Honduras,'' Archbishop Carlos Santi, general secretary of the
conference of Nicaraguan bishops said.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
Bush administration was ``generally supportive'' of the accord
signed Monday by five Central American presidents. He said,
however, there was skepticism that Nicaragua's Sandinista
government will carry out the democratic reforms it has promised.
   ``The Central American presidents must fulfill the accord signed
in Tela, Honduras, but the U.S. government also should not hamper
these treaties, contributing to peace in the region,'' Fitzwater
said.
   The accord calls for disbanding and resettling the rebels, known
as Contras, by the first week of December. It also urges that the
U.S.-backed government of El Salvador and the leftist guerrillas
resume peace negotiations.
   On Thursday, Defense Minister Humberto Ortega publicly ordered
the Nicaraguan army to extend ``all guarantees of personal safety''
to any Contras who want to return home.
   Ortega _ President Daniel Ortega's brother _ said in a
communique that he ordered the action after learning that Col.
Enrique Bermudez and other top Contra military leaders living in
Miami applied for asylum in the United States.
   About 11,000 Contras and 12,000 dependents live in squalid camps
in southern Honduras, near the Nicaraguan border. For the past
year, they have received only non-lethal aid from the United States
such as boots and foodstuffs.
   President Ortega has promised to hold free and fair national
elections on Feb. 25. He also got Nicaragua's 20 opposition
political parties to back the peace plan.
   A spokesman for Protestant denominations in Nicaragua said,
``all U.S. churches could use the accord as a weapon to demand that
their government should not interfere in the region's affairs.''
   The Rev. Miguel Angelo Caso, an evangelist, called the Tela
accord ``a painful and bloody birth, in which a spark of life is
present.''
   In San Jose, Costa Rica, President Oscar Arias received a
message from Mikhail Gorbachev in which the Soviet president said
Moscow would send no more arms to Nicaragua.
   In a message transmitted Thursday to Arias by Alexander Mokanuu,
vice president of the Soviet Parliament, Gorbachev told reporters
he supports the Central American peace plan.
   Both the Soviet Union and Cuba have supplied the Sandinistas
with weapons and military assistance for the past eight years.
   In San Salvador, members of a commission promoting peace talks
between the rightist government and Marxist-led guerrillas said
Thursday they found good will and determination on both sides to
solve the 9-year-old war.
   A Salvadoran rebel spokeswoman told a Honduran radio station the
guerrilla army ``is willing to lay down its weapons in order to
achieve a lasting peace in El Salvador.''
   The commission comprises the three main opposition political
parties.
   Four rounds of negotiations between 1984 and 1987 failed to
produce a breakthrough toward ending El Salvador's civil war, in
which an estimated 70,000 people have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
