<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland-Warning     08-11 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland-Warning,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scotland Yards Warns of Possible Terrorist Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist squad issued a
warning Thursday that terrorists might bomb targets on the British
mainland to mark the 20th anniversary next week of the deployment
of troops in Northern Ireland.
   The Irish Republican Army was not named in the statement, which
urged the public to be vigilant during ``this emotive time in
Ireland's history.''
   But the IRA has waged a bloody campaign, mainly in Northern
Ireland, to drive the British from the Protestant-controlled
province and unite it with the mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
   The IRA has hit British targets on the European continent and
waged bomb campaigns on the British mainland _ including a bomb
attempt on the life of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and her
Cabinet on Oct. 12, 1984.
   A new barrier designed to guard against suicide car-bombers was
being installed Thursday at Downing Street, where the prime
minister has her office and residence.
   Monday marks the 20th anniversary of the arrival of British
troops in the province.
   ``Attacks on the mainland against commercial and other
non-military targets during this period cannot be ruled out,'' a
Scotland Yard spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   He urged people to be on the lookout for suspicious packages,
especially on the London subway, on buses and in department stores.
</TEXT>
