<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--HorseRescue     08-11 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Horse Rescue,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Free Horse From Well</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emergency workers used a tow truck to haul
an 1,100-pound horse out of an abandoned well Thursday after the
animal fell into water up to its neck.
   ``It's a good thing he didn't go down head first,'' said Bob
Miller, an associate professor at the University of Missouri
veterinary school.
   Boone County firefighter and University veterinary faculty and
students helped rescue Marty, a 4-year-old gelding. Marty was
turned loose Wednesday with some dairy cows in an oat field in west
Audrain County.
   ``We turned the horse and the cows in here so they could eat the
oats,'' said Perry Miller, who lives on the farm. ``We never
thought about the well.''
   There are no barriers around the well. When the horse failed to
appear by Thursday morning, Miller, who is not related to Bob
Miller, went looking for Marty and found him with his head above
the fetid water.
   Bob Miller was lowered by rope into the 4-foot-deep hole and
tranquilized the animal. He helped loop a rope around the animal's
shoulders, and the tow truck pulled Marty free.
</TEXT>
