<DOCNO> AP890811-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-`Mancuso     08-11 0839</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-`Mancuso,' Adv 15,0861</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, Aug. 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Writer sees FBI Agent Nick Mancuso as Old-Fashioned Idealist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Writer-producer Steve Sohmer says he sees the
hero of his upcoming NBC series as an old-fashioned idealist who's
a dinosaur in today's FBI.
   The show ``Mancuso, FBI,'' starring Robert Loggia as Nick
Mancuso, is a spinoff from the miniseries thriller ``Favorite Son.''
   Sohmer, who wrote the best-selling novel about political
corruption in Washington, and adapted it for the miniseries, said
what excites him most about Mancuso is that idealism.
   ``He's had a lifelong love affair with the Constitution,'' he
said. ``But when you look at him you know only blind justice would
choose this man as her champion. Everyone underestimates him. He's
the hero of the 1990s because he believes passionately in his
country and wishes the country would live up to its principles.''
   The miniseries, which ran last fall prior to the presidential
election, told of a conspiracy to boost the candidacy of a handsome
senator for vice president. At the time, Republicans protested that
there were certain similarities to candidate Dan Quayle. Sohmer
pointed out that the book was written and the miniseries was filmed
long before anyone knew Quayle would be the Republican candidate
for vice president.
   Mancuso, along with his secretary, played by Randi Brazen, and
Charles Siebert as the head of forensics, are holdovers from the
miniseries. New members of the cast are Lindsay Frost as a Justice
Department lawyer and a special agent in charge, yet to be cast.
   Sohmer is executive producer of ``Mancuso, FBI,'' which will be
filmed in Los Angeles with some second-unit work in Washington.
   ``Mancuso is a very personal guy with me,'' said Sohmer. ``He's
a character based on an amalgam of things I feel, some of my
father, my grandfather.
   ``He's a guy in a $10 suit who can never get his tie all the way
up. He's not prepossessing. He's a man who's a first-generation
American born to immigrant parents who taught him this is the
greatest country in the world. After college and law school, he
joined the Army out of patriotism and became a military policeman.
There he was recruited for the FBI.''
   Sohmer said he has asked for FBI cooperation in filming the
series, but said he will not give the agency script approval.
   ``I want to make this as close to FBI policy, rules and
procedures as possible,'' he said. Agents who have seen the show's
FBI office set say it's authentic.
   ``But this really isn't a show about the FBI. It's about people
in trouble, American ideals, the law and how people try to subvert
those ideals and place themselves above the law. It's David vs.
Goliath.''
   Each episode begins with what appears to be a run-of-the-mill
case. But it soon turns into a crime where the stakes are very high.
   An investigation of a murder at a Department of Energy facility
turns out to be a plot by one of our allies to steal fissionable
material. In another story, the press uncovers what appears to be
the womanizing past of a cabinet appointee. But Mancuso discovers a
plot to discredit the appointee.
   In addition to his writing and his producing duties for
``Mancuso,'' Sohmer recently became president of Nelson Television.
Doing triple-duty leads to a schedule in which he begins writing at
five in the morning. At eight, he conducts story conferences for
the series, and at 11 he goes to his office at Nelson.
   His second book, ``The Russian Doll,'' will be published soon by
G.P. Putnam's Sons. It involves a military conspiracy during the
Strategic Arms Reduction Talks. The leading character is a woman
Air Force lieutenant.
   Sohmer is a former executive at CBS and NBC and a former
president of Columbia Pictures.
   When ``Favorite Son'' was published three years ago, Brandon
Tartikoff, president of NBC Entertainment, and his wife, Lily,
volunteered to be hosts of a book party.
   ``When I got to the party Brandon said, `I want to do a
miniseries and then make the cop a series.''' Sohmer recalled. ``I
was on top of the world.''
   Sohmer also wrote the upcoming NBC movie, ``Hidden Rage,''
starring Jaclyn Smith as a Chicago policewoman who returns to her
hometown to confront the man who raped her 20 years before.
   Next up, he will write two miniseries. He was reluctant to give
details, but described one as ``a look at America in turmoil in the
1960s.'' The other is set in Washington.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   HAND-HELD HILARITY _ ABC Television is looking for home videos
for a new show called ``America's Funniest Home Videos.'' The
hour-long variety show for later this season is asking for home
videos that include silly blunders at parties, weddings and
sporting events, celebrity impersonations, unexpected foul ups,
oddball news events, animal antics, kids and ``just about anything
else.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, Aug. 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
