<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Grebenshikov Adv14   08-11 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Grebenshikov, Adv 14,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, Aug 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Grebenshikov Brings Musical Glasnost to West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life as a rock star in pre-glasnost Russia
wasn't all-night parties, screaming fans or MTV promos. Boris
Grebenshikov didn't deal with groupies; he was questioned by the
KGB.
   ``They would talk to me, and tell me, `Don't say a word to
anyone.' And of course, I would tell everyone. It was the only
weapon I had,'' said Grebenshikov, an underground rock phenomenon
in the Soviet Union since 1972.
   Grebenshikov survived his outlaw status, releasing a dozen
``albums'' _ actually bootlegged cassettes _ through the Soviet
Union's black market. Things are different now; he sits in a
friend's Manhattan penthouse apartment to discuss ``Radio
Silence,'' his debut Western album.
   ``My life was saved by rock 'n' roll. Absolutely,'' said
Grebenshikov, speaking perfect English while chain-smoking Soviet
cigarettes.
   He worked without his band, Aquarium, on ``Radio Silence.''
Instead, Grebenshikov hooked up with Dave Stewart of Eurythmics,
who produced the album. Other high-powered help was brought in as
well _ Stewart's partner, Annie Lennox, the Pretenders' Chrissie
Hynde and actor Harry Dean Stanton all contribute vocals to the
album.
   While Grebenshikov appreciates their help and friendship, this
rock 'n' roll innocent's introduction to the music industry in the
United States has been less than pleasant.
   An appearance on ``Late Night With David Letterman'' rankled;
Letterman insisted on talking about how much money Grebenshikov
might make. Grebenshikov filmed a rush-job video in Times Square;
asked about it, he sadly shakes his head.
   The non-stop promotional whirl, which includes a tour now
underway, also was a shock. And there's the emphasis on selling
records, which Grebenshikov dismisses with a two-syllable American
obscenity.
   ``You go to Tower Records, and you have rows and rows of
product, but maybe three or four good records,'' he says,
disdainfully.
   This wasn't what Grebenshikov knew as rock 'n' roll when he sat
in his bedroom in the Soviet Union, twisting the radio dial in a
frantic search for the music which he said would set him free.
   Each Beatles single was a revelation. His early exposure to Bob
Dylan had the same intense effect on him as it did on a New Jersey
teen-ager a world away, Bruce Springsteen.
   ``I remember hearing `I Want You.' I could understand about
maybe 70 percent, but I thought to myself: This is it. This is the
sound,'' said Grebenshikov, 35, who wrote in English for the first
time on ``Radio Silence.''
   He went on to form Aquarium in 1972. In short order, he was both
kicked out of the Communist Youth League for his musical efforts
and dubbed the Soviet Dylan; he also became the focus of Eric
Clapton-esque graffiti (``Boris is God'') in Leningrad.
   Grebenshikov is unsure how many Aquarium tapes are out there in
the Soviet Union; once the group was legitimized by the government,
its first three albums sold 3{ million copies on the official
Melodiya label.
   Not that numbers matter to the charismatic Grebenshikov; they
don't. Neither does a perfect mix or exacting production on his
records; he's more interested in how a record feels when he listens
to it.
   ``I don't really care how good it sounds. I care about, what am
I doing? Is the inspiration here? 'Cause people tend to hide behind
the sound. ... Even if it's a perfect thing, sounds great _ I don't
care, I just don't care,'' says Grebenshikov.
   ``Give me some sounds, so we can fly with it, we can soar with
it. ... I don't care about how it sounds. If it's right, it's
right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Aug. 14</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
