<DOCNO> AP890811-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1348EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-Gadhafi'sRevolution Adv20-1stadd   08-11 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gadhafi's Revolution, Adv 20-1st add,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRIPOLI: harboring him.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Western diplomats, some citing Palestinian sources, say
there are reports that Gadhafi has stopped giving money to terror
groups such as Abu Nidal's, most likely because of their ties to
Moslem fundamentalism.
   But the diplomats add that there are other unconfirmed reports
that guerrilla training bases still operate in the Libyan desert.
   The diplomats say they have heard reports that the alleged
chemical weapons plant at Rabta, 60 miles southwest of Tripoli, has
been dismantled. But they caution it could be rebuilt later.
   Last December, President Reagan said he could not rule out a
military strike to destroy the plant that Gadhafi insisted was
designed to manufacture pharmaceuticals. The tensions over the
plant escalated in January when U.S. warplanes shot down two Libyan
MiGs in the Mediterranean.
   Some Libyans insist their life has improved during the 20 years
of Gadhafi's rule.
   ``Before the people didn't have houses, there were no schools,
no streets,'' said one. ``Now the people have houses, schools and
streets.''
   The Western diplomats said over the years Gadhafi has squandered
billions on arms, military adventure and prestige projects.
   The most obvious changes are in the shops. Gadhafi's socialist
policies had forced most shops to close years ago, leading to
shortages and blackmarket prices. The colonel had all but stopped
imports of consumer goods, allowing only a few to be sold through
giant state companies. In 1985, he expelled thousands of foreign
workers while at the same time his revolutionary system forbade
Libyans from working for other Libyans under most circumstances.
   Last year, Gadhafi began allowing small businesses to import
some goods for sale.
   Now about two-thirds of the shops in the Arab market and central
Tripoli are open. The shelves are stocked with household goods,
jewelry and cheaply made clothes from Malta, Tunisia, Yugolavia,
Romania and Italy.
   Barefoot weavers toil at ancient looms in the old quarter while
other craftsmen etch designs in decorative copper or brass plates.
   Private fruit, vegetable and meat stores are open all over the
city. But the shelves are still barren in the vast,
government-owned People's Markets, which are combination department
stores and supermarkets.
   At noon one recent day the food shelves on one People's Market
store had only bottled fruit drinks, canned fish, processed cheese
from Holland, tea from China, jars of honey, cans of condensed
milk, Turkish detergent and large burlap sacks of sugar.
   Diplomats said the new openness led to price gouging that
prompted the government to close some shops.
   Near Sabatrah, 50 miles west of Tripoli, scores of shops and
storefronts have been reduced to rubble by government bulldozers.
   ``You see it everywhere,'' one diplomat said. ``The official
reason is that the shops were illegal, they did not have the proper
licenses and building permits.''
   But a young Libyan businessman said, ``I think this is a good
idea because it will teach respect for the law.''
   Gadhafi's policies make it difficult, but not impossible, to
have a successful business, said the businessman who used his own
money to start a restaurant and two wholesale food supply
businesses.
   Still he acknowledges that for most people without their own
money there is a sense of hopelessness.
   ``My dream,'' said a young government employee, ``is to go to
America.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 20</NOTE>
