<FIRST>s w AM-Pell-Schneider Adv13   08-11 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pell-Schneider, Adv13,0854</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, Aug. 13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pell Re-election Campaign Inactive As Schneider Gears Up For Senate
Challenge</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, is acting like a man who doesn't want
to be a senator for six more years.
   While other senators up for re-election next year have already
raised hundreds of thousands _ and in some cases several million _
dollars, Pell's fund-raising activities have been moribund.
   The 31 senators who have established campaign committees for a
1990 re-election bid raised an average of nearly $750,000 each
during the first six months of this year.
   But, according to campaign disclosure reports filed at the
Federal Election Commission, Pell received just a single $5,000
contribution during the same period.
   The numbers are more curious considering the 70-year-old
Democrat is likely to face his toughest race in 18 years.
   Since his hard-fought 1972 victory over Republican John H.
Chafee, who went on to win the state's other Senate seat four years
later, Pell has won re-elections in 1978 and 1984 by 3-to-1 margins
against weak Republican opponents.
   But next year, Pell likely would face Claudine Schneider, an
ambitious and popular five-term congresswoman.
   Miss Schneider, who has all-but-announced a Senate run, reported
more than $200,000 in campaign contributions to her House
re-election committee for the January-June FEC reporting period.
She raised only one-fifth that amount during the corresponding
period two years ago.
   ``When he knows he could face someone as aggressive as Claudine
Schneider, I don't see how he can afford to take that passive
attitude,'' said Wendy DeMocher, a spokeswoman for the National
Republican Senatorial Committee
   Pell aides say the senator's lack of fund raising is not a sign
that he is waffling on whether to run, but an outgrowth of his
concerns that the campaign season has become too long.
   ``He has said repeatedly he has every intention of running,''
said a senior Pell aide who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``He just feels very strongly that the campaign process has gotten
out of hand.''
   ``He's just practicing what he preaches,'' said Anita Dunn, a
spokeswoman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
   Pell, however, apparently did not feel that way in previous
elections. In the first six months of 1983, the year before his
last campaign, the senator raised nearly $100,000 in preparation
for a campaign that was considered laughably easy.
   Pell does have $444,686 in his campaign coffers in preparation
for 1990, but 21 of the 30 other senators running next year have
more, according to newly filed FEC documents.
   National GOP campaign strategists, who have virtually ignored
Pell in past races, have targeted the senator as one of the six
incumbent Democrats they will aggressively try to push out of the
Senate next year.
   Pell is one of the most popular politicians in Rhode Island
history, winning his Senate seat in 1960 by defeating two former
governors in a primary and going on to win in 1966, 1972, 1978 and
1984.
   He has been a leading advocate for the arts and education, and
in 1986 he rose to chairman of the powerful Senate Foreign
Relations Committee.
   But chairmen of that committee have in the past suffered at
re-election time, attacked by challengers who charge that they are
paying too much attention to international problems and not enough
to parochial concerns. Five years ago, Democrat Paul Simon
successfully challenged then-Foreign Relations Chairman Charles
Percy, R-Ill.
   Pell is vulnerable in other areas, not least of which is his
preoccupation with psychic powers.
   Miss Schneider could be a formiddable candidate.
   She has broad statewide recognition since Rhode Island has only
two House seats. And she is just the type of Republican that
Democrat-dominated Rhode Island likes _ a liberal on social issues
with a strong environmental record. She came to Congress by the
rarest of routes _ defeating a Democratic incumbent _ and has won
re-election by Pell-like margins ever since.
   The change of administrations at the White House also will help
the congresswoman. While it is questionable how much support she
would have received from conservatives running the party in the
Reagan years, Miss Schneider already has had First Lady Barbara
Bush featured at a lucrative fund-raiser.
   Age also could become a major factor in the race.
   Miss Schneider is 42, the same age Pell was when he first came
to the Senate nearly 30 years ago.
   Pell will be 71 in November and would be 78 at the end of
another six-year term.
   Pell, however, would still be a youngster compared to his
predecessor. Theodore Green came to the Senate at age 69 and
retired in 1960 at age 93.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Christopher Callahan, a regional reporter for
The Associated Press, has covered New England policies and politics
from Washington since 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
