<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1350EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-SouthKorea-Women Adv20-2Takes   08-11 0804</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea-Women, Adv 20-2 Takes,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Feminists Demand Change in South Korea's Male-Dominated Society</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although few in number, South Korean
feminists have mounted an attack on a deeply rooted culture that
encourages women to be dutiful and subservient to their fathers,
husbands and sons.
   The movement has yet to take hold on a broad scale and a major
effort still looms ahead, but the feminists say South Korea no
longer can afford to treat its women as servants and sexual objects.
   They maintain the nation's remarkable economic growth owes much
to women's labors and that the transition from authoritarian to
democratic government will not be complete until women's rights are
assured.
   ``Demand your equal rights,'' reads a headline in the
50,000-circulation Women's News, a weekly.
   Yet, cabarets, barber shops and bars still provide sexual
services to men, and authorities say hundreds, possibly thousands,
of young women are kidnapped each year or forced into prostitution.
   In companies, many male managers make no secret of passing over
women for promotions. Some companies fire women who marry and as
recently as a year ago banks rarely allowed pregnant women to serve
the public.
   When 14 women were appointed last year to head women's
provincial programs, the government called the move a major step
forward. But one appointee said she was shown to her new office
``across from the toilet'' and another contended the government
lumped women, old people and children together ``in order to
dispose of us easily.''
   Women comprise up to 50 percent of the work force and many
thousands of South Korean women have college educations, yet they
still receive half the wages of men, are denied promotions and
often are discriminated against in th courts.
   ``Men are afraid if we have our own identity, our own career,
our own viewpoints, that they are losing something,'' says the only
woman in President Roh Tae-woo's Cabinet, Kim Yung-chung.
   The challenges are formidable and require a change of attitude
in both sexes as well as enforcement of laws, says Chung Il-sook,
president of Ewha, the nation's oldest and largest school for
women, a catalyst in the women's movement. She says change, though
painfully slow, is inevitable.
   Korean feminists concede their movement faces an uphill
struggle. In a nation of 42 million people, only a few thousand are
actively lobbying for women's rights.
   Advocates hope, however, that the establishment of local
assemblies in 1990 will be a turning point to lure women into
politics and they see potential allies in more than 2,500 women's
organizations around the country.
   Paek Young-ok, an Ewha professor, says Korean women need to be
given the opportunity to participate in the political process to
ensure that women play a permanent and far-reaching role in
government and laws affecting their lives.
   ``Fully one-half of the entire adult population have been all
but invisible in political terms,'' she says. Paek blames this on
sex-role conceptions and the limitations of political opportunity.
   A 1988 equal employment act guarantees employment opportunities
for women and the employment security act calls for increasing the
options for women's work. But feminists say that without
enforcement, the words are window dressing.
   ``The provisions are perfect,'' said Kim, the Cabinet member who
oversees policy for women. ``But our job is to narrow the gap
between legal provisions and practices ... to fully implement the
provisions.''
   The first woman to run for president, Hong Suk-ja, became so
exasperated that she told a news conference two years ago, ``I am
prepared to do everything humanly possible but strip tease to help
emancipate Korean women.''
   In nearby Japan, a record 22 women were elected recently to the
upper house of Parliament, an event cheered by Korean feminists,
who failed to elect one woman to the last National Assembly in
Seoul.
   Networking among Korean professional women has taken root with
breakfast and luncheon clubs. Women can attend training courses to
prepare for politics or business, and telephone hotline numbers are
available for women in need. Concerts of women composers and
women's cinema festivals now are being held.
   Yet many women show no sign of joining the struggle. It's common
for a wife to stay in the kitchen when a family entertains or, if
she's at the table, not to speak in deference to her husband. Even
radical students demanding sweeping change ignore women's rights
and treat women as cheerleaders instead of policy makers.
   ``Some say I'm a feminist,'' President Roh said at a news
conference. ``I got a lot of votes from women in my last election.''
   But his wife, Kim Ok-sook, remains dutifully in his shadow,
usually appearing in public walking behind him and rarely speaking
to the press.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890811-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1351EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-SouthKorea-Women Adv20-1stadd   08-11 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-South Korea-Women, Adv 20-1st add,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 20 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>SEOUL: the press.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The head of the leading opposition party, Kim Dae-jung, came
under attack after his wife, Lee Hee-ho, gave speeches in the last
presidential campaign.
   ``Democracy begins at home,'' she said one speech, urging South
Koreans not to discriminate between male and female children.
   A door plaque at Kim's residence lists his wife's name alongside
his, a rarity and a source of disdain among some of their neighbors.
   Surveys indicate that despite growing sensitivity to women's
expanding roles in society, both sexes expect women to remain
subservient and both consider lower wages for women ``natural.''
   The government says 45 to 50 percent of the 20 million-member
work force are women, half in unskilled or semi-skilled
manufacturing and assembly-line jobs.
   Feminists charge that women face discrimination at every level.
They note that only nine of the country's 1,798 lawyers and 24 of
the 1,008 judges are women.
   The government-run Korean Women's Development Institute,
established in 1983, says the deeply rooted, male-oriented
mentality of Korean culture has led to most women feeling inferior
to men, an attitude it says prolongs discrimination.
   Acceptance of women's second-class role is linked to the
500-year-old teachings of Confucius, who stressed the role of men
and felt that the woman's place was to serve, to obey her husband
and bear him a son.
   ``Women are never to ask questions but are supposed to do what
men tell them,'' says a businesswoman. ``Women are losing patience,
and the younger the woman, the less patience she has.''
   Traditionally Korean women were identified not by name, but by a
reference relative to the men in their lives.
   They were known as so-and-so's daughter, so-and-so's wife and in
old age, so-and-so's mother. So few people knew their mother's
given name that after the 1950-53 Korean War divided the peninsula,
officials had difficulty uniting families.
   ``The culture is changing,'' said Ewha's Dr. Chung. To
democratize South Korea and continue its economic growth, she said,
the nation needs ``to mobilize its full human resources. Why should
women be restricted?''
   Demands of women's groups include changing family law in which
males benefit more than females in marriage, divorce and
inheritance.
   ``If women of advanced training and high caliber are to be
excluded from our social system for no other reason than that they
are not men, it will be a great loss and a waste of valuable
resources,'' said a recent editorial in the Korea Herald.
   Women labor union leaders say impoverished factory workers are
joining educated women in demanding change. Male managers complain,
as one put it, that women who once ``kept their mouths shut now
scream about hours and wages.''
   Union activist Lee Kyong-ja has a college degree and worked 20
years for the Korea Development Bank. Her efforts to unionize women
at the bank resulted in demotion, a 14-day hunger strike and
dismissal before she was reinstated as a union chief.
   ``Women should learn to complain, negotiate, and fight, no
matter how much time and pain it may take, because it's a long way
that we have to go,'' she said.
   ``Education is the real hope for women's rights,'' says Chang
Pil-wha, head of Ewha's 12-year-old women's studies department, the
first established in Asia. Some 2,000 of Ewha's 17,000 students
take courses each semester in women's issues.
   ``People must recognize women as social beings,'' said Yoon
Seon-young, a college junior. ``We cannot be discriminated against
any longer.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
