<FIRST>u f BC-Hilton     08-11 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hilton,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hotel Chain Puts Itself Up For Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hilton Hotel Corp. put itself up for sale
Thursday, telling its financial advisers to seek buyers for the
whole company or its lodging and gaming divisions.
   The advisers, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Eastdil Realty
Inc., have been surveying the giant hotel-gambling company's
properties since mid-June. They reported on that survey at a board
meeting Thursday, company spokesman William Lebo said.
   Lebo said Beverly Hills-based Hilton would consider selling its
lodging segment and its casino operations in Nevada and Australia
separately.
   ``Management indicated that a package of confidential
information relative to the company will be available in
September,'' the company said in a statement.
   Hilton has been considered a takeover candidate since May 8,
when Barron Hilton settled a long-running dispute over the estate
of his late father, company founder Conrad Hilton, with the Conrad
N. Hilton Foundation.
   The settlement gave Barron Hilton control of about 25 percent of
Hilton stock, and he said May 11 the company would consider serious
buyout bids.
   Lebo said numerous potential buyers had inquired about Hilton,
but declined to elaborate except to say that interest was worldwide.
   ``With a company with a name like ours, you could find buyers
literally anywhere, Hong Kong, Japan,'' he said.
   Hilton stock was trading at $63 per share when the estate
dispute was settled.
   The New York Stock Exchange suspended trading of Hilton stock
when the buyout announcement was made.
   After trading resumed, the stock closed down $3.87{ at $108. The
stock had hit to a 52-week high of $111.87{ Wednesday on reports
that the board was considering at least two formal buyout bids.
   Hilton has about 48 million shares outstanding.
   Hilton owns 12 hotels, including the Waldorf Astoria and the Las
Vegas and Flamingo Hiltons in Nevada, and manages 12 hotels it owns
in partnership with others.
   The company manages 18 hotels in which it has no ownership
interest and franchises about 240 Hilton Inns.
   Hilton also has two Las Vegas casinos, another in Reno, Nev., is
building another in Laughlin, Nev., and has a 10 percent interest
in a hotel-casino in Queensland, Australia.
   The company last year earned $130.9 million on revenue of $915.4
million.
</TEXT>
