<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-Jacobs     08-11 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Jacobs,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jacobs and Avon Talk About Company's Business Outlook</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Irwin L. Jacobs, who has made a bid of
about $2.85 billion for Avon Products Inc., has had a meeting with
the chairman of the big cosmetics company but a possible sale of
Avon wasn't on the agenda.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer,
talked about the company's business plans with Jacobs for about 1{
hours during a meeting Thursday at Avon's New York headquarters,
Avon spokesman John Cox said.
   Cox described the meeting as ``amicable.'' The two men met
alone, without financial advisers or other assistants, Cox said.
   ``The two men had a full and complete discussion of Avon's
recently announced business plans,'' Avon said in a news release
issued after the meeting. ``As agreed to before the meeting, there
were no discussions about the sale of the company.''
   Jacobs, who oversees his holdings from a base in Minneapolis,
wasn't immediately available for comment.
   Earlier this week, Jacobs said he was evaluating what
alternatives he has in his pursuit of Avon. Avon's board on Aug. 3
rejected Jacobs' proposed $41-a-share bid.
   A document submitted to the Securities and Exchange Commission
and made public Tuesday said Jacobs would continue to ``evaluate
his alternatives with respect to the company.'' Jacobs' bid would
be worth about $2.85 billion, if he redeemed Avon's preferred
shares as well as buying the company's nearly 55 million shares of
common stock.
   ``Among the factors to be considered in such evaluation will be
that which transpires at or arising from any meetings with
representatives of the company,'' Jacobs' SEC filing said.
   In a letter to Jacobs to inform him that the Avon board rejected
the offer, Preston had said he would agree to meet with Jacobs to
discuss the company's business plans ``but not to negotiate the
sale of the company.''
   Jacobs, in a partnership with Amway Corp., holds about 10.3
percent of Avon's common stock outstanding. Jacobs has said that he
was acting on his own _ without Amway _ in making the attempt to
get control of Avon.
   Avon, the world's biggest direct sales company and a major
beauty products concern, has fended off other suitors recently and
has taken steps to speed its financial turnaround.
   In May, Avon rejected a $39-a-share, or $2.1 billion, takeover
offer from direct-sales rival Amway. It also brushed off advances
from Mary Kay Corp., parent of door-to-door makeup seller Mary Kay
Cosmetics.
   The company has been in the process of selling off its health
care services operations to concentrate on its core beauty and
personal care products business.
</TEXT>
