<FIRST>r f PM-Hooker     08-11 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hooker,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.J. Hooker Gets Line of Credit to Help in Reorganization</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lower-case ``biggs'' is correct.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L.J. Hooker Corp.'s reorganization under federal
bankruptcy laws and an influx of credit should keep the company's
stores stocked and projects afloat, the new manager of the company
says.
   Officials of General Electric Capital Corp. said Thursday a
proposed $50 million ``debtor-in-possession'' credit line was
intended to help Hooker get back on its feet. The proposal is
subject to approval by the U.S. bankruptcy court.
   L.J. Hooker, the Atlanta-based U.S. subsidiary of Australia's
Hooker Corp., filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the federal
Bankruptcy Code in New York on Wednesday.
   The borrowing under GE Capital's proposed line of credit is to
be secured by certain assets of L.J. Hooker, including inventories
of the Bonwit Teller and B. Altman &amp; Co. store chains, said Jeffery
H. Coates, senior vice president of G.E. Capital's Corporate
Finance Group.
   Meanwhile, vendors reportedly are balking at selling merchandise
to Bonwit Teller and Altman's due to the parent company's financial
difficulties.
   The Wall Street Journal reported today that several vendors have
said they will sell merchandise only on a cash basis to the two
department store chains.
   Sanford C. Sigoloff, a turnaround expert, who has been hired by
L.J. Hooker to manage the company during reorganization, told the
Journal that the reaction of vendors isn't surprising.
   ``There's nothing strange about the vendor reaction, because
this company hasn't been the best corporate citizen in terms of
payment,'' he said. ``Our job is to essentially work with the
trade, give them cash before delivery, and then develop a
relationship that allows them to give us trade credit.''
   Coates said the presence of Sigoloff played a role in the
decision by G.E. Capital to extend the credit line. GE Capital is a
subsidiary of General Electric Co.
   ``It is a time to take the pressure out of the pressure
cooker,'' Sigoloff said in an interview with The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. ``We have to jump-start this company, which
has been starved for cash. Now the test is who gets the cash and
how much.''
   He said the priority would be to L.J. Hooker's ``customers,''
those who have bought L.J. Hooker homes and who shop in the
company's department stores. ``We are going to clean the slate and
get going again,'' he said.
   Sigoloff, who will meet with Hooker creditors later this month,
has rehabilitated several financially troubled companies, including
Wickes Companies Inc., a California-based retailer that also was in
Chapter 11.
   While some of L.J. Hooker's holdings were not included in the
bankruptcy filing, analysts said that might be because they already
are in negotiations with potential purchasers.
   Anthony McLellan, a former president of L.J. Hooker who is
trying to purchase the L.J. Hooker homes division, said, ``I
understand that (Sigoloff) is interested in disposing of the
assets.''
   ``I expect he'll be interested in meeting people who are
interested buying,'' said McLellan.
   Meanwhile Thursday, the anchor store of Thornton Town Center, an
L.J. Hooker mall development in Denver, said it would open as
scheduled next month despite the company's financial problems.
   In Denver, bigg's, called Colorado's first ``hypermarket,''
announced its scheduled Sept. 20 opening at Thornton Town Center
would not be affected by the L.J. Hooker filing.
   L.J. Hooker is the mall's main developer, and bigg's is slated
to be the 700,000-square foot shopping center's main tenant.
   Pierre Weaver, executive vice president of Hyper Shoppes,
bigg's' parent company, said the store can be successful regardless
of the mall's fate.
   L.J. Hooker has subsidiaries in the development and retail
markets. In a statement Wednesday, Sigoloff said the bankruptcy
filing, which includes L.J. Hooker Homes, will allow the company to
restructure and repay debts, which total about $1.2 billion.
   Under Chapter 11, a federal court order frees the company from
the threat of creditors' lawsuits until it can develop a plan to
put its finances in order. The reorganization plan must be accepted
by a majority of the creditors.
</TEXT>
