<TEXT>
   The stock market churned ahead in active trading
today, bidding to reach record highs with encouragement from
unexpectedly favorable news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 12.71 to
2,725.34 by 11 a.m. on Wall Street, surpassing the closing peak of
2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 5 to 3 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 738 up, 422
down and 585 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 74.65 million shares at
midmorning.
   The Dow Jones industrial average made a short-lived run Thursday
afternoon past its peak of two summers ago, but then fell back in
late trading.
   This morning, analysts said buyers drew some fresh inspiration
from evidence that inflationary pressures have eased significantly
as the economy has slowed.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods dropped 0.4 percent in July, posting its biggest
decline in three years. Advance estimates in the financial world
had called for the index to be unchanged or modestly higher.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets after the figures were
reported. Prices of long-term government bonds rose nearly $10 for
each $1,000 in face value, putting their yields just below 8
percent.
