<FIRST>r d BC-SearsCuts     08-11 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sears Cuts,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sears Cuts 104 Jobs at Telemarketing Headquarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. said it will reduce by
nearly half the 250-member workforce at its telemarketing operation
as part of continuing cutbacks in its merchandise group staff.
   Sears, which this week cut jobs in its catalog headquarters,
said Wednesday that 104 of the employees at its suburban Chicago
facility, most of them part time, will be terminated at the
company's credit telemarketing and shop-at-home direct-marketing
services departments by Oct. 6.
   Many of those remaining in the two departments will be part-time
workers, as opposed to full time.
   ``The reason for this reorganization is that their business is
cyclical,'' said a Sears spokeswoman. ``We want better coverage on
the phones, and part-time employees are more suited to that.''
   The credit telemarketing operation, which handles 800-number
credit inquiries and credit solicitation, will move to existing
facilities in Knoxville, Tenn., in October. About 80 jobs in that
department, including those of 20 full-time workers, will be
eliminated.
   In the direct-response department, 24 full-time workers will be
cut, leaving 136 part-time workers behind to handle the job.
   The cuts are all part of Sears' previously announced
wide-ranging restructuring program, which includes reducing its
Sears Merchandise Group staff. Sears is the nation's largest
retailer.
</TEXT>
