<DOCNO> AP890811-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     08-11 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices surged in early trading today,
driven by a new government report on wholesale prices that
suggested inflation is under control.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond rose ~ point, or about $8.75 per
$1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from price, plunged to 7.91 percent from 8.05 percent
late Thursday.
   The Labor Department reported today that wholesale prices fell
0.4 percent in July for their biggest decline in three years.
Prices were pushed down by declining costs for gasoline and new
cars, the report said.
   The drop, as measured by the government's Producer Price Index,
followed a 0.1 percent dip in June, as the wholesale inflation
gauge registered its first back-to-back monthly declines since
early 1986.
   ``The bond market is stronger based on the Producer Price
Index,'' said Mitchell Held, managing director, chief financial
economist, Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
   The market had anticipated a rise of 0.1 to 0.2 percent, Held
said.
   The report is good news to bondholders, whose investments are
devalued by inflation. It also bolstered arguments of economists
that inflationary pressures will subside in the second half of the
year, giving the Federal Reserve more room to lower interest rates
in an effort to keep the economy out of a recession.
   Analysts said the credit markets took little notice of a second
government report on retail sales, which shot up 0.9 percent last
month to the highest level in three months. In addition, the
government revised upward May and June sales.
   ``The PPI is clearly outweighing the retail figures,'' said
Irwin L. Kellner, chief economist at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Credit market analysts said prices could reverse course once the
market digests the retail numbers.
   ``We thought consumer spending was in a recession and all of a
sudden we see that it has been rising,'' said Held. ``This could
influence the Fed's decision about easing credit.
   ``The Fed cannot ease unless we get some clearcut evidence that
this economy is weak and it simply isn't there,'' he said.
   Analysts said a healthy response to Thursday's $9.75 billion
refunding auction also carried over to this morning's market and
helped firm prices.
   The Treasury sold the 30-year bonds, which go on sale next week,
at an average yield of 8.14 percent, or slightly more than many
dealers had been expecting a few days ago.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues rose between 1-16 point to 3-32 point,
intermediate maturities were up between [ point and 5-16 point and
long-term securities had soared between 7-16 point and 1 1-32
point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was up 3.95 to 1,193.54 by late
morning.
   In corporate trading, industrials also gained. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 0.80 to 332.58.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, fell to 7.99
percent with the discount down 10 basis points at 7.74 percent.
Yields on six-month bills fell to 7.86 as the discount lost 8 basis
points to 7.47 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 7.91
percent as the discount fell 10 basis points to 7.38 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest rate banks charge each
other for overnight loans, was quoted at 9 percent, unchanged from
late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
