<FIRST>u f AM-RetailSales     08-11 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retail Sales,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Indicate Economic Expansion Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt. Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales, riding a wave of renewed auto
sales, posted a strong 0.9 percent increase in July, the government
said Friday in a report providing fresh evidence the country's
longest peacetime expansion was in no danger of ending.
   ``I think the widespread increase in retail sales indicates the
consumer is alive and well,'' commented Allen Sinai of The Boston
Co. Economic Advisers Inc. in New York. ``Certainly, the data
indicated no imminent recession.''
   ``You aren't going to find any reasonable economist now who will
tell you that we are heading into a recession,'' agreed Michael K.
Evans of Evans Economics Inc. in Washington.
   Economists watch retail sales closely as a barometer of economic
health since they account for about one-third of the nation's
economic activity. There have been fears that recent
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve to contain inflation might
push the nation into a recession.
   But the Fed switched course in June and since then has nudged
interest rates lower in an attempt to attain a so-called
``soft-landing'' _ slower economic growth with low inflation. The
current economic expansion has lasted six and a half years.
   ``Bring out the champagne as far as (Fed Chairman Alan)
Greenspan is concerned,'' Evans said. ``He pulled off what most of
his critics said couldn't be done.''
   The Commerce Department reported retail sales increased to a
seasonally adjusted $143.7 billion last month following a 0.1
percent decline in June. The June sales had been revised to $142.4
billion from the $140.8 billion previously reported.
   The department also sharply revised its May report, saying sales
actually rose 0.8 percent rather than fell 0.1 percent. A spokesman
said the unusually large change resulted from retailers reporting
additional sales, including about $300 million each in the auto and
food categories and $100 million each in the restaurant, building
materials and general merchandise areas.
   Both revisions, together with Friday's report, point to a
stronger economy than previously thought.
   Automobile sales led June's increase, although almost all
categories posted moderate to strong improvements. The exceptions:
furniture and other home furnishings, down 0.3 percent, and
clothing, down 1.5 percent. Gasoline station sales remained flat.
   Car sales, which fell 1 percent in June, rebounded last month
with a huge 2.7 percent increase. That was the best sales month
since October 1988 when purchases rose 4.7 percent.
   July auto sales totaled $31.7 billion, the highest level since
$31.9 billion in December 1988, the department said. The sales
record was $33.9 billion in September 1986.
   Autos represent about 20 percent of total retail sales.
Excluding autos, July retail sales rose 0.4 percent, following
increases of 0.2 percent in June and 1.2 percent in May.
   Both durable and non-durable categories posted increases.
Durables _ big-ticket items expected to last more than three years
_ rose 1.7 percent after falling 0.9 percent in June and 0.5
percent in May. Besides autos and home furnishings, this category
includes building materials, up 0.6 percent.
   Sales of non-durable goods were up 0.4 percent after climbing
0.4 percent in June and 0.2 percent in May. Restaurant sales were
up 1.2 percent; general merchandise including department stores,
0.5 percent; food stores, 0.6 percent; and drug stores, 0.1 percent.
   For the three months from May through July, overall retail sales
were 6 percent higher than the same period in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
