<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1447EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RareEarth     08-11 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rare Earth,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Needs Nation's Permission To Mine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a land with more reindeer and
musk oxen than people, Hecla Mining Co. is hunting for rare
minerals for the electronics industry, a company official says.
   Hecla and two partners began drilling in June on a tract of land
in southeastern Greenland reached only by helicopter. Workers are
looking for deposits of niobium and rare earths, a group of 17
chemically similar elements increasingly in demand.
   ``Rare earths are weird and wonderful things,'' said W. Glen
Zinn, Hecla vice president in charge of exploration. ``They're
strategically critical and mined in only one place in North
America.''
   Hecla, based in Coeur d'Alene, holds 47 percent of the Sarfotoq
project, while Nuna Oil, a Danish national oil company, controls 50
percent. A German mining exploration company called Gewerkschaft
Wilhelm Bergbaugesellschaft holds 3 percent, Zinn said.
   Hecla will spend up to $500,000 this year on Sarfotoq, he said.
Another $4 million could be spent in the next four years if Hecla
decides to proceed with mining.
   The venture is a further step by Hecla into specialty metals. In
March, the company bought a $5.5 million gallium and germanium mine
near St. George, Utah. The metals are used in the making of fiber
optics and infrared lenses.
   Zinn said the partners secured government permission to explore
the area of land estimated at 36 square miles. A license to mine is
needed before production could begin. The site is near a game
refuge for musk oxen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
