<DOCNO> AP890811-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-KohlbergKravis     08-11 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Kohlberg Kravis,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeover Specialists Might Buy Up to 15 Percent of BTR</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. takeover specialists Kohlberg Kravis Roberts
and Co. might buy as much as 15 percent of BTR PLC, a British
industrial conglomerate, the companies said Friday.
   Kohlberg Kravis has filed a statement with the U.S. Federal
Trade Commission indicating it intends to buy $15 million or more
of BTR shares in the open market, BTR said.
   The filing would allow Kohlberg Kravis to buy as much as 15
percent of BTR without making further disclosures to U.S. antitrust
authorities, BTR said. To acquire a 15 percent stake at current
prices would cost $1.9 billion.
   Kohlberg Kravis considers any stake it may build in BTR an
investment, BTR said.
   Kohlberg Kravis later confirmed the announcement, saying it was
``pleased with the receptivity of BTR to KKR being a shareholder in
the company.''
   BTR shares rose 58 cents to $7.28 on London's Stock Exchange.
   With the company's current market value at about $13 billion, a
takeover bid for BTR would rank as Europe's second-largest ever.
Only Hoylake Investments Ltd.'s pending, hostile $21 billion bid
for BAT Industries PLC would be larger.
   John Cahill, BTR's chief executive, said in a telephone
interview from Providence, R.I., that his company didn't believe
Kohlberg Kravis' move was ``sinister,'' and instead may represent a
play for a toehold in the British market at a time when British
stocks are undervalued relative to other markets.
   Kohlberg Kravis' ``past behavior pattern is not one of a hostile
bidder,'' he said.
   BTR produces equipment and components for the construction,
energy, automotive, electrical and other industries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
