<HEAD>Claridge Sale Delayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sale of the Claridge Casino Hotel
to a group of investors headed by a former casino executive has
been delayed past the original closing date of next Tuesday, an
official said Friday.
   A.L.M. Moonstone Inc., the purchasing partnership, was able to
find ``a more advantageous financing approach'' that led to a
paperwork delay, said Alfred J. Luciani, who heads the partnership,
said from his office in Las Vegas.
   The partnership has asked the Claridge board of directors for an
extension to complete its review before the state Casino Control
Commission, he said.
   Bob Renneisen, executive vice president of the Claridge, said
Friday that the board of directors is considering the request for
an extension.
   Luciani, former executive vice president of Golden Nugget Inc.,
and his partners agreed April 15 to buy the financially struggling
Claridge, a 501-room facility one block from the Boardwalk. A
purchase price has not been revealed, but Luciani said the company
plans to spend about $25 million to renovate the building.
   The Claridge lost $20 million in 1988 on revenues of $174.6
million. In June, Claridge Corp. took control of the casino hotel
from the Del Webb Corp. of Phoenix after completing a financial
restructuring plan.
</TEXT>
