<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-11 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Corn Futures Soar The Limit On Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most corn futures prices closed up the daily
limit of 10 cents a bushel Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade
following a government report projecting a lower-than-expected U.S.
corn harvest.
   Other grain and soybean futures closed substantially higher.
   The USDA report, released Thursday afternoon, projected a corn
crop of 7.35 billion bushels compared with expectations of about
7.53 billion bushels.
   The government pegged this year's U.S. soybean production at
1.91 billion bushels compared with market estimates of about 1.95
billion and estimated the spring wheat crop at 487 million bushels
compared with the 493 million estimated earlier.
   The USDA also lowered its estimates for Canadian and Soviet
grain production, suggesting that demand for U.S. grains _
especially wheat _ is likely to increase.
   Analysts said the corn numbers were the most bullish among the
three markets. Soybean prices were held in check by perceptions of
a large South American soybean crop and by the USDA's revision of
its projected soybean stocks figure.
   The agency added 30 million bushels to the size of the projected
soybean stockpile on Aug. 31, the end of the 1988-89 marketing
year. The USDA now expects surplus soybeans to total 155 million
bushels this year.
   ``At first blush it was friendly, but once you got into the
supply-and-demand, it wasn't all that bullish,'' said Pat
O'Connell, grain-market analyst with Refco Inc., a large
Chicago-based futures brokerage.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 4\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.98 a bushel; corn was 5\
cents to 10 cents higher with September at $2.34 a bushel; oats
were 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with September at $1.41{ a bushel;
soybeans were 8 cents to 16} cents higher with August at $6.15 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
