<FIRST>r f AM-PosnerSwap     08-11 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Posner Swap,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financier Declines to Swap Oceanfront Property With State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Victor Posner
has decided to build five 30-story condominium buildings on his
oceanfront property after rejecting a state offer for a land swap.
   The Florida Department of Natural Resources had been trying
since March to persuade the Miami Beach executive to swap his 13
acres of oceanfront property for 67 acres of state-owned land near
the Doral Country Club in Miami.
   The Posner tract, the city's only undeveloped oceanfront land,
is wedged between a strip of high-rises and would have made a
perfect setting for a park, state officials said.
   But Posner thought the swap would not have been profitable for
him, said his attorney, William J. Roberts.
   The Miami land, formerly owned by the Federal Aviation
Administration, is worth $8 million, while Posner's land is worth
$15 million, state officials said.
   Roberts said Posner would proceed with plans to build the
condominiums with 1,500 units on the site. ``We're going full speed
ahead,'' he said.
   But Posner still needs approval from the state because two of
the five buildings would be built near the ocean.
</TEXT>
