<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1957EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Bonds-Fine     08-11 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds-Fine,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel to Pay $100,000 to State of Arkansas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has agreed to pay
a $100,000 fine to the state Securities Department even though the
government said it has no evidence the firm did anything wrong in
the state.
   The consent order stems from the possibility that Drexel's
Beverly Hills, Calif., junk bond department might have committed
improper trades in Arkansas from 1984 through 1986.
   Drexel agreed April 13 to pay $650 million and plead guilty to
six felonies to settle Securities and Exchange Commission fraud
charges stemming from the government's insider-trading crackdown.
   State Securities Commissioner Beverly Bassett said Drexel would
pay the $100,000 even though it hasn't had an office in Arkansas
for four or five years.
   ``The incentive here is to avoid us revoking or suspending their
license,'' the commissioner said. ``This will sort of hold that in
abeyance _ even if the felony convictions don't relate to
activities in Arkansas, because they're registered in the state and
we don't look kindly on licensees having felony convictions.''
   She said the size of the fine was based on the size of Arkansas
and estimates of the amount of activity Drexel had in the state.
She said most of Drexel's junk bonds were sold to pension funds,
institutional investors and savings and loans.
   She said she has no idea what, if any, fraudulent securities
actions had been committed by Drexel in Arkansas during the time
period. ``My guess is it's not likely to be a significant number,''
she said. ``But we don't know. We're totally in a vacuum.''
</TEXT>
