<FIRST>r f BC-AMRPlan     08-11 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AMR Plan,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMR Board Approves Share Purchase Plan Revision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of AMR Corp., parent of American
Airlines, strengthened the company's anti-takeover provisions
Friday even though the company said it was unaware of any imminent
takeover attempt.
   If any person or group buys 10 percent of more of AMR's
outstanding common shares, the company's share purchase plan would
entitle stockholders to buy additional shares at half price. The
original plan, adopted in 1986, called for the option to go in
effect after a 20 percent acquisition.
   Additionally, after a 10 percent acquisition, but before a 50
percent acquisition, the company's board of directors would be
entitled to exchange each share purchase right for one new share of
common stock.
   The share purchase rights plan was adopted originally to enable
stockholders to maximize the long-term value of their investments,
officials said.
   AMR spokesman Jim Brown said neither the orginal plan nor the
amendment is meant to block potential buyers from bidding for the
company.
</TEXT>
