<HEAD>Oil Futures Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude and heating oil futures slipped in
moderate trading Friday with little news to spur the market.
Gasoline finished mixed.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
closed 11 cents lower at $18.48 per 42-gallon barrel. Still, the
contract up 45 cents from last Friday's price of $18.03.
   Among refined products on the exchange, unleaded regular
gasoline for September delivery rose 0.3 cent to 51.46 cents a
gallon. The October contract rose 0.6 cent to 49.82 cents, while
contracts for later delivery declined.
   Heating oil futures also declined after leading the market
higher in recent days. The September contract lost 0.1 cent to
finish at 50.20 cents a gallon. October dropped 0.1 cent to 50.84
cents and other contracts had smaller declines.
   Analysts said the market turned in a dull performance, with no
fresh news to influence prices.
   ``The market did almost nothing,'' said Richard Redoglio, energy
broker for Merrill Lynch Energy Futures, ``There was some
profit-taking that reduced some of the gains that we made earlier
in the week but we shouldn't read too much into it.''
