<FIRST>u f AM-AutoPrices     08-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Prices,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM `Pre-Introductory' '90 Car Prices Up an Average 3.4 Percent over
'89</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. on Friday announced an
average ``pre-introductory'' price increase of 3.4 percent for its
1990 model cars over comparably equipped 1989 models, a smaller
rise than analysts have anticipated.
   The announcement does not reflect final retail prices, but gives
an indication of how much GM prices may change from 1989 levels.
Ford Motor Co. has projected a 4.8 percent increase and Chrysler
Corp. has not yet made a projection.
   The smaller-than-expected boost could be from GM trying to
de-escalate the incentive war that has been going on for most of
the year, said Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton in New
York, who said he has expected price increases to be around 5
percent for the 1990 model cars.
   By holding price increases lower than anticipated, automakers
may be able to justify offering smaller incentives, and save on
those costs, he said.
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan said the company was seeking to
partially recover increased material, labor, health care and other
costs. He said 0.9 percentage points of the increase could be
attributed to federal requirements for passive restraint systems in
1990 cars.
   GM plans to install driver-side air bags in 15 of its car lines,
or about 500,000 vehicles, during the 1990 model year. The rest of
the cars will have automatic seatbelts for drivers and front-seat
passengers.
   Thomas Wagner, general manager of Ford Motor Co.'s Ford
Division, said recently that he expected retail prices for 1990
cars to increase about 4.8 percent over 1989 prices. Half of that
increase was due to passive restraint systems, he said.
   Ford is expected to announce formally its 1990 prices in
mid-September.
</TEXT>
