<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-11 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Soars Despite Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar soared to its highest levels since
early summer in heavy worldwide trading Friday, boosted largely by
technical factors.
   Gold prices sank. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery fell $2.10 a troy ounce to close at
$365.20. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for
gold at $363.50 an ounce, down from $366 on Thursday.
   The dollar's rally was already under way overseas when the
government released economic data showing a 0.4 percent decline in
July wholesale prices and a higher-than-expected 0.9 percent jump
in retail sales during the same period.
   The figures suggested that inflation may be abating while
economic growth continues.
   Typically when wholesale prices decline, ``interest rates come
down and the dollar gets weaker,'' said Jack Barbanel, a senior
vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co.
   ``But investors felt reasonably comfortable that the Federal
Reserve would not change (interest) rates, and they were right,''
he said. There was no change Friday in the federal funds rate, the
interest rates banks charge each other for overnight loans.
   Concerted dollar-selling by the Federal Reserve and other major
central banks failed to halt the currency's climb, and that only
served to ``reinforce its strength,'' said Ronald Holzer, chief
dealer at Harris Trust and Savings Bank in Chicago.
   ``The way the market absorbed the dollars ... means intervention
will be ineffective in the short run,'' he said.
   In addition, the market was buoyed by Japanese investors' hearty
appetite for U.S. Treasury issues. The Japanese bought more 30-year
bonds than had been expected at this week's auction, and traders
think the trend could continue.
   Linda McLaughlin, a trader at Chemical New York Capital Markets
Group, said that with the upcoming redemptions of Japanese
government securities later this month, the Japanese are likely to
shift to higher-yielding U.S. securities.
   ``There will be a continued need for dollars'' to make those
purchases, she said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.05 yen close at 140.10 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 141.90 yen. In New York,
the dollar closed at 141.90 yen, up from 139.80 yen on Thursday.
   In London, the dollar spurted against the British pound. It cost
$1.5850 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6280 late Thursday. In
New York it cost $1.5820 to buy one pound, less expensive than
Thursday's $1.6188.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.9405 West German marks, up from 1.9055; 1.6755 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6395; 6.5555 French francs, up from 6.4415;
1,395.25 Italian lire, up from 1,372.00, and 1.1746 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1711.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.9390 West German marks, up from 1.8905; 1.6705 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6325; 6.5455 French francs, up from 6.3955;
2.1685 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1275; 1,388.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,356.75, and 1.1754 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1722.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $362.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $366.25. In Zurich, gold fell to
close at a bid $361.00 compared with $366.35 late Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.51 to close at a bid $365.55
an ounce.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market, where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.10 a troy ounce, compared
with $5.16 on Thursday. But on New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.192 a troy ounce from $5.163.
</TEXT>
