<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   08-11 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market yielded to a late round of
selling Friday, falling short for the second straight session in
its bid to reach a new high in the Dow Jones industrial average.
   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips, up more than 15 points in
early trading, was down 28.64 at 2,683.99 by the close.
   That left the average with a 30.54 gain for the week, but still
short of the closing peak of 2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 5 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
586 up, 934 down and 477 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 197.55 million
shares, against 198.66 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 237.78 million shares.
   After an abortive run to new highs Thursday, analysts said
buyers drew some fresh inspiration Friday morning from evidence
that inflationary pressures have eased significantly as the economy
has slowed.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods dropped 0.4 percent in July, posting its biggest
decline in three years. Advance estimates in the financial world
had called for the index to be unchanged or modestly higher.
   But interest rates, after an initial decline in the credit
markets, surged upward again, and stock traders lost their early
enthusiasm.
   Rates on long-term Treasury bills, which pushed below 8 percent
in the early going, climbed to the 8.12 percent-8.18 percent range
by late in the session.
   Brokers said word of a surprising robust 0.9 percent increase in
retail sales last month contributed to doubts that the Federal
Reserve would relax its credit policy further in the near future.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 2 at 115{; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down | at
39]; General Electric, down } at 57|; Philip Morris, down 3\ at
160, and Eastman Kodak, down 1} at 50.
   Berkshire Hathaway, the highest-priced issue in the NYSE list,
fell 25 to 8,075. The company reported lower operating earnings for
the second quarter.
   UAL climbed 5~ to 257, completing a week in which it soared 92{
points after the company attracted a takeover offer from investor
Marvin Davis of Los Angeles.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $26.99 billion, or 0.79
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.70 to 192.27.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 4.18 to 394.38, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down 3.51 at 344.74.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped 1.07 to 462.48. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 380.64, down 1.60.
</TEXT>
