<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-11 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copper Futures Surge on Threatened Strike in Peru</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices surged to a three-month high Friday on New
York's Commodity Exchange on panicky buying fueled by expectations
of a miner's strike beginning Monday in Peru, the world's
sixth-largest producer.
   The threatened strike is the latest addition to a long list of
supportive factors that may point toward a repeat of the dramatic
upward moves that occurred in late 1987 and late 1988.
   On other markets Friday, corn futures rose the daily limit;
sugar was sharply higher; energy futures fell; precious metals were
mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Copper futures settled 4.75 cents to 5 cents higher with August
at $1.1735 a pound, the highest settlement price for a nearby
contract since May 19.
   The threatened Peruvian strike triggered the move, but analysts
said the rally actually reflected the convergence of many
supportive factors.
   ``The copper market today was every commodity trader's dream:
the fundamentals and the technicals came together,'' said William
O'Neill, director of research for Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   Key fundamental factors, besides the situation in Peru, included:
   _a 36-day-old strike at the Highland Valley copper mine in
British Columbia;
   _frequent power outages in Chile, one of the world's largest
copper producers, due to a drought;
   _the prolonged shutdown of the Bougainville copper mine, a
target of frequent terrorist attacks, in Papua New Guinea;
   _severe financial problems in Zaire and potential labor problems
in Zambia, two African nations that are important copper producers.
   On the technical side, the market pierced tough resistance at
$1.14 a pound, bringing in successive waves of buying.
   With so many problems plaguing the industry, copper production
is running below consumption for the third straight year.
   Analysts said the rally could mark the beginning of a bull move
similar to those of 1987 and 1988, when tight supplies drove prices
to record highs.
   Most corn futures prices closed up the permitted daily limit of
10 cents a bushel Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade following a
government report projecting a lower-than-expected U.S. corn
harvest. Other grain and soybean futures also advanced.
   The USDA report, released Thursday afternoon, projected a corn
crop of 7.35 billion bushels compared with expectations of about
7.53 billion bushels.
   The government pegged this year's U.S. soybean production at
1.91 billion bushels compared with market estimates of about 1.95
billion, and estimated the spring wheat crop at 487 million bushels
compared with an expected 493 million.
   The corn numbers were considered more bullish than those for
wheat and soybeans. Soybean prices were held in check by
perceptions of a large South American soybean crop and by the
USDA's revision of its projected soybean stocks figure.
   Wheat settled { cent to 4\ cents higher with September at $3.97}
a bushel; corn was 5{ cents to 10 cents higher with September at
$2.34 a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4 cents higher with September
at $1.41{ a bushel; soybeans were 8{ cents to 16\ cents higher with
August at $6.15 a bushel.
   Sugar futures rose sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange, partly in anticipation of an expected large sugar
purchase by India and partly on bullish chart signals.
   Sugar contracts settled .33 cent to .57 cent higher with October
at 14.42 cents a pound.
   Crude and heating oil futures slipped while gasoline was mixed
in moderate trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, with
little news to spur prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 14 cents
lower with September at $18.48 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent
to .10 cent lower with September at 50.20 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .30 cent lower to .06 cent higher with September at
51.46 cents a gallon.
   News of a 0.4 percent drop in wholesale prices last month
triggered selling of gold futures on New York's Commodity Exchange.
Gold settled $2.10 to $2.80 lower with August at $365.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 2.9 cents to 3.1 cents higher with August at
$5.192 a troy ounce.
   Live cattle futures finished .35 cent lower to .10 cent higher
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange with August at 74.67 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .40 cent lower to .33 cent higher with
August at 85 cents a pound; hogs were unchanged to .60 cent higher
with August at 46.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .27
cent to .60 cent higher with August at 24.77 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
