<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 1827EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     08-11 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonds Finish Lower After Roller-Coaster Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished lower Friday after one of
the wildest sessions of the year, surging on encouraging inflation
news but plunging as traders decided the Federal Reserve was not
ready to loosen its credit policy.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond ended up with a loss of 1\ points,
or about $12.50 per $1,000 face amount. Earlier in the day, the
bond was up by about $15 for every $1,000 in face value.
   ``We used to get whipsaw days like this back in 1981 and 1982,
but you don't see reversals like this that often,'' said Elliott
Platt, fixed-income research director for Donaldson Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette Securities Corp.
   The 30-year bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction
from price, rose to 8.15 percent from 8.05 percent late Thursday.
At midday, the bond's yield had fallen to about 7.91 percent.
   Bond prices moved sharply higher early Friday after the Labor
Department reported that wholesale prices fell 0.4 percent in July.
Many analysts had been expecting a modest increase. The decline was
the biggest in three years.
   Analysts said the report suggested inflation was no problem and
encouraged speculation that the Federal Reserve would encourage
lower interest rates, a development that would boost prices of
fixed-income securities.
   But traders who were looking for immediate action by the central
bank were disappointed when the Fed stepped into the market at
midday and arranged short-term sales of securities, a procedure
that drains reserves from the monetary system and places upward
pressure on interest rates.
   ``The market wasn't expecting that, and it took the wind out of
the rally,'' said Kevin Flanagan, money market economist for Dean
Witter Reynolds.
   He said a news service report that quoted an unidentified Fed
staffer as saying the central bank wasn't going to ease its credit
policy soon further depressed the market, and the selling seemed to
feed on itself.
   ``Once a trend is set in motion, it has a snowball effect,''
Flanagan said.
   David Hale, chief economist for Kemper Financial Services in
Chicago, said as prices fell, traders took a second look at a
retail sales report also released Friday morning and found
surprising strength in the 0.9 percent gain for last month. He said
it suggested the Fed would face no immediate pressure to relax its
credit policy.
   The abrupt turnabout ``shows these markets have a speculative
quality to them,'' Hale said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term government issues lost between ] point and | point,
intermediate maturities fell by about ~ point and long-term issues
gave up as much as 1\ points, according to Telerate Inc., a
financial-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 7.47 to 1,182.12.
   In corporate trading, industrials dropped. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, fell 1.94 to 329.84.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3-16 point. The average yield to
maturity rose to 7.26 percent from 7.25 percent late Thursdday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, rose to 8.18
percent with the discount up 8 basis points to 7.92 percent. Yields
on six-month bills rose to 8.06 percent as the discount rose 10
basis points to 7.65 percent. Yields on one-year bills climbed to
8.16 percent as the discount rose 12 basis points to 7.60 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest rate banks charge each
other for overnight loans, was quoted at 8 15-16 percent, down from
9 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
