<FIRST>r f AM-MAIBasic     08-11 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MAI Basic,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Four Expects Loss Due to Failed Bid for Prime Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Computer maker MAI Basic Four said Friday
it expects to report a significant third-quarter loss, primarily
because of expenses from its failed bid to buy Prime Computer Inc.
   MAI Basic Four on Thursday scrapped the last remnant of that
attempt, its $525 million cash offer to buy Prime Computer's
minicomputer business. Prime, of Natick, Mass., agreed last week to
sell the whole company to a New York venture capital firm.
   MAI Basic Four, a Tustin-based manufacturer of mid-size business
computers, said its abandoned tender offer for Prime, along with a
downturn in business, had forced it to begin restructuring, a
process that began last week.
   The company said it expected its earnings report for the quarter
ending June 30 to show a writeoff of $13 million to $15 million for
the restructuring and $5 million to $6 million in operating losses.
   The company said a streamlining it is undertaking is expected to
reduce direct costs and expenses by $25 million to $30 million, and
predicted it would return to profitability by the first quarter of
fiscal 1990.
   New York investor Bennett S. LeBow, MAI Basic's controlling
shareholder, is still trying to purchase Prime's minicomputer unit
through an MAI affiliate, Brooke Partners. LeBow hopes to oust
Prime's directors by proposing an alternate slate of directors at
Prime's annual meeting on Aug. 24.
   On Aug. 4, Prime accepted an offer of $1.2 billion from J.H.
Whitney &amp; Co. MAI Basic Four had been pursuing a purchase of all or
part of Prime for nearly nine months. Its efforts recently had
focused on a bid for just the minicomputer unit, which represents
about one-third of Prime's revenue, for $525 million.
</TEXT>
