<FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     08-11 0848</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0887</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices, driven downward by new car
discounts and cheaper gasoline, fell 0.4 percent in July, their
biggest drop in three years, the Labor Department said.
   The Commerce Department also said Friday that retail sales
jumped 0.9 percent last month and that consumer spending in May and
June had not been as sluggish as previously thought.
   Analysts said the double dose of good economic news showed that
inflationary pressures were easing and that the economy was in no
danger of tumbling into a recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street flirted with an all-time high before
retreating as the nation's financial markets reacted to news that
inflation weakened and retail spending rose in July.
   Interest rates gyrated before finishing higher and the dollar
rose sharply in foreign exchange, while on Wall Street the Dow
Jones average of 30 key industrial stocks briefly topped but later
closed below the record high of 2,722.42 set Aug. 25, 1987.
   The Dow industrials finished down 28.64 points from Thursday, at
2,683.99.
   __
   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) _ Northwest Airlines has reached tentative
agreement on a long-term contract covering its 5,000 pilots.
   The contract announced Friday offers an immediate average 9.3
percent pay raise and 4 percent average pay increases in September
1990, 1991 and 1992. It also includes improvements in wage
equalization, job security and productivity, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of farmers who were denied drought
insurance will split an additional $5 million in compensation under
an out-of-court settlement.
   A federal court jury on Friday awarded $40 million to the
farmers from their insurance agent, Good Weather International
Corp., but the farmers agreed outside of court not to seek to
collect that amount.
   Instead, the farmers will collect $4.93 million and the Chubb
Group of insurance companies will collect $3.07 million. The total
of $8 million represents the limit of Good Weather's liability
insurance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Taro Nakayama said Americans are
to blame for friction over trade because they don't understand
Japan, speak its language or try hard enough to penetrate the
Japanese market.
   Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu said Friday he would visit
Washington next month to meet with President Bush and reaffirm
relations with the United States as the foundation of Japan's
foreign policy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has announced an average
``pre-introductory'' price increase of 3.4 percent for its 1990
model cars over comparably equipped 1989 models, a smaller rise
than analysts have anticipated.
   The announcement Friday does not reflect final retail prices,
but gives an indication of how much GM prices may change from 1989
levels. Ford Motor Co. has projected a 4.8 percent increase and
Chrysler Corp. has not yet made a projection.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines has stopped hiring new pilots,
saying it had enough for its rebuilding effort after the past
week's sudden surge in picket-line crossings.
   An Eastern spokesman said Friday the airline canceled training
classes next week for its newest recruits and also will stop
advertising for pilots. Eastern is reorganizing in bankruptcy court
after being hit by a crippling strike by its pilots, flight
attendants and Machinists unions on March 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential task force has indicated that
improved environmental safeguards are essential if oil exploration
is to be allowed in three controversial ocean sites off the
California and Florida coasts.
   But the task force Friday gave no indication in a progress
report on what it will recommend to the president at the end of the
year, and said it also has made no judgment ``on the validity of
conflicting claims about environmental and economic effects'' of
drilling in the three areas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the Supreme Court does not allow the
partial merger of Detroit's two daily newspapers, one will cease
publication and ``the communication of diverse viewpoints'' will be
lost, lawyers for the financially ailing Detroit Free Press said.
   In a brief filed Friday with the high court, lawyers for the
Free Press urged the justices to uphold former Attorney General
Edwin Meese's decision to allow that paper and its competitor, The
Detroit News, to form a joint operating agreement.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market yielded to a late round of selling Friday,
falling short for the second straight session in its bid to reach a
new high in the Dow Jones industrial average.
   Dow Jones' average, up more than 15 points in early trading, was
down 28.64 at 2,683.99 by the close. That left the average with a
30.54 gain for the week, but still short of the closing peak of
2,722.42 it reached on Aug. 25, 1987.
   The dollar soared to its highest levels since early summer in
heavy worldwide trading.
   Bond prices finished lower after one of the wildest sessions of
the year.
   Copper futures prices surged to a three-month high on New York's
Commodity Exchange; corn futures rose the daily limit; sugar was
sharply higher; energy futures fell; precious metals were mixed;
and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
