<SECOND>BC-Earns-HBJ,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts Slightly Smaller Loss in 2nd Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc., which publishes
books, sells insurance and operates theme parks, said Friday its
second-quarter loss narrowed slightly to $42.6 million from a loss
of $44.3 million a year earlier.
   Revenues for the quarter rose 5.3 percent to $434.4 million from
$412.4 million a year earlier.
   Publishing revenue rose 15.7 percent in the quarter to $221
million and insurance revenue rose 10.3 percent to $107.4 million,
but revenue from its theme parks fell 14.5 percent to $105.7
million.
   The company said its publishing results reflected some revenue
from textbook sales that are normally recorded in the third and
fourth quarters.
   Revenue from insurance operations benefitted from the inclusion
of results from 11 farm magazines previously reported with the
publishing group.
   Harcourt blamed the revenue decline at its six theme parks
partly on lost attendance at its central Florida theme parks which
faced competition from new attractions in the area.
   The company has put its theme parks up for sale in an effort to
reduce the debt it assumed two years ago when it undertook a
recapitalization that thwarted a takeover bid from British
publisher Robert Maxwell.
   For the first six months, Harcourt lost $158.7 million in
contrast to a loss of $79.6 million a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose 8.9 percent to $749.9 million from $689.1
million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
